WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.520
[Amit Varma]: If India was a person, she'd be in severe danger from COVID-19.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:12.000
[Amit Varma]: She's 73 years old.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.480
[Amit Varma]: She's got comorbidities.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:14.560
[Amit Varma]: Some organs have failed.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Some organs never worked.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Some parts of her body are at war with others.

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:19.680
[Amit Varma]: It's a mess.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.400
[Amit Varma]: If she was an old woman sitting down to make a sweater, she'd be knitting holes.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:28.960
[Amit Varma]: But of course, India is a country, not a person, so I won't take the analogy too far.

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:34.920
[Amit Varma]: As we hit the 73rd anniversary of our independence, it's worth looking back at this great nation

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:35.980
[Amit Varma]: of ours.

00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:37.320
[Amit Varma]: How did we get here?

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:38.560
[Amit Varma]: What did we do right?

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:39.800
[Amit Varma]: What did we do wrong?

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.360
[Amit Varma]: What is this we even?

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.320
[Amit Varma]: We take so much about our country for granted.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:50.520
[Amit Varma]: The poverty and injustice, the normalized excesses of our politics, our very existence.

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Let's step back and take a deeper look.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:58.760
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:02.840
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral science.

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:14.520
[Amit Varma]: This episode is a bit like an achievement unlocked moment, because from the time I started

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:18.520
[Amit Varma]: the show, I have wanted to have Pratap Bhanumata as a guest on the show.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:20.600
[Amit Varma]: We could never quite make it work so far.

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:26.440
[Amit Varma]: But here we are talking about the wide ranging subject of India over the last 73 years.

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:30.800
[Amit Varma]: People refer to Pratap as PBM, and I refer to myself as a PBM fanboy.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:36.240
[Amit Varma]: I regard him as a finest essayist in our country, so far above the rest that there isn't even

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:37.460
[Amit Varma]: a shortlist.

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:40.680
[Amit Varma]: This leads to one awkward moment for me every month.

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: During the online writing course that I teach, the art of clear writing, I teach the values

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.120
[Amit Varma]: of clarity and simplicity when writing for a mainstream newspaper.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:54.200
[Amit Varma]: I tell my students, make it easy for the reader to process what you are writing.

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Avoid long sentences, avoid words that are too big, and so on.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.620
[Amit Varma]: Then at some point in the month long course, they ask me, so who are the writers you like

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:03.960
[Amit Varma]: in the Indian media?

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And the first name I take, of course, is that of Pratap.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:09.160
[Amit Varma]: And then they all jump on me.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:15.200
[Amit Varma]: He uses long sentences, he uses big words, he even uses adverbs, look screenshot.

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:19.560
[Amit Varma]: At that point, I have to take a step back and go into explanations like, yes, but he's

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:23.560
[Amit Varma]: allowed to because he packs so much into so little.

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:29.480
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, one of the reasons it's so rewarding to read Pratap is that he can go so much deeper

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:33.480
[Amit Varma]: in an 800 word column than any other writer I can think of.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:37.680
[Amit Varma]: This demands that readers have a deeper engagement with the text.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:41.960
[Amit Varma]: So when you sit down to read Pratap, you're not skimming, you're diving in.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And that, to me, justifies the fact that the prose has a rhythm that I would otherwise

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:51.080
[Amit Varma]: say is not quite suited for mainstream newspapers.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:56.440
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, matters of style aside, Pratap is the most insightful commentator on India that

00:02:56.440 --> 00:02:57.840
[Amit Varma]: I have ever read.

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:02.120
[Amit Varma]: He has an acute sense of the political and cultural DNA of this country.

00:03:02.120 --> 00:03:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And I have never read anything by him that does not increase my understanding of India.

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:13.400
[Amit Varma]: That makes him the perfect guest, therefore, for this Independence Day special episode.

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to our conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.880
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.200
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:27.240
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen has been a labour of love for me.

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:32.400
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:33.920
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:39.120
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:43.160
[Amit Varma]: Although The Scene and the Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:45.840
[Amit Varma]: up to the insane engagement level of podcasts.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:51.080
[Amit Varma]: I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics of

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:56.960
[Amit Varma]: producing the show myself – scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:57.960
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:02.600
[Amit Varma]: So, well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:07.240
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this – for every episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:12.480
[Amit Varma]: enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel is worth.

