[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:28.400
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps, and at sceneunseen.in.

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:31.000
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.800
[Amit Varma]: Help keep this thing going – sceneunseen.in slash support.

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:39.520
[Amit Varma]: Pratap, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:45.080
[Guest]: It's a great privilege being here, and frankly, a little intimidating as well, but, you know,

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:46.920
[Guest]: look forward to learning from you.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:51.360
[Amit Varma]: No, hardly, it's far more intimidating for me, you know, I'll, I'll make a confession

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:56.960
[Amit Varma]: here that when I began this podcast, three years ago, I made a quick list of names of

00:04:56.960 --> 00:05:02.040
[Amit Varma]: people I would want on the show, and you were number one, so finally, achievement unlocked

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:03.040
[Guest]: for me.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:04.040
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:05.040
[Guest]: Your encouragement means a lot.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:06.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:12.240
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of start by sort of talking about your early life, like what I'd be really

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.800
[Amit Varma]: keen on like the Pratap Bhanu Mehta that of course, we've never met, but the Pratap Bhanu

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:19.800
[Amit Varma]: Mehta that I know is, of course, a public intellectual, I've read all of your columns

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:24.560
[Amit Varma]: and the impression one would get from that is that the moment you popped out in the world,

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:29.360
[Amit Varma]: you were reading political philosophy and, you know, speaking in, you know, long complex

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:34.200
[Amit Varma]: sentences, but tell me a little bit about what you sort of were as a kid, what your

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:39.280
[Amit Varma]: influences were, and how your sort of intellectual journey made you the sort of political scientist

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:40.280
[Amit Varma]: that you were.

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:41.280
[Guest]: Oh, gosh.

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:45.520
[Guest]: You know, there's that old joke, right, that the deepest influences are so deep that you

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.400
[Guest]: don't even realize their influences.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:50.160
[Guest]: So I'll probably get this narrative wrong.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:54.960
[Guest]: I mean, it is true that as a child, I think my reputation amongst teachers was that one

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:58.560
[Guest]: thing I was absolutely reluctant to do was any physical activity.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:02.640
[Guest]: So I would just sit in one place and sort of read a book or something.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:08.240
[Guest]: I think one way of organizing, you know, my thoughts to this question you've asked is

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:10.920
[Guest]: maybe just pick out three or four key moments.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:16.760
[Guest]: I mean, I am what is in our circles called an academic brat, which is grew up in an academic

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:17.760
[Guest]: family.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:22.880
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think all the insensitive arguments about politics, political theory,

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:26.820
[Guest]: political philosophy were sort of in our years from birth.

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:32.840
[Guest]: It was an interesting household, and in some senses, I think, even in my political views,

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:38.280
[Guest]: I think it's had quite a considerable influence, not in terms of specific beliefs.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:42.680
[Guest]: But as I've grown older, I've come to realize that I think politics is almost as much about

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:48.200
[Guest]: a kind of temperament that you cultivate and the kinds of virtues you value.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:53.320
[Guest]: I think most people in my family, particularly my grandfather, who was actually in politics,

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:59.000
[Guest]: started politics in Rajasthan for many years, but my father also and my mother had in full

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: measure.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
[Guest]: There was a interesting and easy kind of religiosity in the household.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
[Guest]: I mean, this joke in the household is there isn't a place of worship we don't like and

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.280
[Guest]: we don't visit.

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:16.320
[Guest]: But it combined that easy religiosity with also a deep kind of intellectualism about

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:17.560
[Guest]: it.

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:22.680
[Guest]: And in some senses, I think the question, the metaphysical question in some senses,

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:23.680
[Guest]: right?

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:24.680
[Guest]: What is the ground of being?

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:26.840
[Guest]: What is the nature of our consciousness?

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:31.040
[Guest]: That kind of hovered in the air in the household a lot, almost naturally.

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:36.200
[Guest]: I mean, apart from professional colleagues, apart from political scientists, there was

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:40.520
[Guest]: that sort of whole other kind of conversational idiom.

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:46.360
[Guest]: And the two things that I do think were important hindsight about that experience, I think one

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:54.320
[Guest]: was a very different view of what a religious life actually means and what it looks like.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:08:00.560
[Guest]: I think my grandfather's two greatest attributes, one that a religious life has to be utterly

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:08.060
[Guest]: free from vanity of any kind, and second, that the meaning of life in some senses has

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.640
[Guest]: to come from a purpose that is not instrumental.

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:14.840
[Guest]: And one of the interesting things I found about genuinely religious people, I think

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:18.840
[Guest]: in ways that you come across, is there is a kind of, I actually think in genuinely religious

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:24.440
[Guest]: people, there is a healthy skepticism about the world, which is to say that the lack of

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:30.480
[Guest]: vanity and detachment comes from, you know, the sense of, you might say, the transience

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:31.480
[Guest]: of that world.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:37.000
[Guest]: And that can be actually channelized into a kind of healthy distance and skepticism

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.000
[Guest]: as well.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.240
[Guest]: I mean, you might say mysticism and skepticism are kind of two sides of the same coin.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:49.280
[Guest]: But I think that sensibility, I mean, I don't want to put it in sort of philosophical propositions,

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:56.360
[Guest]: but I think that sensibility has remained, I think, quite powerful for me and defines

00:08:56.360 --> 00:08:59.360
[Guest]: the way in which I think I relate to religion.

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:01.680
[Guest]: And I think it's a sensibility that's increasingly vanishing.

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:07.360
[Guest]: I mean, frankly, even the kinds of religious speeches that we encountered were far more

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:08.920
[Guest]: ecumenical.

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:17.320
[Guest]: I think almost all of them subscribe to that dateline from Madhushala.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:19.760
[Guest]: So that sensibility, I think, has remained important.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:24.440
[Guest]: But it also, I think, convinced me that I think it's more a temperament, not so much

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:28.520
[Guest]: a kind of public philosophy, you want to sort of articulate it in propositional terms.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:32.160
[Guest]: It actually loses, in fact, it becomes it's very opposite, right?

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:37.120
[Guest]: Because the idea is to give everybody the space to find, you know, the law of their

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:38.880
[Guest]: own being as it were.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.120
[Guest]: And understand it in non-instrumental terms.

00:09:42.120 --> 00:09:48.400
[Guest]: So that was, I think, the first sort of, you know, formative moment in lasting influence.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:52.800
[Guest]: The second is a interesting political memory.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:59.200
[Guest]: And I know as we grow older, we sometimes exaggerate what we remember.

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:03.320
[Guest]: But this, I think, I can say with honesty that the emergency was a defining moment for

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:04.320
[Guest]: us as children.

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:06.280
[Guest]: I mean, I was about eight years old.

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:09.400
[Guest]: And the astonishing thing is we were living in Shimla at the time.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:16.520
[Guest]: And I think the three things that were very much in the air, which we even grasped as

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:19.280
[Guest]: children very profoundly, right?

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:24.360
[Guest]: One was the potential violation of civil liberties, the threats that, you know, my father's colleagues

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:28.080
[Guest]: were being arrested, the potential threat of him being arrested.

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:34.560
[Guest]: You know, there were sort of clandestine information papers being passed because there was a complete

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:38.640
[Guest]: blackout on news media, so, you know, this was like a cloak and dagger game, you know.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:43.120
[Guest]: These papers would arrive and you were supposed to tear them up, otherwise it'd be incriminating.

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:47.960
[Guest]: It I think was one moment which created a kind of instinctive anti-authoritarianism.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:50.360
[Guest]: Maybe I had this anarchist streak.

00:10:50.360 --> 00:10:54.560
[Guest]: In any case, an instinctive anti-authoritarianism.

00:10:54.560 --> 00:11:01.440
[Guest]: Probably a little bit of a distrust of the Congress party qua organization, if not so

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.760
[Guest]: much its stated ideology.

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:10.320
[Guest]: And I think the third thing, which had appeared in a small way in a state like Himachal, I

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:15.040
[Guest]: mean, you know, one doesn't associate these things with Himachal, was for the first time

00:11:15.040 --> 00:11:19.160
[Guest]: there was a kind of nativist movement in Himachal, Himachal for Himachalis, I mean, Himachal University

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:23.600
[Guest]: where my father was teaching, was a young university and had created an extraordinary

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:26.800
[Guest]: wealth of talent, actually, now that we look back.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:32.400
[Guest]: But you know, there was a movement saying, look, Himachal should be for Himachalis and

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:39.040
[Guest]: that in part prompted our move out of Himachal, you know, in a sense, back to Rajasthan.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:46.480
[Guest]: So I think that sort of anti-nativism, anti-authoritarianism, that instinctive, I think came from the emergency.

00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:52.000
[Guest]: The third moment, if I would say, I think was the departure to Oxford.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.280
[Guest]: So I finished my schooling in Rajasthan, in Jaipur, and it was a nice kind of idyllic

00:11:58.280 --> 00:11:59.280
[Guest]: existence, actually.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:02.560
[Guest]: I mean, I think, you know, Jaipur was a kind of manageable town.

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:07.800
[Guest]: The kind of freedom you can have when you can navigate the whole town on a bicycle and

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:13.400
[Guest]: not worry about safety or anything else is not a freedom we've experienced since.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:18.960
[Guest]: I left for Oxford right after high school, and I know people can have different experiences

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:26.240
[Guest]: in Oxford, but for political philosophy, Oxford between 1985 and 1988 was just an astonishing

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:27.240
[Guest]: place.

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:34.960
[Guest]: I mean, I was lucky to have two extraordinary tutors, one who's been a kind of abiding friend

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:39.800
[Guest]: almost throughout life, Alan Ryan, the other was John Gray.

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:45.400
[Guest]: But apart from that, I mean, you know, Oxford had Jerry Cohen, Derek Parfit, Amartya Sen,

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:49.920
[Guest]: Ronald Rorkin, Joseph Raz, and this is like, you know, one of those sort of one-in-a-century

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:52.400
[Guest]: moments for political theory.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:56.920
[Guest]: And it just reinforced in me, I think, the love of the subject that I had probably picked

00:12:56.920 --> 00:12:58.600
[Guest]: up as a child.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:02.160
[Guest]: My decision to go to graduate school was a very simple one, which is what kinds of books

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:03.160
[Guest]: do you want to read?

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:07.320
[Guest]: Frankly, there was no other kind of forethought to it.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:11.640
[Guest]: But more substantively, I think what Oxford did, which was, I think, interesting was,

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:18.000
[Guest]: you know, I think when I went to Oxford, the little of the intellectual milieu that I was

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.680
[Guest]: familiar with was by and large opposed to liberalism.

00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:28.600
[Guest]: I wouldn't say it's anti-liberal, but I think in Indian political discourse and political

00:13:28.600 --> 00:13:33.680
[Guest]: thought, there has always been this construction of liberalism as somehow being associated

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:38.120
[Guest]: with a selfish, possessive individualism, liberalism having no sense of community.

00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:41.240
[Guest]: You know, there's a standard range of criticisms, right?

00:13:41.240 --> 00:13:46.240
[Guest]: Liberalism really having no moral foundations other than self-interest.

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:54.560
[Guest]: And what I think Oxford did for me was revive a kind of interest in the deep moral foundations

00:13:54.560 --> 00:14:00.640
[Guest]: of liberalism, which I think continued when I went to do my doctoral work at Princeton.

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:02.920
[Guest]: Alan Ryan was an extraordinary teacher.

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:09.640
[Guest]: I mean, I think one of the amazing things he did was, as a teacher, was, you know, he

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:15.080
[Guest]: would always say that even reading is an ethical act in some ways, which is that it involves

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:18.960
[Guest]: a sense of fairness to other people's arguments.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:24.960
[Guest]: And the ability to get inside other people's arguments, particularly people whose views

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:25.960
[Guest]: you disagree with.

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:30.760
[Guest]: So, you know, if you're giving a lecture on Marx, or if you're giving a lecture on Hegel,

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:37.480
[Guest]: it should appear as if you were, you know, in a sense incarnating them, right?

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:38.920
[Guest]: And that's a minimal kind of fairness.

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:42.920
[Guest]: And I think that's very much part of a liberal sensibility in some ways, talking about kind

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:51.200
[Guest]: of temperament that, you know, I then went to Princeton and, through a series of accidents,

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:54.080
[Guest]: ended up doing a PhD on Adam Smith.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:57.920
[Guest]: That's kind of a quad journey from this kind of interest in liberalism and religion to

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:03.480
[Guest]: Adam Smith, Adam Smith in the Scottish Enlightenment, and particularly on Adam Smith's moral philosophy.

00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:08.000
[Guest]: And two things that struck me about Adam Smith at the time, which kind of drew me to him,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.200
[Guest]: was one, you know, now, of course, there's been a revival of Adam Smith and people take

00:15:12.200 --> 00:15:17.160
[Guest]: his moral philosophy very seriously, but in the 80s, frankly, beyond reading excerpts

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:24.360
[Guest]: from the Wealth of Nations, Adam Smith was not part of, as it were, the larger literature.

00:15:24.360 --> 00:15:28.560
[Guest]: And I was very struck by two things in Adam Smith's sensibility.

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:31.040
[Guest]: One, again, the same anti-authoritarianism.

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:36.640
[Guest]: I think people often forget that the Wealth of Nations is really also as much about protecting

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:40.480
[Guest]: the state from concentrations of power as anything else.

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:44.480
[Guest]: And the second was, I think, his attitude to history, you know, which has been nicely

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:52.400
[Guest]: described as skeptical Whigism, which is the belief in the possibility of progress, but

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:58.560
[Guest]: the deep sense that a lot of progress is a series of accidents, conjunctures, sometimes

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:02.440
[Guest]: bad people do good things, sometimes good people do bad things.

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:06.880
[Guest]: And I think the Scottish Enlightenment, both Hume and Smith, are absolutely wonderful at

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:07.880
[Guest]: this.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:12.960
[Guest]: So, you know, Smith, for example, in his attitude to capitalism, he doesn't have a single good

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.920
[Guest]: moral word to say about owners of capital.

00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:20.200
[Guest]: But nevertheless, he says, look, you know, there's certain good that comes from deploying

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:21.200
[Guest]: it.

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:25.640
[Guest]: Or, for example, his classic discussion of slavery in American democracy, right?

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:30.320
[Guest]: That his prediction that a republic would be the last to abolish slavery.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:37.360
[Guest]: So there was a kind of paradoxical historical sensibility, which seemed to me to be far

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:43.040
[Guest]: more defensible, I think, than a lot of, I think, approaches to history that try and

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:44.040
[Guest]: find the master key.

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest]: I mean, I like that intellectual effort, because sometimes saying it's a complicated can also

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.800
[Guest]: be an intellectual cop out, right?

00:16:49.800 --> 00:16:51.960
[Guest]: You just say there's lots of things.

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:59.120
[Guest]: But that kind of easy complexity, I think, that Smith had, I think, was hugely attractive.

00:16:59.120 --> 00:17:02.880
[Guest]: I think the anti-authoritarian instincts, again.

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:07.200
[Guest]: And I think it was at Princeton, although I did not end up working on this, but also

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:10.800
[Guest]: the much deeper engagement with modern liberalism, again.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:14.880
[Guest]: I think John Rawls's theory of justice was sort of our Bible.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.320
[Guest]: And I went through a complicated relationship with that book.

00:17:17.320 --> 00:17:23.080
[Guest]: I mean, I think at the time, partly because it was so dominant, you know, there was a

00:17:23.080 --> 00:17:27.840
[Guest]: kind of natural young person's instinct to rebel against the hegemony of Rawls.

00:17:27.840 --> 00:17:33.120
[Guest]: We would always joke, you know, write essays called not another paper on Rawls.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:38.320
[Guest]: But as I've grown older, I do think it's one of the most remarkable books ever written.

00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:42.640
[Guest]: I think there's a very austere dignity to that book.

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:43.640
[Guest]: And it's almost deceptive.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:48.280
[Guest]: I mean, almost nobody reads part three of the theory of justice, which is an astonishing

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:49.280
[Guest]: piece of moral psychology.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:52.720
[Guest]: I mean, you don't have to agree with the specific principles Rawls advances.

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:58.720
[Guest]: But I think as an answer to the fundamental question of political existence, which is

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:06.480
[Guest]: how can you reconcile social cooperation with a recognition of our basic freedom and equality,

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:10.840
[Guest]: I think it's probably the most interesting framework with which to think.

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:16.480
[Guest]: The final thing I'd just say in this journey and as a moment, I think, was another teacher

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:18.640
[Guest]: I encountered at Princeton, George Kateb.

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:20.800
[Guest]: I mean, Alan also had moved to Princeton.

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:24.560
[Guest]: So there was kind of that continuity from Oxford.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:27.680
[Guest]: And George Kateb was a remarkable figure in American political theory.

00:18:27.680 --> 00:18:32.440
[Guest]: He's not much known outside academic circles, but really one of the truly great teachers

00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:38.440
[Guest]: in American academia, very different from Alan's in the sense that much more combative

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:43.000
[Guest]: in his teaching style with very strong sort of views.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:48.480
[Guest]: But the one thing, you know, which was his life's work, I think, and I'm putting it in

00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:55.680
[Guest]: my words, I think he put it a lot more eloquently, was, I think hanging out with him nourished

00:18:55.680 --> 00:19:02.080
[Guest]: my instinctive rebelliousness against any kind of collective pronouns or forms of collective

00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:10.200
[Guest]: identity, where, you know, the very act of naming you in a particular collective identity

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:14.760
[Guest]: actually can be antithetical to your freedom, because it benchmarks you, right?

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:19.480
[Guest]: If somebody says, you know, are you a Hindu, are you Jewish, are you Muslim?

00:19:19.480 --> 00:19:20.480
[Guest]: What does that actually mean?

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:24.720
[Guest]: Who benchmarks the content of what it means to be that, right?

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:29.960
[Guest]: He also used to make, I think, the important point, which is in some ways obvious, but

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:39.440
[Guest]: not well recognized, is that when we get absorbed in a collective identity, right, the form

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:43.720
[Guest]: of living that we engage in also becomes a little bit vicarious.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:48.920
[Guest]: There's a thrill to it, you know, Sachin Tendulkar's achievement becomes my achievement, and frankly,

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:52.720
[Guest]: there is no thrill more unmatched than that, right?

00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:57.800
[Guest]: On the other hand, the fact of the matter is that it is his achievement, right?

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:04.200
[Guest]: And that vicariousness also produces a kind of moral blindness, and that's the moral blindness

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:11.000
[Guest]: that in a sense licenses all crimes in the name of collectivities in a way that you would

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:15.400
[Guest]: not sanction if they were done in the name of an individual, right?

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:19.720
[Guest]: And particularly, I think, I mean, while I understand the historical importance of nationalism,

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:25.720
[Guest]: which is something we can talk about, but the fact that nationalism exhibits both of

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:32.320
[Guest]: these traits, right, I think it can be antithetical to freedom in the sense that it benchmarks

00:20:32.320 --> 00:20:41.200
[Guest]: people and it unleashes a kind of violent vicariousness, which, you know, turns ordinary

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:47.720
[Guest]: people into, I think, let's say, less empathetic towards otherness.

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:53.560
[Guest]: So I think that's probably, you know, I think the broad intellectual journey, I think the

00:20:53.560 --> 00:21:01.080
[Guest]: last and final twist, I mean, talking about oneself is never hugely interesting, but is

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:08.040
[Guest]: we then, I mean, I was in the United States for almost 17 years, after Princeton, went

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:13.840
[Guest]: and taught at Harvard, and walked into that job, again, almost accidentally with the encouragement

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:14.840
[Guest]: of some professors.

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:19.400
[Guest]: And the idea was always to come back to India, and for two reasons, I mean, one, I had this

00:21:19.400 --> 00:21:25.120
[Guest]: big sense that the real stakes are actually in India, I mean, at that time, America was

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:27.560
[Guest]: characterized by a deep overlapping consensus.

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:35.120
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it's hard to imagine that world now in this polarized, and, you know,

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:39.480
[Guest]: if you're interested in the future of political theory, India was the place in some ways,

00:21:39.480 --> 00:21:40.480
[Guest]: right?

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:44.080
[Guest]: I mean, it was going to have exactly the role that 19th century Europe had, right?

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:47.200
[Guest]: The society of the future, all the big debates are happening.

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.440
[Guest]: So we came back.

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:57.120
[Guest]: And I think coming back, of course, also led me back to much deeper interest in Indian

00:21:57.120 --> 00:22:02.480
[Guest]: politics and Indian traditions, which is something I never formally studied while I was in the

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:03.480
[Guest]: United States.

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:07.480
[Guest]: I mean, I always thought my connection to India was way too personal for me, I didn't

00:22:07.480 --> 00:22:12.280
[Guest]: want to write on it as a kind of academic subject for the American Political Science

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:16.760
[Guest]: Association, and within those genres.

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:23.280
[Guest]: And the re-engagement with Indian political thought, I think, Ambedkar particularly was

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:28.000
[Guest]: a huge revelation, whom I had studied only cursorily before then.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.320
[Guest]: And I think we all still study only cursorily.

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:39.160
[Guest]: One because of his absolutely unblinkered view of Indian society in almost every aspect

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:40.160
[Guest]: of it.

00:22:40.160 --> 00:22:44.880
[Guest]: And really a kind of moral clarity of take no prisoners, which is astonishing.

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:51.960
[Guest]: But I think second, I think he did put his finger on, I think, the original sin of Indian

00:22:51.960 --> 00:22:54.320
[Guest]: civilization, which is caste.

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:56.880
[Guest]: And you don't have to agree with Ambedkar.

00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:05.280
[Guest]: But I think the fact that that legacy and history informs not just social conflicts,

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:09.720
[Guest]: but also, frankly, our insecurities about religion and metaphysics.

00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:13.360
[Guest]: You don't have to agree with his claim that, you know, Indian metaphysics of Indian thought

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:18.040
[Guest]: rises and falls with caste, and if you take away caste, there's nothing else.

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:24.600
[Guest]: But it's hard to deny the fact that we are so anxious about its status, has something

00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:28.320
[Guest]: to do with, you know, in some sense, with caste.

00:23:28.320 --> 00:23:34.400
[Guest]: And the second thing about Ambedkar is that he's the first and only thoroughgoing modern

00:23:34.400 --> 00:23:41.040
[Guest]: constitutionalist in the Indian tradition, who just says, look, we have to act as if

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:43.200
[Guest]: we are free and equal.

00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:44.760
[Guest]: You don't have to give arguments for this.

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:49.320
[Guest]: In fact, anybody who demands arguments for this is probably already playing mischief,

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:50.320
[Guest]: right?

00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:56.280
[Guest]: Who's talking the language of modern constitutionalism, he has none of Nehru's sentimentalism.

00:23:56.280 --> 00:24:01.960
[Guest]: He, I think, very clearly sees the limitations of this extraordinary nationalist project,

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:10.240
[Guest]: which at one level was trying to create the space for a Indian way of thinking, right?

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:12.320
[Guest]: But I think Ambedkar's question is very simple.

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:16.160
[Guest]: I mean, you know, what you need is liberty, equality, and fraternity, and everything else

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:18.480
[Guest]: follows from that.

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:23.480
[Guest]: But if you start at the identity end of the story, what is an Indian way of thinking,

00:24:23.480 --> 00:24:26.040
[Guest]: then you're down the path of self-destruction.

00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:29.960
[Guest]: So you know, I guess it's all of these elements, and I'm not sure these different elements

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:37.080
[Guest]: can be easily reconciled, but that's how at least I see kind of my journey, not well exemplified.

00:24:37.080 --> 00:24:41.440
[Guest]: I won't hold any of these people responsible for my failings, but at least those were the

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:43.320
[Guest]: deep moments of engagement.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:47.120
[Amit Varma]: I think Ketab and Ryan just heaved a sigh of relief that they won't be held responsible

00:24:47.120 --> 00:24:48.120
[Amit Varma]: by you.

00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:49.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's a lot to unpack here.

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And I was, so I'll kind of go through the different strands one by one.

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:57.640
[Amit Varma]: One I was, you know, struck by what you said about, you know, the role that religion played

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:02.480
[Amit Varma]: in your life in the sense that we often think of, you know, religion and rationality as

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:05.840
[Amit Varma]: two things which are completely apart from each other.

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:11.120
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, and you know, that a true religious person may have that sort

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:15.520
[Amit Varma]: of sense of distance from the material world that he can then be more dispassionate about

00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:19.460
[Amit Varma]: it and therefore more skeptical, which was fascinating for me.

00:25:19.460 --> 00:25:23.240
[Amit Varma]: So while I don't really want to, you know, get too much into the personal, but I'm kind

00:25:23.240 --> 00:25:29.640
[Amit Varma]: of fascinated by the role of sort of religiosity in sort of shaping the way you think, are

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:30.640
[Guest]: you a religious person?

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:32.360
[Guest]: I mean, the short answer is yes.

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:36.760
[Guest]: And I have no hesitation saying that the only reason I hesitated for a second is that, you

00:25:36.760 --> 00:25:40.880
[Guest]: know, Wittgenstein has this wonderful line that he once said that, you know, I was going

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:44.720
[Guest]: to write that I'm writing to the glory of God.

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:47.720
[Guest]: But a statement like that can be misunderstood.

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:53.120
[Guest]: And what he meant by that was not that there's a kind of vanity in saying, you know, I'm

00:25:53.120 --> 00:25:58.200
[Guest]: religious, or that, you know, you want to look good in the eyes of people who are not.

00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:04.720
[Guest]: I think it was the profound sense that he had that the conditions of making religion

00:26:04.720 --> 00:26:08.720
[Guest]: intelligible in a subjective way no longer exist.

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:15.800
[Guest]: So when somebody says, are you religious or are you X or Y?

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:21.600
[Guest]: One is actually not sure what set of expectations is being actually backed into that claim.

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:25.680
[Guest]: So that's the, and one of the problems, in a sense, I think challenges religion in some

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:26.680
[Guest]: ways.

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:30.840
[Guest]: And in that sense, I think, you know, it is in tension with the world, is that those conditions

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:33.960
[Guest]: of intelligibility exist even less and less.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:40.560
[Guest]: I mean, you are an imaginative kind of interlocutor, but you can imagine 25 other contexts in which

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:46.360
[Guest]: saying I'm religious might evoke associations that you yourself do not have about that term.

00:26:46.360 --> 00:26:50.320
[Guest]: And I think that also, in a sense, exemplified, I think, Kateb's point about sort of the act

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:56.080
[Guest]: of naming public identities in this way, that identities are best, you know, if they're

00:26:56.080 --> 00:27:00.600
[Guest]: kind of background facts about you, which is the ground on which you stand, and that

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:02.720
[Guest]: gives you a freedom to act.

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:06.920
[Guest]: But they become perversions if they become a kind of exhibitionist goal in some ways

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:07.920
[Guest]: that you have.

00:27:07.920 --> 00:27:08.920
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:13.560
[Amit Varma]: I was also kind of struck by the serendipitous nature of this conversation itself.

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:19.480
[Amit Varma]: Because in, you know, two of my recent episodes, I have sort of examined authors that you just

00:27:19.480 --> 00:27:24.240
[Amit Varma]: spoke about, I had an episode with Russ Roberts, where we spoke a lot about Adam Smith, particularly

00:27:24.240 --> 00:27:26.920
[Amit Varma]: a theory of moral sentiments.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:32.120
[Amit Varma]: And in my last episode with Karthik Muralidharan, we also discussed Rawls a little bit.

00:27:32.120 --> 00:27:38.160
[Amit Varma]: And I gave my contentious gyaan on why libertarianism can be derived from Rawls.

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:40.400
[Amit Varma]: But that's sort of a separate matter.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:46.040
[Amit Varma]: I was also, you know, very struck by your quoting Alan Ryan on how reading can be an

00:27:46.040 --> 00:27:47.320
[Amit Varma]: ethical act.

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:52.480
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that, you know, when you join the academia, for example, the one

00:27:52.480 --> 00:27:57.320
[Amit Varma]: thing that you're, of course, doing is that you are, you know, being introduced to frames

00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:58.720
[Amit Varma]: of looking at the world.

00:27:58.720 --> 00:28:02.280
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, as you kind of figure that out, and I think what happens when you

00:28:02.280 --> 00:28:08.120
[Amit Varma]: discover frames to look at the world is that every frame that sort of, you know, and different

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:11.320
[Amit Varma]: frames will seem complete in and of themselves.

00:28:11.320 --> 00:28:16.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, they are very seductive, because a very complicated world and the complicated

00:28:16.080 --> 00:28:22.160
[Amit Varma]: processes of history can be, you know, suddenly seem intelligible, and you're like, okay,

00:28:22.160 --> 00:28:26.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, this explains the world so beautifully, this is who I am, and then you define yourself

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:27.360
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:33.120
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that you haven't done that you haven't not just chosen sort of an ideological

00:28:33.120 --> 00:28:34.640
[Amit Varma]: collective like that.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:39.240
[Amit Varma]: But you've kind of remained open in the sense that it is therefore sort of hard to pin you

00:28:39.240 --> 00:28:44.400
[Amit Varma]: down and say that, oh, you know, PBM is this or that or, or whatever, you're examining

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:45.920
[Amit Varma]: everything critically.

00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:50.880
[Amit Varma]: And how difficult does that become within the world of academia, because surely, there

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:58.240
[Amit Varma]: are pressures that you see around you to conform to a particular ways of thinking.

00:28:58.240 --> 00:28:59.240
[Amit Varma]: That's part one.

00:28:59.240 --> 00:29:04.120
[Amit Varma]: And part two, then is that when you come back to India, I've noticed that a lot of the frames

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:08.280
[Amit Varma]: that you could carry with you to look at the world, for example, the frame of left and

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:13.200
[Amit Varma]: right in politics, don't really apply to India, and you have to then sort of discard bits

00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:18.000
[Amit Varma]: of that and start, you know, constructing your own frames, as it were, or figuring all

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:19.240
[Amit Varma]: that stuff out for yourself.

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:21.760
[Guest]: So what was that process like?

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:26.440
[Guest]: That's a fascinating question, actually, it says a lot about the state of academia.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:28.280
[Guest]: So I think two things, right?

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:34.480
[Guest]: One, as I say, I think as an intellectual enterprise, I think the search for parsimony

00:29:34.480 --> 00:29:37.200
[Guest]: and a master key is very worthy.

00:29:37.200 --> 00:29:41.200
[Guest]: In fact, you need space for people doing that, right.

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:46.000
[Guest]: And for that kind of grand theorizing in some ways, right, I mean, it really moves the horizons

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.240
[Guest]: of our thinking, right.

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:52.480
[Guest]: But I think it's important to remember that theory is not the world, in some ways.

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:57.080
[Guest]: I mean, I think that's something kind of and, you know, one of the most important things,

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:01.320
[Guest]: I think, again, coming back to Adam Smith, right, is that it's interesting, both in his

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:04.560
[Guest]: moral theory, but also in his theory of science.

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:08.440
[Guest]: The one thing that he recognized was the power of the imagination a lot more.

00:30:08.440 --> 00:30:11.800
[Guest]: In fact, he says, look, we are neither creatures of reason in some sense or fashion, we are

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:13.720
[Guest]: more driven by imagination.

00:30:13.720 --> 00:30:17.760
[Guest]: And imagination does have a way of kind of putting together contradictory things in a

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:20.920
[Guest]: way in which reason does not, right.

00:30:20.920 --> 00:30:28.200
[Guest]: So you know, in that sense, I think just being alive to the complexity of reality, that theory

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:36.720
[Guest]: is at most a lens, like every lens, the critical thing is under what conditions.

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:40.840
[Guest]: And reality is one of those things where, under what conditions, pretty much changes

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:41.840
[Guest]: instantly.

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:47.440
[Guest]: I mean, a philosopher once made this very nice distinction that, you know, when we are

00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:50.520
[Guest]: academics, we have to think in terms of other things being equal, right?

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:52.240
[Guest]: That's how economists think often, right?

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:54.480
[Guest]: All our models are other things being equal.

00:30:54.480 --> 00:30:57.680
[Guest]: When we are doing normative, pure normative theory in philosophy, that's where other things

00:30:57.680 --> 00:30:58.680
[Guest]: be equal, right?

00:30:58.680 --> 00:31:00.680
[Guest]: Here are the arguments.

00:31:00.680 --> 00:31:05.040
[Guest]: When you deal with reality, it's all things considered, in some ways.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:07.600
[Guest]: So I think that's, I think, one important element.

00:31:07.600 --> 00:31:13.280
[Guest]: I've always been struck by a line of Neil's words, you know, which was that the opposite

00:31:13.280 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: of truth is falsehood, but the opposite of deep truth is another deep truth.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.320
[Guest]: That there is something to, you know, I think that's it.

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:27.400
[Guest]: But the second thing I think which is important, and this is something I do think academics

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:35.080
[Guest]: sometimes underestimate, is that the world of politics is different from the world of

00:31:35.080 --> 00:31:36.080
[Guest]: academia.

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:42.040
[Guest]: And I think it'd be disastrous for the world if the world of politics was simply the world

00:31:42.040 --> 00:31:45.160
[Guest]: of a particular set of ideas writ large.

00:31:45.160 --> 00:31:50.360
[Guest]: I think politics begins, I think, in the fact of disagreement.

00:31:50.360 --> 00:31:55.480
[Guest]: Frankly, if we didn't disagree, we wouldn't actually need politics in a deep sense of

00:31:55.480 --> 00:31:56.840
[Guest]: the term, right?

00:31:56.840 --> 00:31:58.120
[Guest]: The disagreement can have many sources.

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:03.880
[Guest]: I mean, it can be in ideas, it can be reasoning, it can come from your positions, it can come

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:07.320
[Guest]: from who you are, right?

00:32:07.320 --> 00:32:14.320
[Guest]: And the task of politics, in a sense, is to recognize this plurality, I mean, which is

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:19.840
[Guest]: why when academics think that the purpose of politics is to, in a sense, enact a particular

00:32:19.840 --> 00:32:25.840
[Guest]: idea, whether it's Marxist on the one hand or libertarian, it's that moment where you

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:28.640
[Guest]: cease to be political, in some senses.

00:32:28.640 --> 00:32:32.640
[Guest]: I mean, it's as oxymoronic as you might say Christian politics might be.

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:38.000
[Guest]: I mean, you know the answer to the question before it's been asked.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:42.680
[Guest]: Politics also operates in the realm of legitimacy rather than the realm of truth, right?

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:48.840
[Guest]: Which is, you and I might disagree, I might be more centrist, you might be more libertarian.

00:32:48.840 --> 00:32:54.080
[Guest]: At the end of the day, the political job is, can we find a way of actually living together

00:32:54.080 --> 00:32:57.320
[Guest]: in a way in which both of us feel we have space?

00:32:57.320 --> 00:33:02.360
[Guest]: But also in some ways, right, our core sense of being is recognized, right?

00:33:02.360 --> 00:33:08.280
[Guest]: Now that's a very different problem from the intellectual problem of what is the truth.

00:33:08.280 --> 00:33:12.520
[Guest]: I mean, you might well be right, you know, in the way you reason.

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:17.800
[Guest]: I might well be right, but that is actually not the political problem.

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:27.600
[Guest]: And dismissing disagreement simply as a function of lesser reasoning, right, and that's very

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:31.880
[Guest]: tempting for academics to do, you know, where the answer to every disagreement is, if you

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:35.360
[Guest]: only thought enough, you would come to my point of view.

00:33:35.360 --> 00:33:41.080
[Guest]: That actually, I think, strikes me as just a misleading description of the human condition.

00:33:41.080 --> 00:33:47.040
[Guest]: Now, you mentioned kind of conformity and the pressure to conform, I think, in academia.

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:48.040
[Guest]: I'd say two things.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:49.040
[Guest]: Yes, there are.

00:33:49.040 --> 00:33:53.760
[Guest]: I mean, I think academics can also function like collective tribes.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:58.920
[Guest]: Often the pressure to conform is not what people think it is, which is, particularly

00:33:58.920 --> 00:34:02.160
[Guest]: in the social sciences and humanities, it's actually not political views, it's actually

00:34:02.160 --> 00:34:03.160
[Guest]: methodological views.

00:34:03.160 --> 00:34:10.840
[Guest]: I mean, you know, various departments like to reproduce their own sort of method of inquiry

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:11.840
[Guest]: in some ways, right?

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:16.680
[Guest]: And I think a lot of the kind of most pedantic and frustrating disputes in academia are actually

00:34:16.680 --> 00:34:20.920
[Guest]: over that institutional control, right?

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:25.960
[Guest]: But I think coming to more substantive things, I think, look, I think you obviously have

00:34:25.960 --> 00:34:30.440
[Guest]: to have some set of values and, you know, the joke about liberals that they can't take

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:35.400
[Guest]: their own side in an argument, I think, is a telling joke in some ways.

00:34:35.400 --> 00:34:39.560
[Guest]: I think that certainly applies when it comes to world views, and you have to be open to

00:34:39.560 --> 00:34:44.000
[Guest]: receptivity, but you have to have some baseline moral values, right?

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.400
[Guest]: Some things that allow you to draw a red line.

00:34:48.400 --> 00:34:54.600
[Guest]: Now when people speak of conformity in academia, I think, you know, you can at one level take

00:34:54.600 --> 00:34:59.240
[Guest]: the most egregious examples of woke politics.

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:02.760
[Guest]: And certainly there's a lot more of that these days.

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:10.040
[Guest]: But I think it is, one has to say, I think, a fact, and probably a progressive fact or

00:35:10.040 --> 00:35:18.760
[Guest]: productive fact, that almost all moral theories have to operate within a broad plateau of

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:23.960
[Guest]: freedom and egalitarianism, at least moral egalitarianism, right?

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:27.960
[Guest]: So often when people complain that there's conformity, and I think, you know, what they

00:35:27.960 --> 00:35:35.240
[Guest]: want to say is that there are certain kinds of hierarchical conceptions of our relations

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:40.720
[Guest]: to each other that are no longer considered socially acceptable, right?

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:44.640
[Guest]: So for example, I mean, you obviously can't defend racism and caste in the way you do,

00:35:44.640 --> 00:35:49.040
[Guest]: and often there's a passive aggressive way of re-articulating them in a kind of different

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:53.440
[Guest]: language, right, in which you can play victim, right?

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:59.600
[Guest]: So to the extent that there are certain core moral propositions of that kind, and those

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:05.440
[Guest]: have to be exhibited in the way in which you treat and respect people, those will be the

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:09.480
[Guest]: basis for, I would say, a certain kind of conformity, because those are the basic elements

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:11.320
[Guest]: of that social contract, right?

00:36:11.320 --> 00:36:16.440
[Guest]: That's what gives predictability, you know, so for example, freedom of expression, right?

00:36:16.440 --> 00:36:22.840
[Guest]: Ideally should just be that, that it's a core norm that all of us respect, and none of us

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:24.800
[Guest]: sort of, you know, violate.

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:30.520
[Guest]: Now often what happens with freedom of expression is all sides weaponize it, right, in the sense

00:36:30.520 --> 00:36:35.400
[Guest]: that it's a convenient tool when you want to use it for your side, it's inconvenient

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:39.040
[Guest]: when you want to extend the same courtesy in some senses to other people, right?

00:36:39.040 --> 00:36:43.560
[Guest]: So that kind of, I think, building off a little bit of a consensus, okay, what are these moral

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:45.560
[Guest]: baseline values, I think is important.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:51.040
[Guest]: I'll just give you one example, I think, which is illustrative of this.

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:56.760
[Guest]: So I've used this example often, but because it's so vivid, in this context, it might make

00:36:56.760 --> 00:36:57.760
[Guest]: sense.

00:36:57.760 --> 00:37:03.240
[Guest]: So, you know, I often used to get this criticism, and I'm sure you've heard it many times that

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:09.400
[Guest]: liberalism and libertarianism and all of these nice things that you guys talk about are basically

00:37:09.400 --> 00:37:11.800
[Guest]: foreign imports, right?

00:37:11.800 --> 00:37:16.600
[Guest]: These are ideologies born in the West, they might not have applicability in India.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:20.440
[Guest]: And I remember once having this conversation with a group of members of parliament from

00:37:20.440 --> 00:37:25.600
[Guest]: all across the political spectrum, and some very strident ones who, the context was private,

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:31.680
[Guest]: so they were having a no holds barred discussion, each had their own victim narratives.

00:37:31.680 --> 00:37:37.240
[Guest]: And in the course of that conversation, I just happened to ask them this question, I

00:37:37.240 --> 00:37:46.280
[Guest]: said, can all of you recount an instance where you resented something, because it had been

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:48.880
[Guest]: imposed on you without your consent?

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:52.800
[Guest]: It could be in a familial context, you know, your parents asked you to do things that you

00:37:52.800 --> 00:37:55.200
[Guest]: did not agree to doing.

00:37:55.200 --> 00:37:59.760
[Guest]: It could be in a political context, you were asked to conform to a law that you did not

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:02.200
[Guest]: agree with, right?

00:38:02.200 --> 00:38:05.240
[Guest]: And how did you react to that?

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:09.800
[Guest]: And most of us, well, sometimes we have to go along, but that sense of resentment is

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:11.160
[Guest]: quite powerful.

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:15.720
[Guest]: Often, in fact, some of them said we resent things just because we are being forced to

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:19.160
[Guest]: do it, even if we agree with that, right?

00:38:19.160 --> 00:38:25.800
[Guest]: And it struck me then that actually all that liberalism requires is an extending of that

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:29.360
[Guest]: courtesy to everybody else, right?

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:35.680
[Guest]: That very elemental experience that all of us have of feeling resentful if we are being

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:36.680
[Guest]: coerced.

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:40.320
[Guest]: If you could just extend that courtesy that maybe others are feeling that way as well.

00:38:40.320 --> 00:38:44.400
[Guest]: I said, that's all it takes to get liberalism off the ground, you're actually all liberals

00:38:44.400 --> 00:38:46.600
[Guest]: when it comes to yourself, right?

00:38:46.600 --> 00:38:48.940
[Guest]: You all want to claim those freedoms.

00:38:48.940 --> 00:38:53.680
[Guest]: Just extend that courtesy, extend that courtesy not just to other groups, but importantly,

00:38:53.680 --> 00:38:57.240
[Guest]: groups need to extend that courtesy to individuals within it, right?

00:38:57.240 --> 00:39:02.640
[Guest]: So groups will often say, minorities will often say, majorities will often say, please

00:39:02.640 --> 00:39:06.440
[Guest]: don't impose a particular set of norms on us, right?

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:11.600
[Guest]: Well, extend that same courtesy to individuals within that group, right?

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:16.440
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think you have to kind of link it back to a certain kind of moral

00:39:16.440 --> 00:39:17.440
[Guest]: psychology.

00:39:17.440 --> 00:39:21.720
[Guest]: And that was, I think, again, one of the interesting things about Adam Smith, that at the heart

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:25.960
[Guest]: of liberalism was a certain kind of moral psychology, right?

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:33.360
[Guest]: If you've ever experienced this elemental resentment, and you can extend the courtesy

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:38.880
[Guest]: of understanding that others might be feeling the same, you're on your way to being liberal.

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:43.320
[Guest]: And it's nonsense to say that the West always had it or we don't have it.

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:45.960
[Guest]: We just need to be a little bit more self conscious about it.

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:46.960
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating.

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And I have a big question, which I'd save for later in the podcast, but I'll bring it

00:39:50.400 --> 00:39:51.400
[Amit Varma]: up now.

00:39:51.400 --> 00:39:56.000
[Amit Varma]: But before that, a quick observation that you know, it often strikes me that all ideological

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:01.760
[Amit Varma]: differences really come down to differences about means, you know, the ends we can agree

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:07.060
[Amit Varma]: on, we all agree that, you know, nobody should be poor, that, you know, we should find ways

00:40:07.060 --> 00:40:12.040
[Amit Varma]: of doing something about the genetic lottery, and sort of equal opportunities for all, and

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:17.040
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah, we all kind of agree on that the disagreements are about means.

00:40:17.040 --> 00:40:21.120
[Amit Varma]: And what I would say, you know, everything that you just said, they use the word liberal,

00:40:21.120 --> 00:40:25.480
[Amit Varma]: one could just as well in modern times, because liberal means so many things to so many people

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:29.840
[Amit Varma]: use the word libertarian, because this is also sort of a spiel that I, you know, give

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:35.040
[Amit Varma]: my friends of all ideological persuasions that no matter what ideology you profess to

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:39.040
[Amit Varma]: believe in your personal life, you're libertarian, if you go out for a meal with a friend, you

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:43.760
[Amit Varma]: won't force her to, you know, eat what you're eating, you won't force her to pay, and so

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:45.880
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth, blah, blah, blah.

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:51.760
[Amit Varma]: But then, you know, what is sort of natural to us in our in the personal domain, that

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:54.160
[Amit Varma]: coercion is bad and consent is important.

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:58.400
[Amit Varma]: We suddenly forget about it when we abstract it out to a bigger domain.

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:01.080
[Amit Varma]: But this observation itself might be completely moot.

00:41:01.080 --> 00:41:08.960
[Amit Varma]: If my next question has any sort of sense to it, which is that what I have sort of been

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:12.680
[Amit Varma]: thinking about over the last few years, watching what's happening in the world around us, both

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:18.680
[Amit Varma]: in the US and in India, is that I've been wondering how much ideology is about ideas

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:24.840
[Amit Varma]: and how much it is about tribalism, for example, you mentioned that politics begins with disagreements.

00:41:24.840 --> 00:41:31.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, many of those disagreements might on the surface of it be about ideas, but to what

00:41:31.120 --> 00:41:37.240
[Amit Varma]: extent are those ideas, you know, not causes, but pretexts to sort of use a phrasing that

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:41.960
[Amit Varma]: you've used in one of your pieces in another different context, which I've picked it up

00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:42.960
[Amit Varma]: from there.

00:41:42.960 --> 00:41:47.720
[Amit Varma]: For example, I look at the US, and I see what Donald Trump has done to the Republican Party,

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:53.760
[Amit Varma]: where people who would call themselves conservative, five years ago, are, you know, have become

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:57.720
[Amit Varma]: anything but, they have completely been transformed by circumstance.

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:04.040
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in India, you know, one of our mutual friends, Suyash Rai, once said something

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:09.640
[Amit Varma]: very interesting to me after demonetization, we were both kind of cribbing about how it,

00:42:09.640 --> 00:42:12.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, the damage that it caused.

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:16.240
[Amit Varma]: And I hope you won't mind me quoting this private conversation, but he basically said

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:20.800
[Amit Varma]: ki yaar Amit mujhe communist se dar nahi lagta hai, mujhe classical liberal se dar lagta

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:21.800
[Amit Varma]: hai.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And what he meant by that was that so many people who call themselves classical liberal

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:30.280
[Amit Varma]: and said, oh, we supported Modi in 2014, for, you know, more free markets and all of that,

00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:36.360
[Amit Varma]: were completely forgetting the principles that they once professed allegiance to, and

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:40.640
[Amit Varma]: completely forgetting all of those principles now that they had chosen a tribe and what

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:45.200
[Amit Varma]: seems to happen, have happened with many people like that here, what seems to have happened

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:49.840
[Amit Varma]: with, you know, say, Republicans in the US, and really what seems to be happening with

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:56.040
[Amit Varma]: people across all stripes, is that I am more and more coming to the conclusion that ideology

00:42:56.040 --> 00:43:02.320
[Amit Varma]: is kind of contingent, which is why, you know, within academia, you'll have, you know, pressures

00:43:02.320 --> 00:43:07.080
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, becoming someone with a much more leftward tilt, and so on and so forth.

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:11.080
[Amit Varma]: And actually, deep down, it's something else, you're choosing a tribe to belong to, you're

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:15.680
[Amit Varma]: adopting that ideology, but you don't really give a damn about the principles like again,

00:43:15.680 --> 00:43:20.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, you said just now that you spoke about how liberals, you know, treat freedom

00:43:20.100 --> 00:43:24.520
[Amit Varma]: of speech is something contingent again, where, you know, they'll invoke it when it's, you

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:29.800
[Amit Varma]: know, for example, there are liberals in India who, who, you know, when the right wing uses

00:43:29.800 --> 00:43:34.480
[Amit Varma]: certain laws against him, like sedition or 295A or whatever, they'll say, oh, horrible

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:40.000
[Amit Varma]: laws, but they have no issues using 295A themselves when they want to, you know, for example,

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:44.880
[Amit Varma]: all the vicarious thrill that was there on Twitter and social media when Anup Goswami

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:50.800
[Amit Varma]: was sort of prosecuted recently for laws we should not exist, right, and which liberals

00:43:50.800 --> 00:43:52.440
[Amit Varma]: agree should not exist.

00:43:52.440 --> 00:43:57.220
[Amit Varma]: So my deeper sort of concern there is, and I'm sure you've thought about it is that to

00:43:57.220 --> 00:44:03.720
[Amit Varma]: what extent is ideology, therefore, contingent, and all of this is just a sham, you know,

00:44:03.720 --> 00:44:08.320
[Amit Varma]: and if that is the case, if at the heart of this is a kind of tribalism, which we choose

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.840
[Amit Varma]: to dress up in different ways, then you know, what is the point of this whole political

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:13.840
[Amit Varma]: project?

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:20.120
[Guest]: Wow, really big question, probably sort of meandering, meandering to it, I think, two

00:44:20.120 --> 00:44:22.120
[Guest]: or three different angles, right?

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:26.520
[Guest]: So one is, I think we have to be clear about the sense in which ideology matters, right?

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:31.880
[Guest]: I mean, so there's, there's a couple of technical meanings of the term ideology, where it just

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:33.800
[Guest]: doesn't refer to just ideas people have.

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:38.440
[Guest]: I mean, I do think there is, for example, I think some analytical power to Marx's conception

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:46.640
[Guest]: of ideology, right, where in a sense, what ideology does is it defines the horizons within

00:44:46.640 --> 00:44:47.880
[Guest]: which we think.

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:51.840
[Guest]: So in a capitalist order, you cannot think outside of the horizons of competition and

00:44:51.840 --> 00:44:53.880
[Guest]: private property, right?

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:58.480
[Guest]: And in that sense, I think there's a certain kind of power to that system that all differences

00:44:58.480 --> 00:45:05.880
[Guest]: apart, that's a core institution of the society that in some senses permeates, you know, everything's

00:45:05.880 --> 00:45:09.120
[Guest]: right or wrong is a different matter, but, you know, to that extent, I think many would

00:45:09.120 --> 00:45:10.760
[Guest]: argue ideology still matters.

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:15.560
[Guest]: In fact, ideology often matters precisely when it's not most clearly articulated.

00:45:15.560 --> 00:45:17.800
[Guest]: That's actually its power.

00:45:17.800 --> 00:45:23.520
[Guest]: But I think coming more directly to your question, I do think there is something about a social

00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:30.760
[Guest]: science vocabulary that has, I think, narrowed our horizons of politics, I think, immensely.

00:45:30.760 --> 00:45:34.400
[Guest]: And again, that's something that was quite remarkable about Smith, and, you know, if

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:37.920
[Guest]: you read David Hume's History of England, for example, right?

00:45:37.920 --> 00:45:43.720
[Guest]: We always used to set this exam question for students, that the key to a political thinker

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:47.360
[Guest]: is not his arguments or her arguments, the key to a political thinker is trying to figure

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:51.600
[Guest]: out what do they fear most, right?

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:58.360
[Guest]: And at that level, politics operates at a deeply psychological level, right?

00:45:58.360 --> 00:46:01.800
[Guest]: Those who fear anarchy, right?

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:05.320
[Guest]: And that's a fear about the world, that's not a fear about abstract ideas.

00:46:05.320 --> 00:46:11.240
[Guest]: Yes, in principle, we all want to be libertarian, or we all want to be actually, frankly, I

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:16.000
[Guest]: wouldn't mind an anarchist world where all authority was completely spontaneously generated,

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.000
[Guest]: right?

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.360
[Guest]: Yet, temperamentally, you fear that world, either because you think it's not possible

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:28.520
[Guest]: or because you think, in some senses, it'll put you in jeopardy in ways you can't imagine,

00:46:28.520 --> 00:46:29.680
[Guest]: right?

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:36.920
[Guest]: Those who fear, I mean, classically, right, the fear of equality has come from two sources.

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:43.600
[Guest]: It has either come from a fear of existing groups losing privilege, right?

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:47.680
[Guest]: That's been the sort of almost always the classical thing, we just don't ask these questions

00:46:47.680 --> 00:46:50.480
[Guest]: where we got our wealth from, right?

00:46:50.480 --> 00:46:54.360
[Guest]: Or secondly, I think, you know, particularly in the 19th century, the fear of equality

00:46:54.360 --> 00:46:56.240
[Guest]: was the fear of conformity, right?

00:46:56.240 --> 00:47:01.880
[Guest]: I mean, that's the fear that runs through Mill and Tocqueville, and so forth, that actually

00:47:01.880 --> 00:47:04.160
[Guest]: goes back to Plato in some ways, right?

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:12.240
[Guest]: That somehow, what particular interpretations of equality will do is license a kind of conformity,

00:47:12.240 --> 00:47:17.520
[Guest]: it will disable or disempower the individual, right?

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:22.240
[Guest]: Because equality will unleash the thought that one opinion is as good as any other.

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:28.320
[Guest]: And if one opinion is as good as any other, the paradoxical psychological thought it unleashes

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:35.840
[Guest]: is that I then take my cues from people who have the more numbers, right?

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:40.680
[Guest]: So a lot of actually politics is actually trying to figure out what those fears are

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:41.880
[Guest]: in a colonial context, right?

00:47:41.880 --> 00:47:46.720
[Guest]: I think Jawaharlal Nehru's poignant description, most people did not agree with Gandhi's ideas.

00:47:46.720 --> 00:47:51.480
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think there was ever a congressman who was a Gandhian in any deep sense.

00:47:51.480 --> 00:47:54.200
[Guest]: What he did tap into, right?

00:47:54.200 --> 00:48:00.200
[Guest]: Was in a sense, exposing that fear we had, and finding a vocabulary in which to express

00:48:00.200 --> 00:48:02.280
[Guest]: it and confront it, right?

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:05.040
[Guest]: I think you can see this on debates over secularism and religion, right?

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:09.000
[Guest]: I mean, I think a lot of our fears about religion in public sphere are frankly psychological.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:14.120
[Guest]: I mean, it's, you know, you just associate religion with the fact that if you actually

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:18.920
[Guest]: raise the stakes of politics, it's true that you might make better people, but it's also

00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:23.040
[Guest]: true that you could end up licensing worse evil.

00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:29.440
[Guest]: So I actually do think, and a lot of successful politicians, frankly, I think their big trait

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:34.840
[Guest]: is kind of instinctively grasping, or sometimes creating these fears in some ways, right?

00:48:34.840 --> 00:48:37.520
[Guest]: What do I need to make you afraid of?

00:48:37.520 --> 00:48:42.480
[Guest]: And if I can, you know, give an answer to that fear, right?

00:48:42.480 --> 00:48:43.720
[Guest]: So that's, I think, one thing.

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:46.480
[Guest]: You can even see it in debates in India, right?

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:52.320
[Guest]: I mean, I think, I'm sure one of the questions that, you know, you have thought about deeply,

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:56.360
[Guest]: you know, when we ask this question, why isn't the Indian state more liberal?

00:48:56.360 --> 00:49:00.520
[Guest]: Why haven't libertarian ideas taken hold?

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:02.840
[Guest]: Behind it often is not the cogency of the argument.

00:49:02.840 --> 00:49:09.360
[Guest]: Behind it often is the social experience of distrust, right?

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:10.360
[Guest]: Imagine 1947, right?

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:15.160
[Guest]: I mean, India has experienced a sort of century of low growth.

00:49:15.160 --> 00:49:17.160
[Guest]: There are no markets.

00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:22.400
[Guest]: The only forms of capital that you have actually experienced are usurous forms of capital,

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:23.400
[Guest]: right?

00:49:23.400 --> 00:49:27.880
[Guest]: That, you know, the money, the local money lender that exploits you.

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:33.720
[Guest]: What kind of imagination does that create about markets, right?

00:49:33.720 --> 00:49:36.320
[Guest]: And you're overcoming, and that's where experience does matter.

00:49:36.320 --> 00:49:39.560
[Guest]: I mean, I don't want to sort of fetishize experience.

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:45.880
[Guest]: And often it's very irritating when somebody says, look, my experience against your argument.

00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:50.920
[Guest]: I mean, you know, well, sometimes you can misread your own experience.

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:58.480
[Guest]: Nevertheless, I think experience is important because it does point us in the right direction,

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:01.200
[Guest]: which is, and I think those conversations are harder to have.

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:04.240
[Guest]: Frankly, the argumentative conversations are easier to have.

00:50:04.240 --> 00:50:08.040
[Guest]: Here are the three best arguments for the difference principle, or, you know, here are

00:50:08.040 --> 00:50:12.320
[Guest]: the three best arguments for why the price mechanism is a wonderful information aggregating

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:13.720
[Guest]: mechanism.

00:50:13.720 --> 00:50:18.720
[Guest]: It's harder to convince people who've actually never seen that work, right?

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:19.720
[Guest]: What does that mean?

00:50:19.720 --> 00:50:22.280
[Guest]: I mean, you know, who might benefit from this?

00:50:22.280 --> 00:50:26.480
[Guest]: And I think that, I think, is probably to me the core of politics, as Hobbes rightly

00:50:26.480 --> 00:50:30.920
[Guest]: said, you know, is support of the state was also, you know, fear and I were born twins.

00:50:30.920 --> 00:50:34.960
[Guest]: I mean, he literally made fear itself that category, right?

00:50:34.960 --> 00:50:43.440
[Guest]: But in all kinds of other ways, I think asking this question, what do people fear most?

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:49.400
[Guest]: I think is often an, it's an instructive question, even if it's not an easy question to answer.

00:50:49.400 --> 00:50:53.680
[Guest]: Because often those fears are unrecognized, even by the people who are actually exhibiting

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:57.600
[Guest]: them in, you know, in some ways.

00:50:57.600 --> 00:51:01.680
[Guest]: The second thing I'd say about politics, and again, going back to the category of the imagination

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:08.040
[Guest]: in some ways, right, you know, I frankly, I have to say, the political science is completely

00:51:08.040 --> 00:51:13.680
[Guest]: mystified by a very basic question of political science, what makes for credible leaders?

00:51:13.680 --> 00:51:21.840
[Guest]: I mean, the kinds of leaders people give their allegiance to sometimes in the face of incontrovertible

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:29.760
[Guest]: evidence that they are incompetent, you know, sort of boggles the mind.

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:31.720
[Guest]: Because in a sense, the reverse is the case.

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:37.480
[Guest]: I mean, I think, intellectuals are particularly, I think, prone to misrecognizing leaders,

00:51:37.480 --> 00:51:42.200
[Guest]: partly because we are good at reading arguments, we are not good at reading human nature, we

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:47.520
[Guest]: are not good at reading the protean-ness of people, in some ways, right?

00:51:47.520 --> 00:51:49.360
[Guest]: You know, which is why I think there is always this gap.

00:51:49.360 --> 00:51:51.760
[Guest]: I mean, I think it can be a good faith mistake.

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:54.920
[Guest]: Sometimes you think a particular leader or a particular political party might actually

00:51:54.920 --> 00:51:57.920
[Guest]: carry out your agenda.

00:51:57.920 --> 00:52:02.640
[Guest]: You're probably projecting, in some senses, your arguments, you know, onto them.

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:09.240
[Guest]: But in thinking about the elements of leadership, right, I think that point about vicariousness,

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:11.000
[Guest]: I think actually becomes important.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:16.720
[Guest]: There are some leaders who produce a kind of affect, you know, which makes people feel

00:52:16.720 --> 00:52:17.720
[Guest]: elevated.

00:52:17.720 --> 00:52:21.360
[Guest]: I mean, there's always this temptation to say, yes, I know he's committing a crime,

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:24.560
[Guest]: but at least it's a crime in the cause of greatness.

00:52:24.560 --> 00:52:28.000
[Guest]: There are other leaders who are completely truthful and matter-of-fact, but that's precisely

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.000
[Guest]: the point, which is, they are boring.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:33.840
[Guest]: I mean, by the way, the Scottish Enlightenment used to think boredom was as good an explanation

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:40.360
[Guest]: of social change as anything, often that, you know, something too familiar breeds contempt.

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:43.000
[Guest]: We need to be jostled out.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:49.720
[Guest]: So you know, politics, and then there's, of course, interests, which should never be discounted.

00:52:49.720 --> 00:52:55.520
[Guest]: Everybody wants to risk, even, under most circumstances.

00:52:55.520 --> 00:53:00.560
[Guest]: I think most of us are natural Pareto optimists, which is, show me an outcome which shows me,

00:53:00.560 --> 00:53:04.880
[Guest]: which guarantees me that I'll not be worse off here and now, right?

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:10.920
[Guest]: So politics, in a sense, works in the kind of deep crucible of, you know, the variety

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:11.920
[Guest]: of human nature.

00:53:11.920 --> 00:53:18.680
[Guest]: And I think one of the mistakes of contemporary social science is to reduce that expansive

00:53:18.680 --> 00:53:23.640
[Guest]: vocabulary of moral psychology, which the 18th century had, which some of our texts

00:53:23.640 --> 00:53:30.920
[Guest]: like the Mahabharata have, you know, pride, vanity, jealousy, envy, resentment, you know,

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:33.040
[Guest]: vicarious elevation.

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:37.320
[Guest]: These are all not things that can simply be captured by or reduced either to interest

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:40.000
[Guest]: or to ideas, you know, in some ways.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:44.600
[Guest]: I mean, sometimes you might change your mind just because your friend has done better on

00:53:44.600 --> 00:53:49.920
[Guest]: a particular idea, which you might have agreed with, I mean, you know, as a great line from

00:53:49.920 --> 00:53:56.040
[Guest]: Phoenix goes, you know, when a friend fails, it hurts, when he comes first, it hurts even

00:53:56.040 --> 00:53:57.040
[Guest]: more, right?

00:53:57.040 --> 00:54:02.280
[Guest]: So I think that moral psychology, I think, is much more central to politics than we think.

00:54:02.280 --> 00:54:05.640
[Guest]: And the tribalism that you're pointing out, I think, comes from that, right?

00:54:05.640 --> 00:54:07.160
[Guest]: I mean, what are these tribal instincts?

00:54:07.160 --> 00:54:12.640
[Guest]: I want my side to win or lose is more important, because the thrill of winning or losing is

00:54:12.640 --> 00:54:16.000
[Guest]: more important than what we will achieve.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:23.960
[Guest]: Often that tribalism is a cloaked form of making an argument that you could not make

00:54:23.960 --> 00:54:26.720
[Guest]: straightforwardly in moral terms.

00:54:26.720 --> 00:54:30.840
[Guest]: So when you think of ethnic nationalism, for example, right?

00:54:30.840 --> 00:54:32.680
[Guest]: Majorities-minority complexes, right?

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:37.520
[Guest]: A white majority thinking that it's going to lose, in a sense, its cultural supremacy.

00:54:37.520 --> 00:54:38.960
[Guest]: It's an unstated fear.

00:54:38.960 --> 00:54:41.000
[Guest]: You actually can't state it in moral terms.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:47.160
[Guest]: In that sense, we are operating within a, you know, a moral horizon of freedom and equality.

00:54:47.160 --> 00:54:51.840
[Guest]: And so you then kind of re-articulate it in roundabout ways, right?

00:54:51.840 --> 00:54:54.960
[Guest]: And behind a lot of that tribalism is exactly that fear.

00:54:54.960 --> 00:54:56.600
[Amit Varma]: So lots to unpack there again.

00:54:56.600 --> 00:55:01.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, before we, you know, get down to talking about India, and you know, how we fared in

00:55:01.720 --> 00:55:05.360
[Amit Varma]: the 73 years, which is, of course, the theme of this episode, a small observation and a

00:55:05.360 --> 00:55:07.880
[Amit Varma]: big observation, and I'll ask you to react to them.

00:55:07.880 --> 00:55:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And the small observation is really just sort of elaborating on what you said about horizons.

00:55:13.560 --> 00:55:17.320
[Amit Varma]: There's this great book by Arnold Kling called The Three Languages of Politics, where he

00:55:17.320 --> 00:55:22.140
[Amit Varma]: talks about how, you know, one of the reasons why we are so polarized is that we are always

00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:24.960
[Amit Varma]: talking past each other, never to each other.

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:28.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, we are talking past each other, because, you know, progressives, conservatives

00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:34.160
[Amit Varma]: and libertarians, as it were, will have a different set of horizons and first principles

00:55:34.160 --> 00:55:35.160
[Amit Varma]: that they look at.

00:55:35.160 --> 00:55:40.440
[Amit Varma]: Progressives will care about equality, conservatives about tradition, libertarians about freedom.

00:55:40.440 --> 00:55:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you can talk about exactly the same thing and argue for an hour and you're

00:55:44.880 --> 00:55:48.240
[Amit Varma]: not addressing each other at all, you're just talking into the air.

00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:51.580
[Amit Varma]: So that's a book I'd recommend for my listeners.

00:55:51.580 --> 00:55:57.240
[Amit Varma]: My other sort of observation from, you know, all of what you were saying is that it has

00:55:57.240 --> 00:56:03.440
[Amit Varma]: often seemed to me that the great battle in our civilization over the last 200-300 years

00:56:03.440 --> 00:56:08.760
[Amit Varma]: since the Enlightenment is that through our culture, we are figuring out ways to mitigate

00:56:08.760 --> 00:56:12.280
[Amit Varma]: our hardwiring, using nurture to sort of mitigate nature.

00:56:12.280 --> 00:56:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes, of course, a lot of the time, culture, nurture reinforces nature, but sometimes

00:56:17.240 --> 00:56:18.560
[Amit Varma]: it mitigates that.

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:23.480
[Amit Varma]: So for example, we are hardwired to think the world in zero-sum ways, because we are,

00:56:23.480 --> 00:56:27.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, our instincts were formed in times where we lived in small tribes, and there

00:56:27.160 --> 00:56:32.040
[Amit Varma]: was scarcity and whatever, we think the world in zero-sum ways, we think in tribal ways,

00:56:32.040 --> 00:56:37.160
[Amit Varma]: we have a distrust of the other to play to the sort of the theme of fear, which you were

00:56:37.160 --> 00:56:38.160
[Amit Varma]: talking about.

00:56:38.160 --> 00:56:42.680
[Amit Varma]: We admire strong leaders, which is why I think, you know, you were talking about a great mystery

00:56:42.680 --> 00:56:45.960
[Amit Varma]: of political science, what makes for a credible leader.

00:56:45.960 --> 00:56:49.960
[Amit Varma]: And I think one of the things we are hardwired to is look for macho posturing, look for that

00:56:49.960 --> 00:56:54.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of signaling, which is why, you know, a Trump or Modi will do well.

00:56:54.080 --> 00:56:58.340
[Amit Varma]: And yet, through our culture, we also, you know, we are that unique species, which can

00:56:58.340 --> 00:57:02.560
[Amit Varma]: actually fight its hardwiring, in a sense, through culture.

00:57:02.560 --> 00:57:04.640
[Amit Varma]: And that's a whole battle.

00:57:04.640 --> 00:57:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that because intellectuals are in a sort of an ivory tower, where they

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:16.020
[Amit Varma]: don't have to engage with the real world so much, and politicians do, I think politicians

00:57:16.020 --> 00:57:22.480
[Amit Varma]: get human nature much better, which is why politicians might often use ideology to cloak

00:57:22.480 --> 00:57:25.200
[Amit Varma]: the things they do or what they want to happen.

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:29.600
[Amit Varma]: But they get these primal fears, they know how to exploit them, it's instinctive, you

00:57:29.600 --> 00:57:33.400
[Amit Varma]: know, what you sort of spoke about, you know, experience versus argument.

00:57:33.400 --> 00:57:37.640
[Amit Varma]: So they have that experience of human nature, their incentives are tailored towards acknowledging

00:57:37.640 --> 00:57:42.680
[Amit Varma]: human nature, and, you know, catering for it, while, you know, intellectuals within

00:57:42.680 --> 00:57:46.720
[Amit Varma]: the academy, for example, might not have those same kind of incentives, their incentives

00:57:46.720 --> 00:57:51.800
[Amit Varma]: might be to signal something to their peers, and not to actually make an impact in the

00:57:51.800 --> 00:57:53.000
[Amit Varma]: real world.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it strikes me that any intellectual who really cares about her ideas, almost therefore,

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:07.040
[Amit Varma]: is forced to simultaneously become an activist, because otherwise, your ideas have no impact.

00:58:07.040 --> 00:58:11.080
[Amit Varma]: There's no question at the end of this, I'm just sort of thinking aloud, taking off from

00:58:11.080 --> 00:58:12.080
[Amit Varma]: what you said.

00:58:12.080 --> 00:58:16.400
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, how would you sort of kind of react to this?

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:18.920
[Guest]: No, you know, you said actually something quite important.

00:58:18.920 --> 00:58:22.320
[Guest]: And I want to just kind of build on that, particularly on the role of a politician.

00:58:22.320 --> 00:58:29.360
[Guest]: I mean, to me, politicians have two qualities, which often academics don't, or at least,

00:58:29.360 --> 00:58:34.200
[Guest]: at least academics who have been professionalized, I think, in the cultures of professionalization

00:58:34.200 --> 00:58:36.920
[Guest]: that we now produce in some ways, right?

00:58:36.920 --> 00:58:40.960
[Guest]: I think a lot of the great 19th century thinkers did in some ways, it's quite remarkable how

00:58:40.960 --> 00:58:47.960
[Guest]: much they did, I think, the two qualities are one, as you said, which is the difference

00:58:47.960 --> 00:58:56.080
[Guest]: between being good at arguments versus actually being able to observe human beings, read as

00:58:56.080 --> 00:59:00.640
[Guest]: it were the text of human life and actual live living beings, you know, to decipher

00:59:00.640 --> 00:59:04.600
[Guest]: what Kant called the crooked timber of humanity, right?

00:59:04.600 --> 00:59:05.600
[Guest]: So I think that's one.

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:09.680
[Guest]: The second thing, and I think this is the most important thing about politicians to

00:59:09.680 --> 00:59:20.360
[Guest]: me, and why they are absolutely indispensable, is that the politician's central job is a

00:59:20.360 --> 00:59:23.600
[Guest]: job of kind of social mediation.

00:59:23.600 --> 00:59:29.320
[Guest]: The example that you just read, you may like liberty more, I may like equality more, we

00:59:29.320 --> 00:59:31.880
[Guest]: may disagree about the means.

00:59:31.880 --> 00:59:37.720
[Guest]: Now somebody has to mediate between us, by mediate meaning, create enough structures

00:59:37.720 --> 00:59:45.000
[Guest]: of cooperation that, you know, we don't kill each other, but hopefully, despite these differences

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:48.560
[Guest]: can do collectively things together, right?

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:53.160
[Guest]: And often what people think of as a vice in politicians, which is they're swaying to public

00:59:53.160 --> 00:59:58.280
[Guest]: opinion, politicians can do U-turns quite easily.

00:59:58.280 --> 01:00:02.920
[Guest]: I think in terms of the vocation, that's exactly what you want them to do.

01:00:02.920 --> 01:00:07.840
[Guest]: I mean, I would be very afraid of a politician who just says it's my way or the highway.

01:00:07.840 --> 01:00:12.840
[Guest]: I mean, I want a politician to have some core baseline moral values, right?

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:17.080
[Guest]: And that's at a very kind of high level of constitutional abstraction, okay?

01:00:17.080 --> 01:00:20.520
[Guest]: I don't use violence, I don't use coercion.

01:00:20.520 --> 01:00:27.160
[Guest]: But beyond that, precisely because of the variousness of human nature, the variousness

01:00:27.160 --> 01:00:33.760
[Guest]: of our histories, and the differences in ideas, no society could function if you did not have

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:38.920
[Guest]: somebody doing this job of social mediation, which is why I am actually, I mean, I'm very,

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:45.320
[Guest]: very clear that if intellectuals enter politics, they should enter as politicians.

01:00:45.320 --> 01:00:50.440
[Guest]: I think the idea that, you know, you're carrying some special authority into that realm because

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:53.680
[Guest]: you're an intellectual, I think is just preposterous.

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:57.600
[Guest]: You're just another citizen, and you need to take on the role of a politician, not that

01:00:57.600 --> 01:00:58.600
[Guest]: of an intellectual.

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:03.680
[Guest]: The point you made about, I think, activism, I think, is an important one, I think, because

01:01:03.680 --> 01:01:09.600
[Guest]: that's often the form in which now, I think, intellectual engagement engages with the public

01:01:09.600 --> 01:01:10.600
[Guest]: sphere, right?

01:01:10.600 --> 01:01:19.760
[Guest]: And there also, I think, I would actually, I think, make a distinction, which is it is

01:01:19.760 --> 01:01:29.320
[Guest]: an intellectual's job, I think, to state how they see the world as clearly as it is, without

01:01:29.320 --> 01:01:32.800
[Guest]: fear or favor.

01:01:32.800 --> 01:01:38.880
[Guest]: And in a sense, that's their biggest social role, but they should offer it in the spirit

01:01:38.880 --> 01:01:45.400
[Guest]: that once you have made an argument in public, it is just one argument amongst any, I mean,

01:01:45.400 --> 01:01:50.880
[Guest]: I'm not a big fan of claiming authority in politics, because partly that militates against

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:54.400
[Guest]: the principle of equality, that militates against the idea of legitimacy.

01:01:54.400 --> 01:02:00.360
[Guest]: But yes, I mean, given that we have the luxury, somebody has given the time and, you know,

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:05.880
[Guest]: is paying us to read books, can we advance a few more arguments that, you know, other

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:09.960
[Guest]: people might not have had time to, but you should not do it with the expectation that

01:02:09.960 --> 01:02:10.960
[Guest]: you will win.

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.680
[Guest]: In fact, I think the best you can offer is a well-thought-out provocation.

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:16.680
[Guest]: Have you thought of this?

01:02:16.680 --> 01:02:22.760
[Guest]: You know, that way that Hindi song goes, I think that's the core job in the sense of

01:02:22.760 --> 01:02:24.080
[Guest]: an intellectual.

01:02:24.080 --> 01:02:27.520
[Guest]: I think when you become an activist, I think there are two kinds.

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:34.240
[Guest]: One where there are certain core values that I think intellectuals do want to defend, right?

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:38.480
[Guest]: So you might be an activist in the cause of free speech.

01:02:38.480 --> 01:02:45.040
[Guest]: You might be an academic constitutional lawyer, you know, who's working on environmental regulation

01:02:45.040 --> 01:02:49.000
[Guest]: or something.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:52.080
[Guest]: That kind of activism, I think, is compatible with the academic vocation.

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:56.600
[Guest]: I mean, it's just an extension of the good faith arguments you're making.

01:02:56.600 --> 01:03:04.320
[Guest]: What is, I think, not compatible with academic vocation is that you want your group or your

01:03:04.320 --> 01:03:05.760
[Guest]: side to win.

01:03:05.760 --> 01:03:11.040
[Guest]: And that group becomes, you know, it's the danger of any form of collective power.

01:03:11.040 --> 01:03:16.520
[Guest]: Again, as Adam Smith reminded us, it takes a life of its own, right?

01:03:16.520 --> 01:03:22.360
[Guest]: Just because I was with you in a trade union, just because I was with you on this particular

01:03:22.360 --> 01:03:31.720
[Guest]: cause, actually that solidarity then begins to trump, as it were, the commitment to truth.

01:03:31.720 --> 01:03:37.200
[Guest]: And to that extent, I think intellectuals do have to remain detached from collective

01:03:37.200 --> 01:03:38.400
[Guest]: organizational forms.

01:03:38.400 --> 01:03:43.640
[Guest]: I mean, I do think it's running a risk once they say, we've become part of this organization

01:03:43.640 --> 01:03:44.640
[Guest]: or that organization.

01:03:44.640 --> 01:03:49.960
[Guest]: Or, you know, it's even the danger, for example, in these collective letters that academics

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:53.800
[Guest]: write a lot, you know, where you have to get everybody on a common platform.

01:03:53.800 --> 01:04:00.160
[Guest]: But getting everybody on that common platform is exactly the kind of exercise or a loss

01:04:00.160 --> 01:04:03.080
[Guest]: of your independence, right?

01:04:03.080 --> 01:04:07.600
[Guest]: Now, in some cases, those are necessary, obviously, if your colleagues are being arrested on trumped

01:04:07.600 --> 01:04:12.840
[Guest]: up charges, maybe you do want to come together, some kind of solidarity.

01:04:12.840 --> 01:04:19.840
[Guest]: But I do think intellectuals need to be wary of all forms of power, including the power

01:04:19.840 --> 01:04:23.040
[Guest]: of intermediate collectivities of which they are part.

01:04:23.040 --> 01:04:28.240
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, when you said that, when I sort of phrased that thing about, you know, intellectuals,

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:31.520
[Amit Varma]: if they want their ideas to have an impact or force to be activists, I think I meant

01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:34.960
[Amit Varma]: activists in a really broad sense, which includes politics.

01:04:34.960 --> 01:04:40.760
[Amit Varma]: And the thought that strikes me there is that, that process of trying to engage with the

01:04:40.760 --> 01:04:45.920
[Amit Varma]: real world, even if you enter into that process with the intent of furthering your ideas,

01:04:45.920 --> 01:04:51.080
[Amit Varma]: and you're driven by your ideas, ultimately, you have to cater to interests and leave ideas

01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:56.360
[Amit Varma]: aside, which is why I often say that politics corrodes character, you once you are in politics,

01:04:56.360 --> 01:05:01.320
[Amit Varma]: you sort of the compromises you make along the way changes who you are, if you were that

01:05:01.320 --> 01:05:06.240
[Amit Varma]: person to begin with, because we are all so self delusional that, you know, who knows?

01:05:06.240 --> 01:05:08.120
[Amit Varma]: So So yeah, that's, that's sort of,

01:05:08.120 --> 01:05:10.080
[Guest]: Can I take issue with you slightly?

01:05:10.080 --> 01:05:11.680
[Guest]: I mean, I understand what you're saying.

01:05:11.680 --> 01:05:14.600
[Guest]: And I think I think as an empirical description of politics is right.

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:19.200
[Guest]: But but I think the very trait that you're describing also makes politics the toughest

01:05:19.200 --> 01:05:20.200
[Guest]: in the highest vocation.

01:05:20.200 --> 01:05:28.640
[Guest]: I mean, you know, the kind of politician who can both socially mediate, understand difference,

01:05:28.640 --> 01:05:34.960
[Guest]: understand the complexities of power, and yet retain something of a core compass, right,

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:41.720
[Guest]: that all of this mediation is in the service of, I mean, it's a very rare politician, right.

01:05:41.720 --> 01:05:48.920
[Guest]: But but that's what actually makes politics the most difficult job, I think of any, precisely

01:05:48.920 --> 01:05:54.400
[Guest]: because you, in a sense, have to, you know, keep both sides of that, right, that at one

01:05:54.400 --> 01:05:59.560
[Guest]: level, you are not a creature of your own will.

01:05:59.560 --> 01:06:03.200
[Guest]: That's part of your job is to respond to other people, right.

01:06:03.200 --> 01:06:07.480
[Guest]: And yet, you have to have a certain kind of moral compass and core, core with it.

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:09.920
[Guest]: So we need to encourage politicians of those kinds.

01:06:09.920 --> 01:06:14.160
[Guest]: I mean, I, I would hate to end this conversation with cynicism about politics, because if you

01:06:14.160 --> 01:06:19.560
[Guest]: think it's indispensable, I think we do need to ask, you know, what kinds of characters

01:06:19.560 --> 01:06:21.880
[Guest]: are better suited to the kinds of politics you want?

01:06:21.880 --> 01:06:25.240
[Amit Varma]: No, no, in fact, I love your description of politics.

01:06:25.240 --> 01:06:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's fairly obvious that politicians are necessary.

01:06:27.800 --> 01:06:30.360
[Amit Varma]: Like if they didn't exist, we would have to invent them.

01:06:30.360 --> 01:06:35.080
[Amit Varma]: Whereas, you know, it is contentious whether intellectuals are necessary.

01:06:35.080 --> 01:06:40.040
[Amit Varma]: But but can you name any politicians like that who you think retain their integrity

01:06:40.040 --> 01:06:44.000
[Amit Varma]: in the face of pressures which would force others to compromise?

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:49.640
[Guest]: Oh, it's, it's, you know, it's, it's a tough one.

01:06:49.640 --> 01:06:53.640
[Guest]: And the reason I'm hesitating, because I think it does say I think something contempt, something

01:06:53.640 --> 01:06:58.440
[Guest]: about the contemporary moment as well, right, which is, and how we, in a sense, judge people,

01:06:58.440 --> 01:06:59.440
[Guest]: right.

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:05.320
[Guest]: So one of the things that makes politics hard, I think, at this moment, and has probably

01:07:05.320 --> 01:07:14.440
[Guest]: also paved the way for a certain kind of populism, authoritarianism, fascism, is this kind of

01:07:14.440 --> 01:07:20.800
[Guest]: interesting asymmetry between truth and doubt, or credibility and lack of credibility.

01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:27.640
[Guest]: And what I mean by the asymmetry is this, which is, in order for cynicism to win, or

01:07:27.640 --> 01:07:34.080
[Guest]: in order for us to pull down somebody, all you need to do is find one flaw, right?

01:07:34.080 --> 01:07:35.800
[Guest]: Obama got Libya wrong, right?

01:07:35.800 --> 01:07:40.320
[Guest]: It's quite, it's kind of no brainer, easy to say that, right?

01:07:40.320 --> 01:07:43.520
[Guest]: Or maybe Obama got Syria wrong, right?

01:07:43.520 --> 01:07:50.400
[Guest]: So the standard by which you can actually show that the politician was not true to his

01:07:50.400 --> 01:07:52.840
[Guest]: core principles, it's a very low bar, right?

01:07:52.840 --> 01:07:56.680
[Guest]: I mean, we're all fallible human beings, right?

01:07:56.680 --> 01:08:03.800
[Guest]: And I think one of the peculiarities of this moment is that, on the one hand, almost any

01:08:03.800 --> 01:08:07.200
[Guest]: politician will be destroyed by that skepticism very easily.

01:08:07.200 --> 01:08:12.600
[Guest]: I mean, it just takes like, one instance, oh, you said this when you were 17 years old,

01:08:12.600 --> 01:08:13.960
[Guest]: there you go, right?

01:08:13.960 --> 01:08:16.880
[Guest]: For your detractors, that's enough, right?

01:08:16.880 --> 01:08:22.840
[Guest]: And I think it's that fact that has also paved the way for its complete opposite, where the

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:29.760
[Guest]: only way in which you can hold on to a belief in politician is complete blind faith, right?

01:08:29.760 --> 01:08:35.680
[Guest]: It's the flip side of the same coin, right, which is, you just go in and say, look, I'm

01:08:35.680 --> 01:08:38.600
[Guest]: going to be completely impervious to the facts here.

01:08:38.600 --> 01:08:42.760
[Guest]: You know, as one of my colleagues, Nilanjan Sarkar, has written, the politics of vishwas

01:08:42.760 --> 01:08:44.960
[Guest]: in some ways, right?

01:08:44.960 --> 01:08:50.800
[Guest]: I've given my faith to this person, come what may, they said red is blue, red is blue, they

01:08:50.800 --> 01:08:55.680
[Guest]: say two plus two equals five, and I think both of these are two sides of the same coin.

01:08:55.680 --> 01:09:01.960
[Guest]: So when we judge politicians, I think one of the things we have to, I think, be more

01:09:01.960 --> 01:09:08.960
[Guest]: conscious of that it is an art and it is something that requires the hard historical work of

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:09.960
[Guest]: political judgment.

01:09:09.960 --> 01:09:14.800
[Guest]: In a sense, a moral indictment of a politician is easy, right?

01:09:14.800 --> 01:09:18.480
[Guest]: It's the easiest route to moralize about.

01:09:18.480 --> 01:09:20.800
[Guest]: But what does political judgment mean?

01:09:20.800 --> 01:09:27.920
[Guest]: Which is, how would you rate their capacity to make decisions in the face of all this

01:09:27.920 --> 01:09:29.640
[Guest]: complexity?

01:09:29.640 --> 01:09:33.480
[Guest]: Not just complexity, but the fact that you actually don't know, I mean, you know, if

01:09:33.480 --> 01:09:39.600
[Guest]: Obama says I veer more leftward on healthcare, do I jeopardize the possibility of even passing

01:09:39.600 --> 01:09:41.560
[Guest]: a moderate package?

01:09:41.560 --> 01:09:46.920
[Guest]: How could anybody know what that possibility looks like, right?

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:53.160
[Guest]: So I don't think we have the kind of appropriate kind of conversation about what those standards

01:09:53.160 --> 01:09:54.760
[Guest]: of judgment should be.

01:09:54.760 --> 01:09:58.200
[Guest]: And which is why I was hesitating that, you know, I can think of any name, I can put out

01:09:58.200 --> 01:10:03.040
[Guest]: a name and, you know, I think it will be immediately clear to most people that, you know, here

01:10:03.040 --> 01:10:09.640
[Guest]: are the three flaws, here are the three big mistakes, you know, so and so, so made.

01:10:09.640 --> 01:10:15.560
[Guest]: And so in that sense, you know, I think it's coming to our debates, for example, about

01:10:15.560 --> 01:10:19.680
[Guest]: Nehru, for example, about Modi, for example.

01:10:19.680 --> 01:10:24.200
[Guest]: Of course, Nehru had deep flaws, I mean, you know, you and I can recount lots and lots

01:10:24.200 --> 01:10:28.520
[Guest]: of political instances, sometimes even constitutional instances.

01:10:28.520 --> 01:10:36.520
[Guest]: But is the life judged as a whole, right, where the sense is that, despite these mistakes,

01:10:36.520 --> 01:10:42.360
[Guest]: the movement is in a sense towards a particular constitutional and democratic sensibility.

01:10:42.360 --> 01:10:47.480
[Guest]: You know, I think he's probably done as good as any democratic statesman has in some senses

01:10:47.480 --> 01:10:49.120
[Guest]: done.

01:10:49.120 --> 01:10:50.880
[Guest]: You can think of Roosevelt.

01:10:50.880 --> 01:10:56.080
[Guest]: At one level, it's very easy to indict Roosevelt, I mean, his entire New Deal was founded on

01:10:56.080 --> 01:11:01.540
[Guest]: a very sordid compromise with the racism of Southern Democrats.

01:11:01.540 --> 01:11:05.640
[Guest]: You know, he left that structure of racism in the South intact.

01:11:05.640 --> 01:11:08.700
[Guest]: But what's the counterfactual here, right?

01:11:08.700 --> 01:11:12.600
[Guest]: If he had pushed too hard on that, would anything have been possible at all?

01:11:12.600 --> 01:11:16.400
[Guest]: So I think we need a much more nuanced historical conversation.

01:11:16.400 --> 01:11:21.160
[Guest]: I mean, you know, we probably need a few historians in the room to work it out, you know, come

01:11:21.160 --> 01:11:22.560
[Guest]: to fair judgment.

01:11:22.560 --> 01:11:25.000
[Guest]: So what might be interesting politicians to look for?

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:31.960
[Amit Varma]: No, you know, I didn't mean my comment on sort of politicians not being true to an ideology

01:11:31.960 --> 01:11:33.640
[Amit Varma]: as an indictment of any sort.

01:11:33.640 --> 01:11:38.160
[Amit Varma]: I totally understand, you know, the imperatives of politics and the importance of politics

01:11:38.160 --> 01:11:39.960
[Amit Varma]: and the role that great politicians have played.

01:11:39.960 --> 01:11:45.040
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the point you made about Nehru is well taken that people contain multitudes.

01:11:45.040 --> 01:11:51.080
[Amit Varma]: And in our modern times, sadly, we, you know, try to look for simplistic binaries to, you

01:11:51.080 --> 01:11:54.280
[Amit Varma]: know, discuss everything with and those simply don't work.

