01:13:52.760 --> 01:13:58.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, let's what has always kind of fascinated me, you know, we look back at history with

01:13:58.720 --> 01:14:03.600
[Amit Varma]: the hindsight bias and we think that okay, this is what India is it was inevitable that

01:14:03.600 --> 01:14:07.160
[Amit Varma]: we would turn out like this that we would be this kind of democracy and we'd have this

01:14:07.160 --> 01:14:10.160
[Amit Varma]: kind of constitution.

01:14:10.160 --> 01:14:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's something that we need to keep revisiting because as you've yourself

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:20.960
[Amit Varma]: pointed out, very often, and you know, everything is so contingent, you have a district chain

01:14:20.960 --> 01:14:27.560
[Amit Varma]: of contingent events happening and then suddenly, you know, here we are and it all seems inevitable

01:14:27.560 --> 01:14:29.040
[Amit Varma]: in hindsight.

01:14:29.040 --> 01:14:34.960
[Amit Varma]: What I'd like to talk a bit about is, you know, the founding idea of India, like one

01:14:34.960 --> 01:14:41.280
[Amit Varma]: of the sort of themes that I've explored over the last year and a half or so, and I've asked

01:14:41.280 --> 01:14:46.640
[Amit Varma]: this question to many guests, and I'd be interested in knowing what your answer would be, is that

01:14:46.640 --> 01:14:53.120
[Amit Varma]: at some level, it seems to me that our constitution is a relatively liberal constitution, I say

01:14:53.120 --> 01:14:57.240
[Amit Varma]: relatively because obviously, it's not nearly as liberal as I would like it to be.

01:14:57.240 --> 01:15:04.120
[Amit Varma]: In the classical sense, but it's a relatively liberal constitution, put together by an unelected

01:15:04.120 --> 01:15:09.360
[Amit Varma]: liberal elite, and imposed upon an illiberal country.

01:15:09.360 --> 01:15:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, one, there is a dilemma of whether such an imposition can itself be

01:15:15.840 --> 01:15:19.200
[Amit Varma]: called liberal in any way, if it is an imposition.

01:15:19.200 --> 01:15:23.680
[Amit Varma]: And the other thought being, I mean, the couple of other parallel thoughts that then come

01:15:23.680 --> 01:15:28.520
[Amit Varma]: up is that in today's moment, has politics finally caught up with society, in the sense

01:15:28.520 --> 01:15:34.440
[Amit Varma]: that our politics is finally reflecting the preferences of a majority of the people or

01:15:34.440 --> 01:15:37.480
[Amit Varma]: what the culture really is like?

01:15:37.480 --> 01:15:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, broadly, what are your sort of thoughts?

01:15:41.440 --> 01:15:46.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, taking off from that, is it therefore, a liberal failure to not create

01:15:46.320 --> 01:15:47.720
[Amit Varma]: a liberal culture?

01:15:47.720 --> 01:15:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Because what often, you know, one of my favorite quotes, if I make merchandise for the show,

01:15:52.880 --> 01:15:56.360
[Amit Varma]: I'll probably make a t shirt with that quote is by Andrew Breitbart, where he says, politics

01:15:56.360 --> 01:15:58.080
[Unknown]: is downstream of culture.

01:15:58.080 --> 01:16:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And I think this is something that without, you know, making a value judgment on whether

01:16:02.880 --> 01:16:06.480
[Amit Varma]: the conservatives are right, or the liberal elites are right, or whatever, forget the

01:16:06.480 --> 01:16:11.640
[Amit Varma]: value judgment, but just, you know, should a society have a constitution that doesn't

01:16:11.640 --> 01:16:13.320
[Amit Varma]: reflect what it is about?

01:16:13.320 --> 01:16:15.480
[Amit Varma]: And is that the case to begin with?

01:16:15.480 --> 01:16:16.920
[Guest]: What are your thoughts on all these?

01:16:16.920 --> 01:16:22.280
[Guest]: Actually, the Andrew Breitbart's thought, actually, the RSS had grasped this way before.

01:16:22.280 --> 01:16:24.400
[Guest]: That's one thing they're right about, actually.

01:16:24.400 --> 01:16:30.520
[Guest]: So I mean, I'm tempted to say, how many hours do we have to answer this question, but it

01:16:30.520 --> 01:16:32.320
[Guest]: has one shot at it.

01:16:32.320 --> 01:16:37.320
[Guest]: And to answer it, if you allow me, let me broaden the frame a little bit, because one

01:16:37.320 --> 01:16:42.240
[Guest]: of the, I think, frustrating things about thinking about India is, and this is something

01:16:42.240 --> 01:16:45.400
[Guest]: we shared with the United States, you know, we often think we are sui generis, I mean,

01:16:45.400 --> 01:16:50.960
[Guest]: you know, there's a particular distinctive Indian destiny that comes into it.

01:16:50.960 --> 01:16:55.160
[Guest]: But I think a little bit of comparative perspective is, I think, very important to answering your

01:16:55.160 --> 01:16:56.880
[Guest]: question, right?

01:16:56.880 --> 01:17:00.400
[Guest]: And the way I put it in this way, which is, it depends how you tell the story of this

01:17:00.400 --> 01:17:02.400
[Guest]: fine founding moment.

01:17:02.400 --> 01:17:06.800
[Guest]: So I'd like to tell the story two ways, right?

01:17:06.800 --> 01:17:16.400
[Guest]: One, look, we often forget that it is indeed very rare for constitutionalism to succeed.

01:17:16.400 --> 01:17:21.800
[Guest]: 80 to 90% of constitutions that have been created since the 18th, 19th century actually

01:17:21.800 --> 01:17:23.000
[Guest]: collapse very frequently.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:29.720
[Guest]: I mean, we forget France went through 130, 140 odd years, so many different republics

01:17:29.720 --> 01:17:34.000
[Guest]: before it's stabilized, maybe still not stabilized, right?

01:17:34.000 --> 01:17:41.200
[Guest]: So in that sense, I would not, I think, underestimate or be entirely cynical about that founding

01:17:41.200 --> 01:17:42.200
[Guest]: moment.

01:17:42.200 --> 01:17:47.840
[Guest]: And in that comparative perspective, it actually looks, doesn't look half bad as at least providing

01:17:47.840 --> 01:17:51.840
[Guest]: a modicum of hope to proceed forward.

01:17:51.840 --> 01:17:54.840
[Guest]: The second thing, and this is where I think the comparative perspective is, I think, the

01:17:54.840 --> 01:18:05.080
[Guest]: most helpful, is let us ask the question, what are the sources of illiberalism that

01:18:05.080 --> 01:18:06.960
[Guest]: jeopardize this constitutionalism?

01:18:06.960 --> 01:18:08.680
[Guest]: I'll come about its legitimacy later.

01:18:08.680 --> 01:18:14.320
[Guest]: I mean, whether it was passed by an unelected assembly or so forth.

01:18:14.320 --> 01:18:19.640
[Guest]: And let me be a devil's advocate for a minute and say that, actually, I don't think India

01:18:19.640 --> 01:18:20.640
[Guest]: is unique.

01:18:20.640 --> 01:18:26.320
[Guest]: I don't think this narrative that the West was uniquely fitted to be liberal by the middle

01:18:26.320 --> 01:18:31.280
[Guest]: of the 20th century, India is a traditional conservative society and not liberal.

01:18:31.280 --> 01:18:38.240
[Guest]: I actually don't buy that narrative, to be very honest, and I don't buy it for two reasons.

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:47.560
[Guest]: One, the biggest source of challenge for liberalism, to be honest, globally, has not been the abstract

01:18:47.560 --> 01:18:51.640
[Guest]: debates over freedom of expression, liberties, and so forth.

01:18:51.640 --> 01:18:53.400
[Guest]: Those are incrementally advanced.

01:18:53.400 --> 01:18:59.600
[Guest]: I mean, it's not clear that late 19th century England was any more liberal than in some

01:18:59.600 --> 01:19:00.600
[Guest]: senses we are.

01:19:00.600 --> 01:19:06.640
[Guest]: I mean, you still had to kind of sign the Confession Act for various things, right?

01:19:06.640 --> 01:19:11.280
[Guest]: The real challenge to liberalism has been from nationalism.

01:19:11.280 --> 01:19:15.520
[Guest]: And it's a very paradoxical challenge because at one level, the nation state is the political

01:19:15.520 --> 01:19:20.760
[Guest]: form in which modern constitutionalism flourishes, right?

01:19:20.760 --> 01:19:26.320
[Guest]: But the modern nation state requires a theory of membership.

01:19:26.320 --> 01:19:32.040
[Guest]: Who belongs to this political community which we are trying to be liberal?

01:19:32.040 --> 01:19:38.600
[Guest]: And the disquieting answer is that absolutely everywhere in the world, there is almost no

01:19:38.600 --> 01:19:47.680
[Guest]: exception to this, has the answer to that question not been accompanied by serious forms

01:19:47.680 --> 01:19:51.680
[Guest]: of exclusion and violence, right?

01:19:51.680 --> 01:19:57.320
[Guest]: Most European nation states that we think of it now have kind of relatively homogenized

01:19:57.320 --> 01:19:58.800
[Guest]: by the middle of the 19th century.

01:19:58.800 --> 01:20:02.960
[Guest]: You know, the French expelled the Huguenots and the Protestants.

01:20:02.960 --> 01:20:04.960
[Guest]: England kind of took care of the Catholics and the Jews.

01:20:04.960 --> 01:20:10.120
[Guest]: I mean, you know, we've in a sense accomplished that exclusionary process.

01:20:10.120 --> 01:20:16.080
[Guest]: The United States, right, of course, still hasn't accomplished that process.

01:20:16.080 --> 01:20:21.080
[Guest]: If you look at the late 19th century, right, one of the most sobering facts is that every

01:20:21.080 --> 01:20:26.880
[Guest]: single transition from empire to nation state, right, when the Habsburg Empire dissolves

01:20:26.880 --> 01:20:32.000
[Guest]: into nation states, when the Ottoman Empire dissolves, when the British Empire dissolves,

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:40.400
[Guest]: not a single empire accomplishes that transition without incredible ethnic bloodshed and violence,

01:20:40.400 --> 01:20:42.120
[Guest]: right?

01:20:42.120 --> 01:20:46.680
[Guest]: And to me, that is still, and even if you look at contemporary debates, you know, there's

01:20:46.680 --> 01:20:48.960
[Guest]: an interesting paradox just today, right?

01:20:48.960 --> 01:20:55.800
[Guest]: I mean, even as obdurated judges, Justice Arun Mishra has passed a judgment saying women

01:20:55.800 --> 01:21:00.840
[Guest]: have to have equal rights and property, right?

01:21:00.840 --> 01:21:05.200
[Guest]: You know, to that extent, you might say the constitutional promise of equality is actually

01:21:05.200 --> 01:21:10.680
[Guest]: working out, and yet it's the same Supreme Court, right, which will absolutely excuse

01:21:10.680 --> 01:21:15.700
[Guest]: anything in the name of nationalism, the bridging of civil liberties, right?

01:21:15.700 --> 01:21:24.800
[Guest]: So to my mind, the single biggest source of liberalism that has haunted all liberal societies,

01:21:24.800 --> 01:21:29.240
[Guest]: India is actually not an exception in that, right?

01:21:29.240 --> 01:21:32.520
[Guest]: And that's an undertow even the West feels now.

01:21:32.520 --> 01:21:37.760
[Guest]: You know, Michael Mann has this very powerful article, The Dark Side of Democracy, which

01:21:37.760 --> 01:21:43.400
[Guest]: actually shows post-19th century how European nation states became more homogenized, and

01:21:43.400 --> 01:21:47.400
[Guest]: in each case, accompanied by ethnic cleansing.

01:21:47.400 --> 01:21:53.360
[Guest]: In fact, genocide as a category at some level is a product of a democratic imagination,

01:21:53.360 --> 01:22:00.280
[Guest]: because you target people simply for being who they are, you know, because ethnic demography

01:22:00.280 --> 01:22:03.440
[Guest]: matters to democracy, right?

01:22:03.440 --> 01:22:10.960
[Guest]: Now, India's illiberalism, I would actually also argue, comes from not just nationalism,

01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:16.480
[Guest]: that's one dimension of it, but also this unresolved dilemma in representative democracy,

01:22:16.480 --> 01:22:17.480
[Guest]: right?

01:22:17.480 --> 01:22:25.240
[Guest]: And the unresolved dilemma is this, which is, how is power going to be shared once you

01:22:25.240 --> 01:22:26.880
[Guest]: institutionalize a democracy?

01:22:26.880 --> 01:22:32.480
[Guest]: Now, there's one simple answer you can give, which I'm sure you and I would probably prefer,

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:36.760
[Guest]: which is, look, give everybody the equal vote, one person, one vote, have a constitution

01:22:36.760 --> 01:22:42.520
[Guest]: that safeguards our basic rights, and, you know, on checks and balances, on with it.

01:22:42.520 --> 01:22:50.000
[Guest]: But this solution has proven to be elusive in societies that begin to see themselves

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:56.240
[Guest]: as marked by ethnic or religious majorities and minorities, right?

01:22:56.240 --> 01:23:00.920
[Guest]: Because again, going back to the fear, right, the fear of the minority is that the majority

01:23:00.920 --> 01:23:06.840
[Guest]: is ethnically numerically preponderant, so it will exercise more power, even if you give

01:23:06.840 --> 01:23:10.360
[Guest]: all these nice checks and balances, right?

01:23:10.360 --> 01:23:16.000
[Guest]: And from 1857 onwards, and I think this leads into the rise of Hindutva as well, the big

01:23:16.000 --> 01:23:20.480
[Guest]: debate in India was, how is representative power going to be organized?

01:23:20.480 --> 01:23:25.960
[Guest]: We do, you know, almost 70-80 years of negotiations around these questions, right?

01:23:25.960 --> 01:23:31.320
[Guest]: And particularly around the Hindu-Muslim cleavage, there's the Dalit representation story as

01:23:31.320 --> 01:23:34.680
[Guest]: well, which we can talk about separately, but I think for the Indian purpose, I think

01:23:34.680 --> 01:23:38.220
[Guest]: the Hindu-Muslim cleavage is the most important.

01:23:38.220 --> 01:23:42.000
[Guest]: You try different solutions, right?

01:23:42.000 --> 01:23:46.640
[Guest]: You say, look, there are certain issues on which we will give minorities the veto.

01:23:46.640 --> 01:23:50.520
[Guest]: Well, if you do that, it sets up a majority backlash.

01:23:50.520 --> 01:23:55.480
[Guest]: Why should minorities have veto in excess of their political power, right?

01:23:55.480 --> 01:24:02.800
[Guest]: You try and create representative government compatible with different system of laws.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:06.400
[Guest]: So you, you know, in fact, one of the things, if India had remained united, we probably

01:24:06.400 --> 01:24:09.280
[Guest]: would have been a more conservative country.

01:24:09.280 --> 01:24:14.280
[Guest]: Because the irony is that the most people who were in favor of a united India, the condition

01:24:14.280 --> 01:24:18.760
[Guest]: of it being a united India, as Ambedkar pointed out, was that each community gets to govern

01:24:18.760 --> 01:24:22.040
[Guest]: its own laws, right?

01:24:22.040 --> 01:24:26.560
[Guest]: So from the Minto-Morlay reforms onwards, this constant question, right?

01:24:26.560 --> 01:24:31.040
[Guest]: How will power be shared between Hindus and Muslims?

01:24:31.040 --> 01:24:37.960
[Guest]: If you give the Muslims more protection that they feel they are adequate, you have a reaction

01:24:37.960 --> 01:24:42.300
[Guest]: from the right that says, look, this is a betrayal of the principle of equality, right?

01:24:42.300 --> 01:24:47.980
[Guest]: If you don't give them adequate protection, right, you obviously set up different kinds

01:24:47.980 --> 01:24:48.980
[Guest]: of fears.

01:24:48.980 --> 01:24:51.960
[Guest]: And the fact of the matter is that we never resolved that question.

01:24:51.960 --> 01:24:56.160
[Guest]: And frankly, it could not have been resolved because I think that's true to that American

01:24:56.160 --> 01:25:01.800
[Guest]: constitutionalism thrust, which is that once you pose the question in terms of a permanent

01:25:01.800 --> 01:25:07.240
[Guest]: majority and minority, defined in ethnic terms, there is no solution to, there's no equilibrium

01:25:07.240 --> 01:25:08.240
[Guest]: solution, right?

01:25:08.240 --> 01:25:13.200
[Guest]: The only way you can overcome this is by saying there are no permanent majorities and minorities.

01:25:13.200 --> 01:25:16.400
[Guest]: These are all contingent coalitions and so forth, right?

01:25:16.400 --> 01:25:21.240
[Guest]: Now it's the failure of that negotiation, in part, right?

01:25:21.240 --> 01:25:24.440
[Guest]: That's actually the backdrop of partition.

01:25:24.440 --> 01:25:28.760
[Guest]: In political terms, there is, of course, a much more visceral ethnic and religious dimension

01:25:28.760 --> 01:25:29.880
[Guest]: to it.

01:25:29.880 --> 01:25:34.000
[Guest]: And often those ethnic and religious issues were tested, right?

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:39.000
[Guest]: Those become tests for the representative government, you know, if Congress wins in

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:43.160
[Guest]: UP, will it do Gau Raksha or not, right?

01:25:43.160 --> 01:25:48.040
[Guest]: It's a majority testing its power and a minority fearing it.

01:25:48.040 --> 01:25:56.880
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think the failure of the Indian nationalist movement, while it did

01:25:56.880 --> 01:26:01.080
[Guest]: a remarkable job on almost every other aspect, I think India was brilliant, for example,

01:26:01.080 --> 01:26:03.880
[Guest]: in its thinking about the language question.

01:26:03.880 --> 01:26:08.680
[Guest]: We did not take a ready-made European model saying that the language of the ruler and

01:26:08.680 --> 01:26:12.360
[Guest]: the rule, the language of different provinces should be the same.

01:26:12.360 --> 01:26:18.200
[Guest]: I think when it came to this particular cleavage, frankly, we could not buck the trend that

01:26:18.200 --> 01:26:20.920
[Guest]: every other society has done, right?

01:26:20.920 --> 01:26:27.240
[Guest]: And that's the trend that still casts a kind of shadow on contemporary politics, right?

01:26:27.240 --> 01:26:33.240
[Guest]: You know, so to that extent, I mean, to me, India's constitution, the founding moment,

01:26:33.240 --> 01:26:36.600
[Guest]: one should not forget that it happened in the shadow of partition.

01:26:36.600 --> 01:26:42.440
[Guest]: It happened in the shadow of a massive failure of that nationalist project, which wanted

01:26:42.440 --> 01:26:49.000
[Guest]: the strategic unity of the subcontinent, which thought that there was a traditional cultural

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:56.040
[Guest]: narrative of syncretism, right, that could actually overcome these religious divisions.

01:26:56.040 --> 01:27:00.320
[Guest]: And they completely missed the fact that, and this is something I think we also miss

01:27:00.320 --> 01:27:07.400
[Guest]: in contemporary discourse, that that traditional discourse of syncretism, even if it was only

01:27:07.400 --> 01:27:15.040
[Guest]: imagined, right, could actually not work in the context of modern democratic realities,

01:27:15.040 --> 01:27:16.040
[Guest]: right?

01:27:16.040 --> 01:27:20.440
[Guest]: Older forms of toleration don't require great social mobility.

01:27:20.440 --> 01:27:23.000
[Guest]: We often don't compete for the same things.

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:26.000
[Guest]: Societies are segmented, hierarchical, right?

01:27:26.000 --> 01:27:29.640
[Guest]: Now you're all competing for the same power.

01:27:29.640 --> 01:27:32.680
[Guest]: In that same power, demography becomes important, right?

01:27:32.680 --> 01:27:37.600
[Guest]: So why the census became such a political issue, why it's very important for the BJP,

01:27:37.600 --> 01:27:42.560
[Guest]: the number of Hindus versus the number of Muslims, technically in a liberal society,

01:27:42.560 --> 01:27:43.560
[Guest]: why should this even matter?

01:27:43.560 --> 01:27:48.440
[Guest]: I mean, you don't care what your private religion is and what your private identity is, right?

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:54.880
[Guest]: So to that extent, I would argue that, you know, I don't think the story is as much simply

01:27:54.880 --> 01:27:59.640
[Guest]: a straightforward story of there was a deeply liberal conservative society here.

01:27:59.640 --> 01:28:05.520
[Guest]: I think the bulk of the problems actually came from aporias that are internal to liberal

01:28:05.520 --> 01:28:06.520
[Guest]: democracy itself.

01:28:06.520 --> 01:28:12.240
[Guest]: Now, there is a second way in which I think your narrative has something to it, which

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:17.960
[Guest]: is if you shift the frame from nationalism and the sharing of power between communities

01:28:17.960 --> 01:28:23.120
[Guest]: to what we might call social conservatism, right?

01:28:23.120 --> 01:28:31.800
[Guest]: India was a conservative society, but conservative, we simply mean in basic terms, which is more

01:28:31.800 --> 01:28:38.880
[Guest]: and more individuals were governed by traditional norms of occupation, caste, identity, family,

01:28:38.880 --> 01:28:41.240
[Guest]: and so forth, right?

01:28:41.240 --> 01:28:48.480
[Guest]: Now one of the tasks of the modern state is the way it sets itself is to disembed individuals

01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:52.880
[Guest]: from oppressive social structures of power, right?

01:28:52.880 --> 01:28:57.200
[Guest]: And again, going back to the question, what do you fear more, the Indian state was founded

01:28:57.200 --> 01:29:02.400
[Guest]: on the fear of social power, because social power, as Ambedkar said, meant caste.

01:29:02.400 --> 01:29:07.240
[Guest]: Social power meant sort of patriarchal families, right?

01:29:07.240 --> 01:29:12.120
[Guest]: Social power meant the power of, you know, ostracism, all those kinds of things.

01:29:12.120 --> 01:29:20.400
[Guest]: Now, the Indian constitution, in part, promised that charter of reform, that slowly and gradually,

01:29:20.400 --> 01:29:27.440
[Guest]: right, the most obvious place to do it was caste, temple entry, the abolition of untouchability.

01:29:27.440 --> 01:29:32.000
[Guest]: But again, there are two different liberal approaches to this.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:36.820
[Guest]: And I think, again, as liberals, I think we are torn about this, right?

01:29:36.820 --> 01:29:40.080
[Guest]: One is what you might call a rationalist approach.

01:29:40.080 --> 01:29:49.520
[Guest]: The rationalist approach says that every institution in society must look like or embody the basic

01:29:49.520 --> 01:29:53.680
[Guest]: liberal norms that we expect in our constitution.

01:29:53.680 --> 01:29:58.960
[Guest]: So you might say Article 14, 19, and 21 should govern every institution, right?

01:29:58.960 --> 01:30:04.840
[Guest]: A temple is legitimate only if it doesn't discriminate or exclude, right?

01:30:04.840 --> 01:30:10.760
[Guest]: A family is legitimate only if it treats people equally, right?

01:30:10.760 --> 01:30:16.480
[Guest]: So that's the rationalist, where in a sense, all civic associations, intermediary sources

01:30:16.480 --> 01:30:20.600
[Guest]: of power should also conform to liberal norms.

01:30:20.600 --> 01:30:26.400
[Guest]: There's a second conception that's a little bit more pluralistic, that says that, look,

01:30:26.400 --> 01:30:31.920
[Guest]: you know, these associations and these intermediate sources of power have complex histories, they're

01:30:31.920 --> 01:30:39.200
[Guest]: expresses of people's identities, we may not like them, but they are part of, you might

01:30:39.200 --> 01:30:43.920
[Guest]: say, a more basic freedom of association, right?

01:30:43.920 --> 01:30:48.640
[Guest]: So if a church doesn't ordain women as priests, I mean, that's its business.

01:30:48.640 --> 01:30:51.600
[Guest]: You know, if people want to go to temples that discriminate against women, that's their

01:30:51.600 --> 01:30:52.600
[Guest]: business, right?

01:30:52.600 --> 01:30:59.080
[Guest]: Now, in a way, what the Indian Constitution was, was a kind of compromise between these

01:30:59.080 --> 01:31:00.080
[Guest]: two visions.

01:31:00.080 --> 01:31:04.480
[Guest]: And actually, you can see the tension even in, for example, the Sabarimala judgment,

01:31:04.480 --> 01:31:10.160
[Guest]: you know, in a sense, Hindu Malhotra's judgment, forget the religious argument for a minute,

01:31:10.160 --> 01:31:15.400
[Guest]: in a way, it seems to be saying, look, why should every intermediate institution society

01:31:15.400 --> 01:31:20.200
[Guest]: correspond to what you expect of public institutions, right?

01:31:20.200 --> 01:31:26.400
[Guest]: Now the argument there is that, look, and this is your point about culture in some ways,

01:31:26.400 --> 01:31:33.080
[Guest]: that your public opportunities are deeply structured by these private and civic associations

01:31:33.080 --> 01:31:34.080
[Guest]: and institutions.

01:31:34.080 --> 01:31:39.160
[Guest]: And it's obvious in the case of, for example, gender, I mean, right, if you can't imagine

01:31:39.160 --> 01:31:44.280
[Guest]: in a patriarchal society, civic equality for women actually being realized, other than

01:31:44.280 --> 01:31:47.320
[Guest]: an emotional sense.

01:31:47.320 --> 01:31:55.640
[Guest]: The question is, in a sense, you know, how much do you want to use state power to create

01:31:55.640 --> 01:31:56.640
[Guest]: this reform?

01:31:56.640 --> 01:32:00.960
[Guest]: Or how much do you want to do the work of culture to do this?

01:32:00.960 --> 01:32:05.080
[Guest]: And ideally, in a liberal society, you'll get that balance just right.

01:32:05.080 --> 01:32:11.400
[Guest]: Because having a pure rationalist view does raise questions about the concentration of

01:32:11.400 --> 01:32:15.800
[Guest]: power, you know, risks different kinds of liberties, right?

01:32:15.800 --> 01:32:21.360
[Guest]: Now, what has happened, I think, interestingly, is that the reformists, right, the Congress

01:32:21.360 --> 01:32:27.760
[Guest]: Party, once it acquired state power, it, in a sense, completely gave up that social work

01:32:27.760 --> 01:32:32.920
[Guest]: of reform, which is what it had been doing as a nationalist movement, right?

01:32:32.920 --> 01:32:36.680
[Guest]: You know, it now has state power, it doesn't need to do this stuff.

01:32:36.680 --> 01:32:40.880
[Guest]: Interestingly, what's interesting about the Arnas is, in a sense, is that that's the space

01:32:40.880 --> 01:32:44.600
[Guest]: it began to occupy, right, very, very powerfully, right?

01:32:44.600 --> 01:32:51.360
[Guest]: I mean, it's extraordinary how many so-called, quote unquote, progressive positions the BJP

01:32:51.360 --> 01:32:53.960
[Guest]: has managed to appropriate, right?

01:32:53.960 --> 01:32:59.160
[Guest]: Because what the Congress ended up doing slowly, I mean, obviously, in 1950, there was the

01:32:59.160 --> 01:33:05.240
[Guest]: pressure of partition, it, in a sense, just became comfortable with a status quo, right?

01:33:05.240 --> 01:33:08.200
[Guest]: I mean, why do we want to politicize any of this stuff, right?

01:33:08.200 --> 01:33:13.440
[Guest]: So if, if Muslim personal law doesn't get reformed, that's fine, right?

01:33:13.440 --> 01:33:17.320
[Guest]: You could have created a process of incremental reform.

01:33:17.320 --> 01:33:24.520
[Guest]: And that reinforced the first dynamic about exclusion, because the competition then became

01:33:24.520 --> 01:33:28.320
[Guest]: which communities does the state intervene in most, right?

01:33:28.320 --> 01:33:34.080
[Guest]: That's part of the BJP narrative, that the state deprived the Hindus of their associational

01:33:34.080 --> 01:33:38.000
[Guest]: rights, but it protected minority associational rights.

01:33:38.000 --> 01:33:43.000
[Guest]: Now, I don't think the motives were sinister, I think the motives were just more a combination

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:48.400
[Guest]: of inertia and, you know, why spend political capital on this.

01:33:48.400 --> 01:33:51.480
[Guest]: But it had that net effect, right?

01:33:51.480 --> 01:33:55.920
[Guest]: So you know, to that extent, I think, again, the Indian Constitution is the trajectory

01:33:55.920 --> 01:33:56.920
[Guest]: is no different.

01:33:56.920 --> 01:34:02.400
[Guest]: I mean, let's not forget, right, Switzerland gave women the vote only in 1970.

01:34:02.400 --> 01:34:07.240
[Guest]: That social work is, you know, it's going to be a long haul.

01:34:07.240 --> 01:34:11.520
[Guest]: And to be honest, I am surprised.

01:34:11.520 --> 01:34:17.240
[Guest]: You can look at it this way, which is that, yes, there is a lot of deep exclusionary practice

01:34:17.240 --> 01:34:18.560
[Guest]: in civil society.

01:34:18.560 --> 01:34:25.880
[Guest]: But at the normative level, it's very difficult for anybody to stand up and justify, right?

01:34:25.880 --> 01:34:29.320
[Guest]: You know, in some ways, and that you have to say is an achievement, I think, of that

01:34:29.320 --> 01:34:33.640
[Guest]: constitutional imagination, in some ways.

01:34:33.640 --> 01:34:39.000
[Guest]: So I would submit that I, in comparative perspective, I don't think India looks terribly different,

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:40.000
[Guest]: actually.

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:45.000
[Guest]: I mean, this is part of the process of democratization and modernization.

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:48.920
[Guest]: And I think we are at this particular conjuncture where these two questions have come to the

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:52.320
[Guest]: fore again, right?

01:34:52.320 --> 01:34:58.600
[Guest]: Despite possibility that the BJP is, in principle, and why a lot of Hindus support it, they actually

01:34:58.600 --> 01:35:06.160
[Guest]: don't experience that authoritarianism, right, in relation to where they stand, right?

01:35:06.160 --> 01:35:10.200
[Guest]: You know, but obviously, minorities will, you know, feel it.

01:35:10.200 --> 01:35:14.600
[Guest]: And we've basically decided that, in some senses, we can create a national narrative

01:35:14.600 --> 01:35:20.000
[Guest]: without giving minorities a place, sort of, you know, in it.

01:35:20.000 --> 01:35:23.200
[Guest]: So I think that's a thing.

01:35:23.200 --> 01:35:24.640
[Guest]: I'll just make one last comment.

01:35:24.640 --> 01:35:27.800
[Guest]: I know this answer has been too long, which is much more of an empirical comment, and

01:35:27.800 --> 01:35:32.000
[Guest]: in the spirit that you asked the question of thinking about counterfactuals.

01:35:32.000 --> 01:35:36.200
[Guest]: So I often, in class, pose these two counterfactuals to students.

01:35:36.200 --> 01:35:42.920
[Guest]: One is a counterfactual, let's say, in 1914, or 1915, somewhere in that decade.

01:35:42.920 --> 01:35:47.000
[Guest]: The British just suddenly had a brainwave and decided to leave India.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:51.360
[Guest]: We're quitting, you know, to hell with it, we don't want empire, right?

01:35:51.360 --> 01:35:57.520
[Guest]: Would an Indian constitution have been possible, right, without that 30, 40 years of the kind

01:35:57.520 --> 01:36:01.600
[Guest]: of social mobilization work that the nationalist movement did?

01:36:01.600 --> 01:36:06.600
[Guest]: Actually creating an organizational form, right, that was, in a sense, appropriate to

01:36:06.600 --> 01:36:08.040
[Guest]: the modern world.

01:36:08.040 --> 01:36:16.080
[Guest]: Second counterfactual is, I think, the assassination of Gandhi, which is, if Gandhi had not been

01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:25.400
[Guest]: assassinated and the RSS had not been temporarily delegitimized as a result, would the right-wing

01:36:25.400 --> 01:36:31.520
[Guest]: challenge to Nehru in the 1950s have been even stronger than it was?

01:36:31.520 --> 01:36:32.520
[Guest]: It was actually quite strong.

01:36:32.520 --> 01:36:34.360
[Guest]: I mean, we underestimate how strong it was.

01:36:34.360 --> 01:36:38.040
[Guest]: I mean, not just Karpatri Maharaj and the reform bill, but even within the Congress

01:36:38.040 --> 01:36:39.040
[Guest]: Party, as you know.

01:36:39.040 --> 01:36:43.800
[Guest]: I mean, you know, frankly, people like Govind Balampant and so forth are actually frightening

01:36:43.800 --> 01:36:48.640
[Guest]: figures in the history of Indian communism, right?

01:36:48.640 --> 01:36:55.760
[Guest]: And would the new republic then have, in a sense, been split, not being able to consolidate

01:36:55.760 --> 01:37:00.600
[Guest]: enough power in a way that so many countries around the world have found themselves, right?

01:37:00.600 --> 01:37:04.880
[Guest]: I think that's also an interesting counterfactual to think about.

01:37:04.880 --> 01:37:05.880
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating.

01:37:05.880 --> 01:37:09.280
[Amit Varma]: And I want to come back later to a version of the second counterfactual and we can talk

01:37:09.280 --> 01:37:10.280
[Amit Varma]: more about that.

01:37:10.280 --> 01:37:11.280
[Amit Varma]: But there's a lot to unpack.

01:37:11.280 --> 01:37:13.560
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of observations and questions.

01:37:13.560 --> 01:37:21.040
[Amit Varma]: One is, you know, it's quite a stunning insight in a sense that genocide is incentivized by

01:37:21.040 --> 01:37:25.760
[Amit Varma]: democracy because as you pointed out, and you in the past quoted Syed Ahmed Khan quoting

01:37:25.760 --> 01:37:32.720
[Amit Varma]: John Stuart Mill talking about how democracy is all about demography, you know, the potency

01:37:32.720 --> 01:37:38.760
[Amit Varma]: of the terms majority and minority would not matter anywhere except in a democracy because,

01:37:38.760 --> 01:37:41.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, it is so critical there.

01:37:41.920 --> 01:37:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, one thought that strikes me then is that in any democracy is

01:37:48.080 --> 01:37:52.600
[Amit Varma]: this kind of majoritarianism politics inevitable at some point.

01:37:52.600 --> 01:38:00.920
[Amit Varma]: The other sort of threads I want to unpack is that, you know, one of the sort of conflicts

01:38:00.920 --> 01:38:05.400
[Amit Varma]: at the start, which I don't think we quite figured out either way, is with regards to

01:38:05.400 --> 01:38:08.360
[Amit Varma]: the constitution that what is the aim of the constitution?

01:38:08.360 --> 01:38:12.600
[Amit Varma]: Should it protect individuals, or should it transform society?

01:38:12.600 --> 01:38:17.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and obviously, my bias would be that it should protect individuals.

01:38:17.720 --> 01:38:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And if you try to transform society in a top down coercive way, it's only going to end

01:38:21.800 --> 01:38:22.800
[Amit Varma]: badly.

01:38:22.800 --> 01:38:26.640
[Amit Varma]: But leave that whole argument aside.

01:38:26.640 --> 01:38:32.600
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that like you pointed out that the constitution was partly shaped by

01:38:32.600 --> 01:38:35.040
[Amit Varma]: the contingencies of partition.

01:38:35.040 --> 01:38:38.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the historian Gyan Prakash in an episode we did on the emergency spoke about

01:38:38.480 --> 01:38:43.160
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, so many of the centralizing impulses of the constitution came about because

01:38:43.160 --> 01:38:45.120
[Amit Varma]: the country was being torn apart by violence.

01:38:45.120 --> 01:38:50.040
[Amit Varma]: So those people sitting in that room in Delhi obviously wanted to centralize more power.

01:38:50.040 --> 01:38:55.360
[Amit Varma]: But it then also strikes me, in the narrow context of the relationship between the majority

01:38:55.360 --> 01:39:02.440
[Amit Varma]: and the minority, that we took a protective role, but towards the minorities, but a transformative

01:39:02.440 --> 01:39:05.480
[Amit Varma]: role towards a majority in the classic example of this.

01:39:05.480 --> 01:39:12.720
[Amit Varma]: And this is something where I think I sort of totally understand the RSS point of view.

01:39:12.720 --> 01:39:17.040
[Amit Varma]: The example of this is a Hindu code bill, that with the Hindu code bill, you're trying

01:39:17.040 --> 01:39:24.440
[Amit Varma]: to transform Hindu society, but you're not doing something equivalent for Muslims.

01:39:24.440 --> 01:39:30.200
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, then, you know, when you have all this talk later on of pseudo secularism

01:39:30.200 --> 01:39:35.000
[Amit Varma]: and pandering to minorities and all of that, those seem to be legitimate grievances.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:39.360
[Amit Varma]: And it is kind of irrelevant whether you should have any code bill at all, whether you should

01:39:39.360 --> 01:39:43.320
[Amit Varma]: reform none of them, whether you should reform both of them, it doesn't matter.

01:39:43.320 --> 01:39:47.480
[Amit Varma]: But the bottom line is that at that moment, we are not treating them equally.

01:39:47.480 --> 01:39:51.040
[Amit Varma]: We are saying that, you know, in one case, the constitution is saying, hey, we'll protect

01:39:51.040 --> 01:39:53.720
[Amit Varma]: whatever your customs and whatever they are.

01:39:53.720 --> 01:39:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And even there, we're not really protecting individual rights, we're just looking at them

01:39:57.000 --> 01:39:58.400
[Amit Varma]: as a group.

01:39:58.400 --> 01:40:01.760
[Amit Varma]: But in the other instance, you are saying that, hey, no, we are transformative, and

01:40:01.760 --> 01:40:02.760
[Amit Varma]: we want to transform you.

01:40:02.760 --> 01:40:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And I can see why, you know, this, this can be just so powerful by itself, as a motivating

01:40:11.000 --> 01:40:12.000
[Amit Varma]: factor.

01:40:12.000 --> 01:40:19.720
[Amit Varma]: But my broader question is that, how do you then look at, you know, this, this conflict

01:40:19.720 --> 01:40:24.400
[Amit Varma]: between should we protect or should we transform because they are in conflict with each other?

01:40:24.400 --> 01:40:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Because every transformative act that you try to do involves coercion and involves sort

01:40:29.400 --> 01:40:32.080
[Amit Varma]: of not treating citizens equally and all of that.

01:40:32.080 --> 01:40:36.560
[Amit Varma]: And I can understand that when you look at society at that point, and you see so many

01:40:36.560 --> 01:40:41.040
[Amit Varma]: things wrong with it, you know, with caste, to begin with, that's obviously number one,

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:45.160
[Amit Varma]: but so many other things, and your instinct is that this is horrendous, we must transform

01:40:45.160 --> 01:40:46.480
[Amit Varma]: it, how do we do it?

01:40:46.480 --> 01:40:50.040
[Amit Varma]: Oh, now we have the power of the state with us, our colonial masters are gone, let's use

01:40:50.040 --> 01:40:51.720
[Amit Varma]: the power of the state.

01:40:51.720 --> 01:40:58.120
[Amit Varma]: But I think one of the lessons of history is that top down coercion really doesn't work,

01:40:58.120 --> 01:41:01.760
[Amit Varma]: what you need is social transformation coming from within the kind of transformation that

01:41:01.760 --> 01:41:07.040
[Amit Varma]: in fact, Gandhi would broadly have sympathized with, where Gandhi's whole thing was that,

01:41:07.040 --> 01:41:11.280
[Amit Varma]: no, let's, let's go into the, you know, the villages and the interiors and change society

01:41:11.280 --> 01:41:15.560
[Amit Varma]: from within, even if that is too idealistic in a short span of time.

01:41:15.560 --> 01:41:20.280
[Amit Varma]: And I think it seems that we rely too much on the transformative nature of the Constitution,

01:41:20.280 --> 01:41:24.920
[Amit Varma]: did a halfway and inept job there, and didn't bring about any social change either.

01:41:24.920 --> 01:41:25.920
[Amit Varma]: So what are your sort of thoughts?

01:41:25.920 --> 01:41:28.800
[Guest]: Okay, no, that's a very powerful question.

01:41:28.800 --> 01:41:33.160
[Guest]: I think I agree with much of what you said, but again, I think it just helps to broaden

01:41:33.160 --> 01:41:38.280
[Guest]: the frame a little bit, I think, just to, I think, put that narrative in perspective,

01:41:38.280 --> 01:41:39.280
[Guest]: right.

01:41:39.280 --> 01:41:43.480
[Guest]: And, and I'll first, maybe spend a couple of minutes on the historical narrative, and

01:41:43.480 --> 01:41:49.280
[Guest]: then come to the deep philosophical point you raised about is, you know, is this a constitution

01:41:49.280 --> 01:41:54.000
[Guest]: protective of, of group rights and plurality in some ways, or is it a constitution of freedom

01:41:54.000 --> 01:41:55.000
[Guest]: in some ways?

01:41:55.000 --> 01:42:02.080
[Guest]: I mean, so, you know, at one level, I think the narrative you're describing, right, that

01:42:02.080 --> 01:42:06.760
[Guest]: that has got entrenched, and I think there's some power to it, that the Indian state was

01:42:06.760 --> 01:42:13.240
[Guest]: seen to act asymmetrically towards communities, right.

01:42:13.240 --> 01:42:21.920
[Guest]: Now, we can wind the clock back to the 1950s, and think of a different kind of counterfactual.

01:42:21.920 --> 01:42:26.760
[Guest]: But I do think it's worth, again, remembering two things, and, and, and I'm stressing this,

01:42:26.760 --> 01:42:29.840
[Guest]: because I think it's going to come up again in our contemporary context.

01:42:29.840 --> 01:42:36.520
[Guest]: So there is no question that we need, as a society, a consensus that there are certain

01:42:36.520 --> 01:42:41.560
[Guest]: basic norms of individual freedom that apply to all communities.

01:42:41.560 --> 01:42:45.840
[Guest]: I think if Section 295 has to go in the Indian Penal Code, offenses to religion has to go

01:42:45.840 --> 01:42:46.840
[Guest]: for all communities.

01:42:46.840 --> 01:42:51.080
[Guest]: I mean, I actually don't think a modern state should have a category called offense to religion.

01:42:51.080 --> 01:42:57.640
[Guest]: Doesn't matter what the religion is, you know, in some ways, right.

01:42:57.640 --> 01:43:01.920
[Guest]: When it comes to personal laws, for example, which is the most contentious issue, again,

01:43:01.920 --> 01:43:06.760
[Guest]: I think the shadow of partition did make a difference, which is, I think, Nehru's concern

01:43:06.760 --> 01:43:11.920
[Guest]: that not just that minorities feel safe, but remember, you still haven't solved the question,

01:43:11.920 --> 01:43:21.600
[Guest]: which is, who will be exercising power when these personal laws are being reformed, right?

01:43:21.600 --> 01:43:27.520
[Guest]: And you know, personal laws do sort of affect the most kind of intimate aspects of a particular

01:43:27.520 --> 01:43:28.920
[Guest]: culture's identity in some way.

01:43:28.920 --> 01:43:32.000
[Guest]: So there's always much more at stake.

01:43:32.000 --> 01:43:39.600
[Guest]: Now, if you had created those relationships of trust, right, let's say even now, I'm all

01:43:39.600 --> 01:43:40.880
[Guest]: for a uniform civil code.

01:43:40.880 --> 01:43:43.000
[Guest]: I think it's high time we had it.

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:47.760
[Guest]: And even within a uniform civil code, there can be, you know, interesting creative solutions.

01:43:47.760 --> 01:43:56.040
[Guest]: But the question is, who do you trust to come up with the content of a code that is actually

01:43:56.040 --> 01:43:59.240
[Guest]: just and fair to all communities?

01:43:59.240 --> 01:44:06.040
[Guest]: Will the content of that code, right, could it unwittingly have a Hindu majoritarian hue

01:44:06.040 --> 01:44:07.040
[Guest]: in it?

01:44:07.040 --> 01:44:08.040
[Guest]: Right?

01:44:08.040 --> 01:44:09.040
[Guest]: Possible, right?

01:44:09.040 --> 01:44:16.320
[Guest]: So, you know, going back to the question you asked at the beginning of this program, the

01:44:16.320 --> 01:44:23.120
[Guest]: missing element in this debate has been what are the conditions of trust under which reforming

01:44:23.120 --> 01:44:27.320
[Guest]: all our personal laws can be a common project?

01:44:27.320 --> 01:44:30.960
[Guest]: The misleading part is there is the state and the state reforms Hindus and it doesn't

01:44:30.960 --> 01:44:33.160
[Guest]: reform, you know, Muslim personal law.

01:44:33.160 --> 01:44:34.720
[Guest]: Even that's strictly speaking not true.

01:44:34.720 --> 01:44:41.640
[Guest]: I mean, I think, you know, for political reasons, Rajiv Gandhi overturned the Shah Bano judgment.

01:44:41.640 --> 01:44:46.000
[Guest]: In fact, we often forget that the Supreme Court shortly thereafter in Daniel Latifi kind

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:49.880
[Guest]: of reinstated the original Shah Bano judgment without much fuss.

01:44:49.880 --> 01:44:53.160
[Guest]: So there are possibilities of reform even there.

01:44:53.160 --> 01:45:00.800
[Guest]: The issue is that the state has always been, because it's in a sense seen as a function

01:45:00.800 --> 01:45:06.120
[Guest]: of majority power, and the more you make it a function of majority power, right, the less

01:45:06.120 --> 01:45:12.480
[Guest]: reason people have to trust that what comes out of it, right, will be actually fair and

01:45:12.480 --> 01:45:13.480
[Guest]: just.

01:45:13.480 --> 01:45:16.400
[Guest]: So I think, and one of the reasons why we want to lower the temperature of religious

01:45:16.400 --> 01:45:21.480
[Guest]: politics in India is because that's a necessary condition for paving the way for having this

01:45:21.480 --> 01:45:29.480
[Guest]: debate in a rational, constructive manner that, look, in the 21st century, right, family

01:45:29.480 --> 01:45:33.480
[Guest]: relations cannot be constructed on certain legal lines and so on and so forth.

01:45:33.480 --> 01:45:35.100
[Guest]: So absolutely, I think that's one.

01:45:35.100 --> 01:45:40.000
[Guest]: The second thing, I would go even stronger than you, I mean, to me, the Congress Party's

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:50.280
[Guest]: unconscionable sin is that it actually placed Indian Muslims in the worst of both positions.

01:45:50.280 --> 01:45:54.920
[Guest]: On the one hand, it empowered the most reactionary elements in that society.

01:45:54.920 --> 01:45:58.240
[Guest]: I mean, what is the Indian, All India Muslim Personal Law Board?

01:45:58.240 --> 01:46:05.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's an astonishingly obtuse organization, I mean, seriously, you know, but who sustained

01:46:05.480 --> 01:46:06.480
[Guest]: its legitimacy?

01:46:06.480 --> 01:46:07.480
[Guest]: Right?

01:46:07.480 --> 01:46:10.520
[Guest]: I mean, you don't have to have an either-or solution, you don't have to say the state

01:46:10.520 --> 01:46:18.040
[Guest]: comes marching in, but you can create an intelligent politics where these spaces get opened up.

01:46:18.040 --> 01:46:22.720
[Guest]: And people forget, for example, there is an alternative Muslim women's personal law proposal

01:46:22.720 --> 01:46:27.800
[Guest]: on the table, right, which is way more progressive, right?

01:46:27.800 --> 01:46:35.960
[Guest]: But it was in the Congress Party's interest to keep the Muslims backward and with their

01:46:35.960 --> 01:46:38.880
[Guest]: back against the wall.

01:46:38.880 --> 01:46:44.400
[Guest]: Because at some point, they did decide, or they thought that you needed them as a kind

01:46:44.400 --> 01:46:45.400
[Guest]: of electoral coalition.

01:46:45.400 --> 01:46:49.160
[Guest]: And I think there, the BJP's diagnosis is not wrong, right?

01:46:49.160 --> 01:46:57.480
[Guest]: That ethnic identities work as electoral fodder, only when there is a kind of collective risk

01:46:57.480 --> 01:46:58.480
[Guest]: that they appear.

01:46:58.480 --> 01:47:02.040
[Guest]: If they all become individuals, we actually don't have that.

01:47:02.040 --> 01:47:05.760
[Guest]: But in the process, you know, when we're talking about the 1950s, I don't know if you've ever

01:47:05.760 --> 01:47:08.720
[Guest]: read Paul Brass's biography of Charan Singh.

01:47:08.720 --> 01:47:13.480
[Guest]: It's an astonishing book, actually, one of the best kind of a North Indian politics.

01:47:13.480 --> 01:47:21.320
[Guest]: But you know, the UP government in the 1950s created an active program of de-Muslimizing

01:47:21.320 --> 01:47:23.840
[Guest]: UP government, right?

01:47:23.840 --> 01:47:29.120
[Guest]: So if you look at the statistics, right, Muslim under-representation in police, Muslim under-representation

01:47:29.120 --> 01:47:33.560
[Guest]: in public institutions of the state, Muslim representation in politics, this was not just

01:47:33.560 --> 01:47:36.180
[Guest]: an accident, right?

01:47:36.180 --> 01:47:41.980
[Guest]: So you ended up in this bizarre situation where at one level, Muslims were becoming

01:47:41.980 --> 01:47:46.800
[Guest]: more marginalized, economically more disempowered, and in a sense, in some states, they've actually

01:47:46.800 --> 01:47:50.800
[Guest]: fallen behind Dalits, which is saying quite something, right?

01:47:50.800 --> 01:47:58.400
[Guest]: As a result of active choices the state made on education or not giving education, as a

01:47:58.400 --> 01:48:04.280
[Guest]: result of the kind of cop-out attitude we have towards Mother Saas, but at the same

01:48:04.280 --> 01:48:09.200
[Guest]: time, right, and this is the point Paul Brass makes very powerfully, you had politicians

01:48:09.200 --> 01:48:15.800
[Guest]: like Govind Bannapanth, you had politicians like Charan Singh, who were electorally secular,

01:48:15.800 --> 01:48:20.200
[Guest]: but administratively and ideologically common, right?

01:48:20.200 --> 01:48:27.120
[Guest]: Rajiv Gandhi, I mean, this is one of the most disastrous episodes in modern Indian history

01:48:27.120 --> 01:48:32.080
[Guest]: because here is a government with a 400 seat majority.

01:48:32.080 --> 01:48:37.160
[Guest]: Frankly, the modern contemporary debate on free speech starts with the banning of satanic

01:48:37.160 --> 01:48:43.720
[Guest]: verses, which kind of then sets the paradigm for competitive victimization, the overturning

01:48:43.720 --> 01:48:49.080
[Guest]: of Shahbano, and Congress got it into its head that somehow it could appease both Muslim

01:48:49.080 --> 01:48:52.120
[Guest]: nationalism and Hindu nationalism together, right?

01:48:52.120 --> 01:48:57.160
[Guest]: The net result was you simply created collective insecurity all around, right?

01:48:57.160 --> 01:49:05.000
[Guest]: Now, my plea to the RSS, my plea to the BJP, since they are the hegemonic story, is that

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:08.120
[Guest]: there is a lot of truth in your critique.

01:49:08.120 --> 01:49:14.000
[Guest]: Many of us shared it, I mean, you know, this piece wrote 20 years ago, Congress, secularism

01:49:14.000 --> 01:49:18.040
[Guest]: and freedom, which actually just made this point.

01:49:18.040 --> 01:49:25.560
[Guest]: But in order to overcome this legacy, the first step has to be, in a sense, the recreation

01:49:25.560 --> 01:49:33.600
[Guest]: of a kind of civic trust, where these conversations do not stoke fears in all sides, where it

01:49:33.600 --> 01:49:38.640
[Guest]: doesn't happen in a context where one group says, look, now we have the power.

01:49:38.640 --> 01:49:39.960
[Guest]: And in a sense, we can have them.

01:49:39.960 --> 01:49:44.760
[Guest]: Frankly, if liberals in the left are feeling it, think of what Muslims might be feeling

01:49:44.760 --> 01:49:45.760
[Guest]: it, right?

01:49:45.760 --> 01:49:46.760
[Guest]: Right.

01:49:46.760 --> 01:49:50.640
[Guest]: So the diagnosis had the truth to it, right?

01:49:50.640 --> 01:49:55.960
[Guest]: But it's in a sense, turning the remedy into a kind of poison, right, which is in some

01:49:55.960 --> 01:49:56.960
[Guest]: sense is more divisive.

01:49:56.960 --> 01:50:00.640
[Guest]: Now, coming to your theoretical question, which is, you know, what is the vision of

01:50:00.640 --> 01:50:06.440
[Guest]: the Indian Constitution, I would put it this way, that I actually do think the longer term

01:50:06.440 --> 01:50:11.840
[Guest]: vision of the Indian Constitution is the emancipation of individuals from all forms of intermediate

01:50:11.840 --> 01:50:14.280
[Guest]: social hierarchies.

01:50:14.280 --> 01:50:21.320
[Guest]: I think it recognizes the fact that that can't be done simply through law, right?

01:50:21.320 --> 01:50:25.320
[Guest]: Because you have to actually deploy state power, right?

01:50:25.320 --> 01:50:29.600
[Guest]: You have to force policemen to make sure that people are allowed to enter temples and not

01:50:29.600 --> 01:50:31.840
[Guest]: allowed to temple, right?

01:50:31.840 --> 01:50:37.360
[Guest]: And I think their concern for India's diversity in politics, that they hoped that it would

01:50:37.360 --> 01:50:41.080
[Guest]: come out through a negotiated process, right?

01:50:41.080 --> 01:50:44.320
[Guest]: As you said, you know, there'll be social reform movements.

01:50:44.320 --> 01:50:47.200
[Guest]: And that's exactly the thing that we completely stopped.

01:50:47.200 --> 01:50:51.360
[Guest]: I mean, Congress Party abdicated it, not just because it had the state power, but I think

01:50:51.360 --> 01:50:54.480
[Guest]: even in some senses more broadly.

01:50:54.480 --> 01:50:58.480
[Guest]: And the social change that did come about, right, was a social change that came about

01:50:58.480 --> 01:51:03.080
[Guest]: for other secular developments as the economy goes more complex, certain identities wither

01:51:03.080 --> 01:51:06.200
[Guest]: away, you know, in some instances, you know, so forth.

01:51:06.200 --> 01:51:12.000
[Guest]: So I think that was the vision, which was a kind of ameliorative transformation towards

01:51:12.000 --> 01:51:13.000
[Guest]: individual rights.

01:51:13.000 --> 01:51:17.880
[Guest]: I think the mistake that we have made, and this is again an exercise I set our students

01:51:17.880 --> 01:51:24.120
[Guest]: in class sometimes, that there are a couple of clauses, for example, if you think of the

01:51:24.120 --> 01:51:31.320
[Guest]: clause of protection of minority institutions, right, which can probably be articulated in

01:51:31.320 --> 01:51:36.400
[Guest]: more individualistic rather than collective terms, and you get the same result, right?

01:51:36.400 --> 01:51:41.280
[Guest]: In fact, I think in the TMIY case, I mean, I think the debate between Rumapal and Bariyawal

01:51:41.280 --> 01:51:47.600
[Guest]: was actually very instructive, where one interpretation was that the minority clauses in the Constitution

01:51:47.600 --> 01:51:51.880
[Guest]: are clauses that are setting off exceptions, right?

01:51:51.880 --> 01:51:55.200
[Guest]: The other interpretation of that clause is that it's not setting up exceptions, it's

01:51:55.200 --> 01:51:59.680
[Guest]: just a signal to minorities that these clauses will also protect you.

01:51:59.680 --> 01:52:04.600
[Guest]: So for example, I think on, for example, the freedom to run institutions, a simpler approach

01:52:04.600 --> 01:52:08.400
[Guest]: is, and which is, I think, compatible with the text of the Constitution, should be simply

01:52:08.400 --> 01:52:13.880
[Guest]: to say that, look, so long as you're not taking state money, and you're not doing any other

01:52:13.880 --> 01:52:19.000
[Guest]: kind of fiduciary harm to any other constitutional provision, any group should have the freedom

01:52:19.000 --> 01:52:22.840
[Guest]: to run its institutions as they want, and if you have that provision, minorities will

01:52:22.840 --> 01:52:25.160
[Guest]: automatically be protected, right?

01:52:25.160 --> 01:52:31.440
[Guest]: I mean, but I think the way in which we've developed that Constitution law, we unnecessarily

01:52:31.440 --> 01:52:38.040
[Guest]: give this kind of indication that these exceptions are being carved out, right?

01:52:38.040 --> 01:52:42.680
[Guest]: But you can achieve those same goals better with, in a sense, freedom.

01:52:42.680 --> 01:52:47.600
[Guest]: I would also say this about our discourse on diversity, for example, and one of my kind

01:52:47.600 --> 01:52:53.480
[Guest]: of worries about a lot of my friends, actually, you know, our circles, as it were.

01:52:53.480 --> 01:52:58.540
[Guest]: So we like to celebrate India's diversity as an astonishing country in some ways.

01:52:58.540 --> 01:53:04.440
[Guest]: But diversity is also a conceptual trap, because, you know, diversity is quite compatible with

01:53:04.440 --> 01:53:08.160
[Guest]: each person being boxed into a particular identity.

01:53:08.160 --> 01:53:09.440
[Guest]: We need to defend freedom.

01:53:09.440 --> 01:53:15.180
[Guest]: If individuals are given freedom, lots of new forms of diversity will emerge, right?

01:53:15.180 --> 01:53:19.280
[Guest]: The identity categories that we think are salient right now will cease to be salient

01:53:19.280 --> 01:53:20.560
[Guest]: five, 10 years from now.

01:53:20.560 --> 01:53:21.560
[Guest]: And that's all for the good.

01:53:21.560 --> 01:53:23.360
[Guest]: I mean, that's right.

01:53:23.360 --> 01:53:30.980
[Guest]: So I think that self-conception that in order to oppose the mono-ethnicity of Hindutva,

01:53:30.980 --> 01:53:38.960
[Guest]: what you need to propose in its place is diversity, I think can be conceptually misleading, because

01:53:38.960 --> 01:53:42.320
[Guest]: diversity is also compatible with a certain kind of fixity.

01:53:42.320 --> 01:53:47.360
[Guest]: I think where you and I will probably agree is that we just need to go back to a, you

01:53:47.360 --> 01:53:52.560
[Guest]: know, basic jurisprudence of individual rights and dignity, protect those freedoms, and all

01:53:52.560 --> 01:53:54.640
[Amit Varma]: the diversity will come in its wake.

01:53:54.640 --> 01:53:58.360
[Amit Varma]: This episode of the seen and the unseen is one where you actually come out as a closet

01:53:58.360 --> 01:54:04.080
[Amit Varma]: libertarian quite clearly, you know, one of the sort of constant bugbears that I have,

01:54:04.080 --> 01:54:08.680
[Amit Varma]: and it's not just with regards to the Constitution, but politics today, even more so today, is

01:54:08.680 --> 01:54:12.120
[Amit Varma]: that we think too much in terms of groups and not individuals, you know, like that old

01:54:12.120 --> 01:54:15.080
[Amit Varma]: saying goes, an individual is the smallest minority.

01:54:15.080 --> 01:54:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And the moment you sort of put a label on an individual that you are X or you are Y,

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:25.760
[Amit Varma]: it constrains individual freedom, even in the ways that you think of yourself, like

01:54:25.760 --> 01:54:30.160
[Amit Varma]: these structures matter so much, which I'll kind of come back to.

01:54:30.160 --> 01:54:35.720
[Amit Varma]: But before I ask my other big conceptual question about the founding moment, I want to also

01:54:35.720 --> 01:54:40.080
[Amit Varma]: go back to the counterfactual, because you know, the more that I read the history of

01:54:40.080 --> 01:54:44.440
[Amit Varma]: that period, and even before, it seems to me that all the tall leaders of the Congress

01:54:44.440 --> 01:54:50.960
[Amit Varma]: were Hindu nationalists of a sort, from, you know, Patel to Prasad and Pant Shastri and

01:54:50.960 --> 01:54:51.960
[Amit Varma]: so on.

01:54:51.960 --> 01:54:56.400
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's this, you know, the interesting incident in Uttar Pradesh, when, you know,

01:54:56.400 --> 01:55:01.600
[Amit Varma]: activists of the VHP installed the idol of Lord Ram within the Babri Masjid and at that

01:55:01.600 --> 01:55:06.360
[Amit Varma]: point, Pant was Chief Minister and the Home Minister of UP was Lal Bahadur Shastri.

01:55:06.360 --> 01:55:10.920
[Amit Varma]: And Nehru was aghast and he sent orders that immediately removed the idol and blah, blah,

01:55:10.920 --> 01:55:11.920
[Amit Varma]: blah.

01:55:11.920 --> 01:55:14.880
[Amit Varma]: And they prevaricated and then inertia took over and it never happened because it didn't

01:55:14.880 --> 01:55:16.120
[Amit Varma]: want it to happen.

01:55:16.120 --> 01:55:21.060
[Amit Varma]: But what has also struck me reading the history of that period is that Nehru in that sense

01:55:21.060 --> 01:55:25.960
[Amit Varma]: was a man apart in both good ways and bad ways, not just one or the other when it's

01:55:25.960 --> 01:55:29.280
[Amit Varma]: so easy to think of him in binary terms.

01:55:29.280 --> 01:55:33.920
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the counterfactual that fascinates me is what if Nehru didn't exist, you know,

01:55:33.920 --> 01:55:37.920
[Amit Varma]: or what if for whatever reason, like, you know, there was a point in 1950 where he got

01:55:37.920 --> 01:55:41.000
[Amit Varma]: frustrated and he said, I won't quit and all of that.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And what if for some reason, he wasn't the person sort of shaping all of that?

01:55:46.200 --> 01:55:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you've thought about or how do you think we would have taken shape

01:55:49.600 --> 01:55:50.600
[Amit Varma]: differently?

01:55:50.600 --> 01:55:52.200
[Guest]: And, you know, what are the possibilities?

01:55:52.200 --> 01:55:58.360
[Guest]: No, we actually have, you know, one of my colleagues and friends, Rudraksha Mukherjee,

01:55:58.360 --> 01:56:02.600
[Guest]: the historian actually poses, there's also an interesting counterfactual, if Nehru and

01:56:02.600 --> 01:56:06.720
[Guest]: Bose together had split with Gandhi, which they had come very close to.

01:56:06.720 --> 01:56:09.880
[Guest]: And on ideological grounds, they were all on the same side.

01:56:09.880 --> 01:56:15.800
[Guest]: I think it was Nehru's filial piety towards Gandhi that kind of kept him in place.

01:56:15.800 --> 01:56:19.440
[Guest]: You know, I think what would have happened to the Congress Party, right, in some senses

01:56:19.440 --> 01:56:20.560
[Guest]: would have.

01:56:20.560 --> 01:56:26.480
[Guest]: But I think in particular in these times, though, I think it's worth remembering one

01:56:26.480 --> 01:56:32.800
[Guest]: very big thing about that generation, right, is yes, they disagreed.

01:56:32.800 --> 01:56:35.880
[Guest]: Many of them were Hindu nationalists.

01:56:35.880 --> 01:56:41.120
[Guest]: But it is remarkable that they all recognized greatness when they saw it.

01:56:41.120 --> 01:56:47.040
[Guest]: And it is remarkable that they continue to agree to work despite their differences.

01:56:47.040 --> 01:56:51.720
[Guest]: I mean, I think the Patel-Nehru relationship, contrary to what the BJP says is, you know,

01:56:51.720 --> 01:56:54.520
[Guest]: my colleague Srinath will point out, it's very complicated.

01:56:54.520 --> 01:56:58.720
[Guest]: I mean, Patel has the greatness to recognize Nehru's indispensability, right, you know,

01:56:58.720 --> 01:57:00.120
[Guest]: in some senses at one level.

01:57:00.120 --> 01:57:06.000
[Guest]: And Nehru, in turn, at different points, has the openness to say, yes, you know, I can

01:57:06.000 --> 01:57:07.560
[Guest]: talk to Shyama Prasad Mukherjee.

01:57:07.560 --> 01:57:10.040
[Guest]: Yes, Ambedkar needs to be part of the draft.

01:57:10.040 --> 01:57:11.040
[Guest]: K.M.

01:57:11.040 --> 01:57:15.320
[Guest]: Munshi, one of the most fascinating figures in the kind of Constituent Assembly, right.

01:57:15.320 --> 01:57:21.200
[Guest]: So you know, there's that old saying, right, that often what builds nations is not the

01:57:21.200 --> 01:57:24.040
[Guest]: consistency of their ideologies.

01:57:24.040 --> 01:57:28.920
[Guest]: It's in a sense, the sensibilities and temperaments of the people who come together to build it.

01:57:28.920 --> 01:57:33.560
[Guest]: And I think there was something about that generation that actually trumped a lot of

01:57:33.560 --> 01:57:34.560
[Guest]: this stuff.

01:57:34.560 --> 01:57:38.240
[Guest]: I mean, you know, they didn't all walk out in a half.

01:57:38.240 --> 01:57:40.800
[Guest]: They did see the Constituent Assembly as a joint project.

01:57:40.800 --> 01:57:45.560
[Guest]: Yes, it was not representative in terms of mass franchise, but Congress did bend over

01:57:45.560 --> 01:57:51.800
[Guest]: backwards to make sure that you had Ambedkar's and the K.M. Munshi's in very critical drafting

01:57:51.800 --> 01:57:53.800
[Guest]: roles in the Constitution, right.

01:57:53.800 --> 01:57:59.680
[Guest]: So I think that sensibility, not to take away anything from Nehru, but it is one thing I

01:57:59.680 --> 01:58:07.640
[Guest]: would give all those others credit for as well, that despite themselves, right, including

01:58:07.640 --> 01:58:14.440
[Guest]: Rajendra Prasad, despite themselves, they actually did see not just Nehru, but I think

01:58:14.440 --> 01:58:20.880
[Guest]: it was a kind of tacit acknowledgement that Nehru stands for more than Nehru the person.

01:58:20.880 --> 01:58:26.720
[Guest]: And there is a implicit constitutional vision here that can be shades of disagreement over,

01:58:26.720 --> 01:58:27.720
[Guest]: you know, right.

01:58:27.720 --> 01:58:32.720
[Guest]: And I think what reconciles, I think, this fact, the kind of how can you be Hindu nationalist

01:58:32.720 --> 01:58:37.880
[Guest]: in Congress is, as I said, I think because it's so much outwardly directed, I mean, I

01:58:37.880 --> 01:58:43.960
[Guest]: think one of the interesting things about 20th century Hindu nationalism is that internally

01:58:43.960 --> 01:58:47.840
[Guest]: it has also always tried to place itself as progressive, right.

01:58:47.840 --> 01:58:54.240
[Guest]: I mean, it has to be at the kind of cutting edge of global, and, you know, take Savarkar,

01:58:54.240 --> 01:58:55.240
[Guest]: for example.

01:58:55.240 --> 01:59:01.440
[Guest]: I mean, you know, in the relationship between Hindus and others, Savarkar has an edge.

01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:04.400
[Guest]: But he is internally a reformer in some senses.

01:59:04.400 --> 01:59:09.560
[Guest]: And I think there are a few, I think, Govind Ballapad, for example, who are, I think, genuine

01:59:09.560 --> 01:59:14.040
[Guest]: conservatives, which is what they want to preserve that sort of older Brahminical hierarchical

01:59:14.040 --> 01:59:16.160
[Guest]: order.

01:59:16.160 --> 01:59:23.680
[Guest]: So the success of that generation of Hindu nationalism was that they did create a certain

01:59:23.680 --> 01:59:29.800
[Guest]: kind of at least internal peace with modernity, that, look, this is the trajectory inevitably

01:59:29.800 --> 01:59:32.360
[Guest]: we'll have to go down, right?

01:59:32.360 --> 01:59:38.640
[Guest]: As I said, I think the problem was that it was quite compatible with a certain kind of

01:59:38.640 --> 01:59:40.520
[Guest]: prejudice and hostility to Muslims.

01:59:40.520 --> 01:59:43.480
[Guest]: And by the way, you don't have to be Hindu nationalist to have that hostility and prejudices,

01:59:43.480 --> 01:59:44.480
[Guest]: you know.

01:59:44.480 --> 01:59:46.880
[Guest]: Many liberals can have that, right?

01:59:46.880 --> 01:59:55.040
[Guest]: And not being able to disentangle the ideological and constitutional aspects from where does

01:59:55.040 --> 01:59:59.360
[Guest]: the shading to just becoming a prejudiced against the other, I just don't like you for

01:59:59.360 --> 02:00:00.360
[Guest]: who you are.

02:00:00.360 --> 02:00:03.080
[Guest]: It's nothing, you know, it's nothing that you do.

02:00:03.080 --> 02:00:06.160
[Guest]: You're just very being poses a threat for me, right?

02:00:06.160 --> 02:00:08.720
[Guest]: I think that's just an autonomous dynamic.

02:00:08.720 --> 02:00:13.240
[Guest]: But yes, I mean, you're right that I think Nehru became that kind of indispensable figure

02:00:13.240 --> 02:00:19.600
[Guest]: where even these Hindu nationalists sort of recognize that for the kind of progressivism

02:00:19.600 --> 02:00:24.920
[Guest]: they had in mind internally, it needed to be embodied in a figure who was, you know,

02:00:24.920 --> 02:00:28.120
[Guest]: more constitutional in some ways than they were.

02:00:28.120 --> 02:00:32.440
[Amit Varma]: No, and I did, you know, when I framed the question, I didn't mean the term Hindu nationalist

02:00:32.440 --> 02:00:36.560
[Amit Varma]: in a pejorative sense, but in these modern times, it comes across like that.

02:00:36.560 --> 02:00:41.680
[Amit Varma]: So my next question, and this might be a little long winded, I'll begin by quoting something

02:00:41.680 --> 02:00:46.720
[Amit Varma]: that you have written in your excellent book, The Burden of Democracy, where you wrote,

02:00:46.720 --> 02:00:51.200
[Amit Varma]: quote, if the faith reposed in democracy was unique to India, the style in which government

02:00:51.200 --> 02:00:52.960
[Amit Varma]: was imagined was anything but.

02:00:52.960 --> 02:00:57.440
[Amit Varma]: The entire colonial state apparatus with its laws, conventions, ubiquitous rules, faith

02:00:57.440 --> 02:01:02.280
[Amit Varma]: and the impartiality of the few good men that comprise the state was taken over almost intact.

02:01:02.280 --> 02:01:07.520
[Amit Varma]: To be sure, the state was now to be used for nationalist ends to secure India's territorial

02:01:07.520 --> 02:01:11.480
[Amit Varma]: integrity to spread and implement the development mission of the new regime.

02:01:11.480 --> 02:01:16.640
[Amit Varma]: But the relationship between the state apparatus to whatever ends it was going to be displayed

02:01:16.640 --> 02:01:21.120
[Amit Varma]: and democracy was going to forever remain contentious, stop quote.

02:01:21.120 --> 02:01:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And again, when one looks at the Constituent Assembly debates, you have Somnath Lahiri

02:01:25.600 --> 02:01:29.960
[Amit Varma]: pointing exactly this out, where he talks about, you know, the fundamental rights, the

02:01:29.960 --> 02:01:34.240
[Amit Varma]: way they've been framed with the caveats immediately following where Lahiri says, quote, I feel

02:01:34.240 --> 02:01:38.680
[Amit Varma]: that many of these fundamental rights have been framed from the point of view of a police

02:01:38.680 --> 02:01:39.680
[Amit Varma]: constable.

02:01:39.680 --> 02:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I find that many minimal rights are conceded and are almost invariably followed by a provision

02:01:45.000 --> 02:01:49.560
[Amit Varma]: which takes away a right almost completely, stop quote.

02:01:49.560 --> 02:01:58.160
[Amit Varma]: And my sort of question here is that, does the design of the state then shape the culture

02:01:58.160 --> 02:02:00.860
[Amit Varma]: and shape society itself?

02:02:00.860 --> 02:02:05.300
[Amit Varma]: For example, in the same book, you later talk about how the structural inequalities within

02:02:05.300 --> 02:02:09.400
[Amit Varma]: society can shape the self and I'll quote that bit as well, quote, that inequality and

02:02:09.400 --> 02:02:13.840
[Amit Varma]: our relations to the state are not simply structural injustices, they also profoundly

02:02:13.840 --> 02:02:16.720
[Amit Varma]: shape our sense of self and social possibilities.

02:02:16.720 --> 02:02:21.400
[Amit Varma]: It is a peculiar sense of the self in relation to others that social inequality and the state

02:02:21.400 --> 02:02:25.640
[Amit Varma]: have produced that gives Indian politics its texture, stop quote.

02:02:25.640 --> 02:02:32.160
[Amit Varma]: And this is sort of, you know, it is my thinking that the design of the state that the founders

02:02:32.160 --> 02:02:37.240
[Amit Varma]: chose, a lot of it through inertia, where you just take over the colonial apparatus

02:02:37.240 --> 02:02:44.040
[Amit Varma]: and took over, you know, so much of the IPC and didn't safeguard fundamental rights strongly

02:02:44.040 --> 02:02:46.160
[Amit Varma]: enough in the constitution.

02:02:46.160 --> 02:02:52.360
[Amit Varma]: What that did was that it centralized power, it made the state very powerful.

02:02:52.360 --> 02:02:58.440
[Amit Varma]: And I think from the point of view of a citizen, I think of the matrix of possibilities for

02:02:58.440 --> 02:03:05.040
[Amit Varma]: how an individual can get ahead and what happens in those sort of what the design of the state

02:03:05.040 --> 02:03:11.200
[Amit Varma]: then almost incentivizes is that you get ahead by manipulating the state by getting yourself

02:03:11.200 --> 02:03:17.700
[Amit Varma]: in rent seeking positions by using the coercive power of the state to your ends, and not so

02:03:17.700 --> 02:03:23.160
[Amit Varma]: much through voluntary action within society, which is a positive some game, you know, Jagdish

02:03:23.160 --> 02:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Bhagwati once pointed out, I think, around 2000 that, you know, China has a profit seeking

02:03:28.480 --> 02:03:31.560
[Amit Varma]: mindset and India has a rent seeking mindset.

02:03:31.560 --> 02:03:36.440
[Amit Varma]: And mind, you know, one of the conjectures, one of my conjectures for why that might be

02:03:36.440 --> 02:03:42.520
[Amit Varma]: so is the design of our institutions, where the easiest way, at least for many decades

02:03:42.520 --> 02:03:46.880
[Amit Varma]: to make a fast buck to get ahead in India was to become part of the state apparatus

02:03:46.880 --> 02:03:51.400
[Amit Varma]: and use some of the coercive power of the state, which is a zero sum game, rather than

02:03:51.400 --> 02:03:56.320
[Amit Varma]: rely on voluntary action within society, which is basically what actual free markets instead

02:03:56.320 --> 02:04:00.060
[Amit Varma]: of the markets we've had for most of this time, would enable.

02:04:00.060 --> 02:04:04.760
[Amit Varma]: So what do you think about this, like, is the design of the state, something that has

02:04:04.760 --> 02:04:11.880
[Amit Varma]: fundamentally changed society and shaped culture itself, just by the way it was conceived or

02:04:11.880 --> 02:04:15.080
[Amit Varma]: not conceived in the sense that we just took over the colonial apparatus?

02:04:15.080 --> 02:04:18.040
[Guest]: Oh, this is a large and profound question.

02:04:18.040 --> 02:04:21.640
[Guest]: And I think I'll divide the answer into three different aspects of the state because I think

02:04:21.640 --> 02:04:23.880
[Guest]: logic operates differently.

02:04:23.880 --> 02:04:27.520
[Guest]: But I do have to say, I think, you know, while I understand the spirit of Jagdish's quote,

02:04:27.520 --> 02:04:30.440
[Guest]: I think it's hard to argue that China is also not rent-seeking.

02:04:30.440 --> 02:04:36.880
[Guest]: I mean, in fact, maybe they're smarter about how they do it, but the scale is actually

02:04:36.880 --> 02:04:40.400
[Guest]: of a different, staggeringly different order.

02:04:40.400 --> 02:04:45.920
[Guest]: So I think I'll divide your question into three different bits, three different parts

02:04:45.920 --> 02:04:47.880
[Guest]: of the state.

02:04:47.880 --> 02:04:54.240
[Guest]: One which I think you began alluding to, which is in the realm of civil liberties, right?

02:04:54.240 --> 02:05:01.240
[Guest]: We retained large parts of the criminal code, IPC, section 295, we retained sedition law,

02:05:01.240 --> 02:05:06.080
[Guest]: I think, most scandalously, the Supreme Court's great leeway to the state over Armed Forces

02:05:06.080 --> 02:05:10.680
[Guest]: Special Powers Act, the early judgments in Gopalan.

02:05:10.680 --> 02:05:20.120
[Guest]: Now there, I actually do think that even though it was only episodically used, the culture

02:05:20.120 --> 02:05:27.600
[Guest]: and opening that we created for easy violations of civil rights, I think then set a template

02:05:27.600 --> 02:05:29.520
[Guest]: that which is used later on.

02:05:29.520 --> 02:05:34.440
[Guest]: And you could argue, look, again, don't make this judgment in hindsight, you've just come

02:05:34.440 --> 02:05:35.440
[Guest]: out of partition.

02:05:35.440 --> 02:05:40.160
[Guest]: We can't even actually in a sense imagine, I mean, and Nehru says this, I mean, the last

02:05:40.160 --> 02:05:44.760
[Guest]: parts of discovery of India, there's this extraordinary, none of us have any idea what

02:05:44.760 --> 02:05:46.680
[Guest]: India is going to look like, right?

02:05:46.680 --> 02:05:51.800
[Guest]: I mean, we just suffered this extraordinary trauma, which they weren't in a position of

02:05:51.800 --> 02:05:52.800
[Guest]: understanding.

02:05:52.800 --> 02:05:56.320
[Guest]: But I don't think that that excuses the full extent.

02:05:56.320 --> 02:06:01.040
[Guest]: I do slightly disagree with you a little bit on this whole question of sort of the limitations

02:06:01.040 --> 02:06:06.080
[Guest]: to rights in the Indian constitutions, particularly in freedom of expression and so forth.

02:06:06.080 --> 02:06:09.200
[Guest]: Because there are two ways of looking at that limitation, right?

02:06:09.200 --> 02:06:13.560
[Guest]: One is that, you know, you could actually say that, look, and I think that was the intent

02:06:13.560 --> 02:06:21.880
[Guest]: behind those limitations is, inevitably, these things will end up coming to court, right?

02:06:21.880 --> 02:06:27.280
[Guest]: And somebody will say something, you know, outrageous.

02:06:27.280 --> 02:06:33.040
[Guest]: And I think, as Madhav Khosla's book has pointed out, that one of the reasons you probably

02:06:33.040 --> 02:06:38.160
[Guest]: have a little bit of excess codification in the Indian constitution is because the framers

02:06:38.160 --> 02:06:43.520
[Guest]: wanted to make sure that there were only particular kinds of limitations and questions that generally

02:06:43.520 --> 02:06:45.200
[Guest]: a judge is actually asked.

02:06:45.200 --> 02:06:49.480
[Guest]: It's not just sort of random, you know, there's the reverse danger, right?

02:06:49.480 --> 02:06:53.200
[Guest]: And by the way, I mean, if you take free speech, for example, I mean, just to again, put it

02:06:53.200 --> 02:06:58.320
[Guest]: in perspective, you know, the American constitution's record, even to the late 50s, was as appalling

02:06:58.320 --> 02:06:59.880
[Guest]: as the Indian states was.

02:06:59.880 --> 02:07:04.580
[Guest]: I mean, you know, pacifists were still being arrested in 1920s, 1930s.

02:07:04.580 --> 02:07:06.720
[Guest]: So it's, I think, a tricky thing.

02:07:06.720 --> 02:07:07.720
[Guest]: But I actually agree with you.

02:07:07.720 --> 02:07:11.720
[Guest]: I mean, I think on a couple of things like sedition and so forth, there's just no excuse

02:07:11.720 --> 02:07:14.800
[Guest]: for what we put in the text of the constitution.

02:07:14.800 --> 02:07:20.400
[Guest]: And I think then creating a culture, I think, in the judiciary that, frankly, does not ask

02:07:20.400 --> 02:07:24.800
[Guest]: any questions of the state, when it comes to the exercise of executive power or civil

02:07:24.800 --> 02:07:25.800
[Guest]: liberties.

02:07:25.800 --> 02:07:29.920
[Guest]: It didn't ask it in the 50s, in the emergency, and certainly not asking it now.

02:07:29.920 --> 02:07:34.680
[Guest]: I think there's a second dimension to the state, which is where you are coming from,

02:07:34.680 --> 02:07:39.880
[Guest]: where I have most sympathy with your argument, I think Jagdish's position, you know, no matter

02:07:39.880 --> 02:07:47.560
[Guest]: what anybody says, most of us are supporters of the 1991 economic reforms, where it was

02:07:47.560 --> 02:07:55.320
[Guest]: certainly the case that the state created this absolute intricate and self-reinforcing

02:07:55.320 --> 02:08:02.120
[Guest]: web of patronage and corruption, which corroded political and social life and stymied economic

02:08:02.120 --> 02:08:04.480
[Guest]: efficiency in ways that we cannot even imagine.

02:08:04.480 --> 02:08:05.480
[Guest]: No two ways about it.

02:08:05.480 --> 02:08:11.840
[Guest]: Now, again, I think a little bit of historical perspective, which is that some of it, I think,

02:08:11.840 --> 02:08:12.840
[Guest]: was inevitable.

02:08:12.840 --> 02:08:17.600
[Guest]: I mean, look, we forget in 1947, right, when we had a foreign exchange crisis, there is

02:08:17.600 --> 02:08:20.680
[Guest]: virtually no domestic capital to speak of.

02:08:20.680 --> 02:08:27.600
[Guest]: I mean, capital as we understand it doesn't in a sense exist, right, in some senses, right?

02:08:27.600 --> 02:08:31.480
[Guest]: There's no market in some senses that we speak of, right?

02:08:31.480 --> 02:08:37.600
[Guest]: And there are no capabilities, because the one thing the British colonialism was not

02:08:37.600 --> 02:08:38.840
[Guest]: was a development colonialism.

02:08:38.840 --> 02:08:43.240
[Guest]: I mean, I think my old teacher, Mr. Atul Kohli, has argued this very powerfully.

02:08:43.240 --> 02:08:50.480
[Guest]: I mean, the British state was interested in keeping order, extracting enough, using tariffs

02:08:50.480 --> 02:08:53.480
[Guest]: and other things to give Britain a trade advantage, and that was about it, right?

02:08:53.480 --> 02:08:58.080
[Guest]: There was no serious developmental investment.

02:08:58.080 --> 02:09:05.720
[Guest]: So to that extent, it was inevitable that the state would have to be the locus of some

02:09:05.720 --> 02:09:12.760
[Guest]: kind of collective action, because development requires us doing things, not just letting

02:09:12.760 --> 02:09:14.680
[Guest]: people free to do things.

02:09:14.680 --> 02:09:18.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's okay to say that, you know, you have the freedom to invest, but if there is

02:09:18.480 --> 02:09:22.460
[Guest]: zero capital, right, where do you go?

02:09:22.460 --> 02:09:27.360
[Guest]: But even there, I would support you, which is that I do think at least even as early

02:09:27.360 --> 02:09:31.320
[Guest]: as the late 50s, I think direction should have been clearer, that particularly in domestic

02:09:31.320 --> 02:09:36.240
[Guest]: industrial production, the license permit charges, we call it, needed to be in a sense

02:09:36.240 --> 02:09:37.240
[Guest]: dismantled.

02:09:37.240 --> 02:09:44.040
[Guest]: It also had the consequence of becoming enmeshed in our electoral economy.

02:09:44.040 --> 02:09:49.080
[Guest]: So you know, that was, those were the rents that then sustained political coalition and

02:09:49.080 --> 02:09:51.480
[Guest]: so forth.

02:09:51.480 --> 02:09:54.840
[Guest]: So I think on that, I'm in agreement with you, and I think my big worry is that we are

02:09:54.840 --> 02:09:57.400
[Guest]: actually going to go back to the bad old days of the 70s.

02:09:57.400 --> 02:10:02.720
[Guest]: I think there's going to be too much sort of, in some senses, discretion in the allocation

02:10:02.720 --> 02:10:06.840
[Guest]: of capital of the kind that we witnessed in the 70s.

02:10:06.840 --> 02:10:12.800
[Guest]: But the third area, and to me, this is the biggest, frankly, failure of the industry,

02:10:12.800 --> 02:10:20.920
[Guest]: because other ones were correctable in some ways, was in order for markets to function,

02:10:20.920 --> 02:10:26.760
[Guest]: right, there need to be certain baseline necessary conditions in place, right?

02:10:26.760 --> 02:10:32.920
[Guest]: If India is to be competitive, you need logistics, you need energy, you need education, right?

02:10:32.920 --> 02:10:36.960
[Guest]: Even Hayek thought you need public health, right?

02:10:36.960 --> 02:10:42.840
[Guest]: And the irony of the Indian state in the 1950s and 60s was that the place where it needed

02:10:42.840 --> 02:10:49.480
[Guest]: to have a more effective catalyzing role was the place where it unconscionably failed the

02:10:49.480 --> 02:10:51.880
[Guest]: most, right?

02:10:51.880 --> 02:10:55.960
[Guest]: And actually then creating decades of distrust about the state.

02:10:55.960 --> 02:10:58.480
[Guest]: So you got the worst of both worlds, right?

02:10:58.480 --> 02:11:05.800
[Guest]: You didn't get deficiencies of an entrepreneurial culture, but you did not get, I mean, and

02:11:05.800 --> 02:11:09.560
[Guest]: this is one difference between India and communist China, the one difference between India and,

02:11:09.560 --> 02:11:13.480
[Guest]: you know, the Soviet Union and other communist countries, you actually did not for years

02:11:13.480 --> 02:11:19.800
[Guest]: and years, a few IITs apart and so forth, get the human capital infrastructure energy

02:11:19.800 --> 02:11:20.800
[Guest]: base.

02:11:20.800 --> 02:11:23.600
[Guest]: I mean, one thing we forget about the Chinese state, that's what it does, right?

02:11:23.600 --> 02:11:30.560
[Guest]: It's not just a free market, it did manage to educate its population faster than we did.

02:11:30.560 --> 02:11:35.120
[Guest]: It did manage to create the collective goods that are required for competitiveness, particularly

02:11:35.120 --> 02:11:36.120
[Guest]: infrastructure.

02:11:36.120 --> 02:11:40.040
[Guest]: I mean, even now with Atmir Barbarat, the thing that worries me is nobody asks you what

02:11:40.040 --> 02:11:42.560
[Guest]: makes an economy competitive, right?

02:11:42.560 --> 02:11:45.800
[Guest]: Costs, energy costs, logistic costs, right?

02:11:45.800 --> 02:11:48.240
[Guest]: Human capital costs.

02:11:48.240 --> 02:11:52.680
[Guest]: These are the basic places where I think the state needed to have a role.

02:11:52.680 --> 02:11:57.880
[Guest]: And these are the places in which the way which the state ended up being designed was

02:11:57.880 --> 02:11:59.240
[Guest]: a catastrophe.

02:11:59.240 --> 02:12:06.520
[Guest]: I think education being the prime example where it wasn't so much that, I mean, I lay

02:12:06.520 --> 02:12:13.400
[Guest]: my cards on the table in this, which is, I actually do think you need good and effective

02:12:13.400 --> 02:12:14.960
[Guest]: forms of public education.

02:12:14.960 --> 02:12:20.560
[Guest]: There are very few examples in the world of societies sort of not being able to, or being

02:12:20.560 --> 02:12:24.800
[Guest]: able to educate their population without public education.

02:12:24.800 --> 02:12:30.680
[Guest]: But the form in which you design the education system where, for example, teachers' unions

02:12:30.680 --> 02:12:36.280
[Guest]: got enmeshed in the political process, I mean, it was a disaster waiting to happen.

02:12:36.280 --> 02:12:42.720
[Guest]: And in some senses, a lot of the privatization that happens in India does not happen because

02:12:42.720 --> 02:12:45.600
[Guest]: of the first principles that you are talking about.

02:12:45.600 --> 02:12:50.760
[Guest]: It's simply, okay, because there's state failure, let's go to the market, except that the conditions

02:12:50.760 --> 02:12:54.680
[Guest]: for making the market succeed, right?

02:12:54.680 --> 02:13:01.800
[Guest]: As Adam Smith said, light but effective regulation still don't exist in many areas, right?

02:13:01.800 --> 02:13:05.640
[Guest]: The last and final thing I'd say about this, and I think for those of us who are particularly

02:13:05.640 --> 02:13:11.920
[Guest]: worried about economic reform, as I'm sure you are, right, you know, the challenge which

02:13:11.920 --> 02:13:18.080
[Guest]: we haven't solved is the relationship of Indian capital to Indian politics, right?

02:13:18.080 --> 02:13:23.600
[Guest]: So one, I'll be very honest with you, I think the Indian capital itself has been a relatively

02:13:23.600 --> 02:13:24.600
[Guest]: unenlightened group.

02:13:24.600 --> 02:13:30.560
[Guest]: I mean, even now, when their back is against the wall, I mean, you know, 3% growth, as

02:13:30.560 --> 02:13:35.000
[Guest]: Marx would have said, they're just not thinking as a class for itself, sometimes, which they

02:13:35.000 --> 02:13:38.280
[Guest]: would actually, I mean, at least on their own terms, right?

02:13:38.280 --> 02:13:43.200
[Guest]: But I have something more in mind in the relationship between capital and politics, which is, because

02:13:43.200 --> 02:13:50.760
[Guest]: politics depended on certain forms of resource generation, the close connections between

02:13:50.760 --> 02:13:55.400
[Guest]: capital and politics ended up undermining both, right?

02:13:55.400 --> 02:13:58.600
[Guest]: A lot of reforms didn't happen because incumbent capital didn't want it.

02:13:58.600 --> 02:14:00.600
[Guest]: I mean, that was Indira Gandhi's model in some ways, right?

02:14:00.600 --> 02:14:02.960
[Guest]: I mean, it wasn't that she was anti-capital.

02:14:02.960 --> 02:14:07.000
[Guest]: It's just that like, the builders are, you know, periodically throwing out money.

02:14:07.000 --> 02:14:14.000
[Guest]: I was once reading the KGB archives, published archives, just kind of randomly, and the extraordinary

02:14:14.000 --> 02:14:19.640
[Guest]: fascinating thing in the 70s, right, where, you know, Pranab Mukherjee, Raghuram Iyer,

02:14:19.640 --> 02:14:25.040
[Guest]: stalwarts of the Congress are kind of mediating with the Russians on the rupee ruble trade

02:14:25.040 --> 02:14:26.840
[Guest]: for the supply of tobacco, right?

02:14:26.840 --> 02:14:33.120
[Guest]: I mean, you know, and you can guess what the main objective of that mediation was.

02:14:33.120 --> 02:14:45.280
[Guest]: So in some senses, the Indian state has always thought it necessary to control capital enough.

02:14:45.280 --> 02:14:54.160
[Guest]: What happened in 1991 was we unleashed liberalization in some sectors, because we said there are

02:14:54.160 --> 02:14:58.440
[Guest]: rents to be collected elsewhere, factor markets in particular, and now what you could do in

02:14:58.440 --> 02:15:02.960
[Guest]: factor markets was just mind-boggling, right?

02:15:02.960 --> 02:15:08.480
[Guest]: And that's the crisis that came to haunt us in UPA2, right, where just at the moment where

02:15:08.480 --> 02:15:14.480
[Guest]: Indian capital was being legitimized, finally, right, you suddenly have this public perception

02:15:14.480 --> 02:15:19.400
[Guest]: that Indian capital is broken all the way down, because factor markets are broken.

02:15:19.400 --> 02:15:25.920
[Guest]: Credit, right, I mean, this is one thing which very few in India have paid attention to,

02:15:25.920 --> 02:15:30.960
[Guest]: and I think Jagdish Bhagwati there was right, I think Arvind Subramaniam's original arguments

02:15:30.960 --> 02:15:36.640
[Guest]: were right, which is we just didn't pay enough attention to finance, and the way in which

02:15:36.640 --> 02:15:42.640
[Guest]: the structures of financialization, right, create this deeply unhealthy relationship

02:15:42.640 --> 02:15:47.960
[Guest]: between state and capital, to the point where the capital itself can't be a counterweight

02:15:47.960 --> 02:15:50.840
[Guest]: to the state, because it's so dependent on it.

02:15:50.840 --> 02:15:54.200
[Guest]: And frankly, we are entering an even more exalted phase of that again.

02:15:54.200 --> 02:15:58.440
[Guest]: I mean, I think what you're going to get in the next 5-10 years is you're going to get

02:15:58.440 --> 02:16:04.960
[Guest]: greater and greater concentrations of capital, in part produced by unfair regulatory arbitrage

02:16:04.960 --> 02:16:13.320
[Guest]: by the state, right, and because capital allocation is actually what matters to markets, it's

02:16:13.320 --> 02:16:19.680
[Guest]: going to distort the opportunities of lots of small, medium, genuine entrepreneurs, right.

02:16:19.680 --> 02:16:24.280
[Guest]: So we just haven't got that state-capital relationship right.

02:16:24.280 --> 02:16:30.120
[Guest]: And I think, to be honest, I think the problem is at both ends, because it's also that incumbent

02:16:30.120 --> 02:16:37.120
[Guest]: holders of capital will continue to subsidize, not just because it's in their individual

02:16:37.120 --> 02:16:41.920
[Guest]: interest that I can understand, but I think even in the way in which they articulate what

02:16:41.920 --> 02:16:44.480
[Guest]: their demands are, right.

02:16:44.480 --> 02:16:50.680
[Guest]: And it's going to therefore both going to distort our politics and the structure of

02:16:50.680 --> 02:16:52.240
[Guest]: Indian capitalism.

02:16:52.240 --> 02:16:57.240
[Amit Varma]: So I have four observations to make on these very insightful thoughts of yours.

02:16:57.240 --> 02:17:01.080
[Amit Varma]: But before that, first, I'll just inform my listeners that I had a great episode with

02:17:01.080 --> 02:17:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Madhav Khosla on his book, India's founding moment, and we discussed this there.

02:17:05.280 --> 02:17:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And I'll continue to be a little skeptical about the rationale of those caveats about

02:17:09.400 --> 02:17:12.520
[Amit Varma]: limitations or limitations, I'm not quite sure of that.

02:17:12.520 --> 02:17:18.160
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, observation one, I'm kind of struck by the paradox that we have

02:17:18.160 --> 02:17:20.760
[Amit Varma]: both lost faith in the state.

02:17:20.760 --> 02:17:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And yet, you know, there's almost a religion around the state in the sense that one, we

02:17:25.480 --> 02:17:30.320
[Amit Varma]: don't expect the state to do anything for us, we kind of exist in spite of the state

02:17:30.320 --> 02:17:33.240
[Amit Varma]: because there is no rule of law anywhere, for example.

02:17:33.240 --> 02:17:36.920
[Amit Varma]: And that might be one reason, for example, that the performance of the current government

02:17:36.920 --> 02:17:41.240
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter at all, the approval ratings are super high, because people just have completely

02:17:41.240 --> 02:17:46.720
[Amit Varma]: disassociated what is happening in their lives and the governance they're getting with whoever

02:17:46.720 --> 02:17:47.720
[Amit Varma]: is in charge.

02:17:47.720 --> 02:17:52.160
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, that's paradoxical, because whenever anything goes wrong, and

02:17:52.160 --> 02:17:57.240
[Amit Varma]: an Indian wants something to change, their instinctive response is that the state should

02:17:57.240 --> 02:18:01.920
[Amit Varma]: do this, that the state should pass a law or the state should fund this or whatever.

02:18:01.920 --> 02:18:07.640
[Amit Varma]: And this is a paradox, I kind of struggled to get my head around, there's a disconnect

02:18:07.640 --> 02:18:08.640
[Amit Varma]: here.

02:18:08.640 --> 02:18:12.560
[Amit Varma]: My second observation is that, you know, what you said about education, in fact, I just

02:18:12.560 --> 02:18:17.080
[Amit Varma]: had a great episode on this with Karthik Muralidharan, which was 20 minutes long.

02:18:17.080 --> 02:18:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the things I'd like to say is that I don't think there is a binary

02:18:20.600 --> 02:18:23.800
[Amit Varma]: between public education and private provision.

02:18:23.800 --> 02:18:28.200
[Amit Varma]: What I have always been in favor of is that by all means, we have public education, but

02:18:28.200 --> 02:18:33.080
[Amit Varma]: also allow private education, you know, allow private entrepreneurs to set up schools for

02:18:33.080 --> 02:18:38.120
[Amit Varma]: profit, don't set conditions, and all of that, just make it easy for them, which doesn't

02:18:38.120 --> 02:18:39.760
[Amit Varma]: mean you do away with public education.

02:18:39.760 --> 02:18:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And my contention is that just as we saw in 91, that you freed up telecom, you freed up

02:18:44.880 --> 02:18:50.120
[Amit Varma]: airlines, and we can see the difference that competition made in those areas where you

02:18:50.120 --> 02:18:55.480
[Amit Varma]: can buy a mobile phone today for 600 rupees and access is so democratized and easily available

02:18:55.480 --> 02:18:57.160
[Amit Varma]: and nobody misses MTNL.

02:18:57.160 --> 02:18:59.200
[Amit Varma]: I suspect same would happen to education.

02:18:59.200 --> 02:19:03.880
[Amit Varma]: But even if it doesn't keep the public education going, you don't need to constrain private

02:19:03.880 --> 02:19:04.880
[Amit Varma]: entrepreneurs.

02:19:04.880 --> 02:19:08.140
[Amit Varma]: And I think this was a one fundamental flaw in the design of the state that even back

02:19:08.140 --> 02:19:11.480
[Amit Varma]: in the day, fine, there is no capital, you need to build industries.

02:19:11.480 --> 02:19:15.960
[Amit Varma]: But you don't stop others from doing all this stuff, you leave that space for them.

02:19:15.960 --> 02:19:20.160
[Amit Varma]: My third observation was what you said about capital and politics, where first, I'd like

02:19:20.160 --> 02:19:24.320
[Amit Varma]: to draw the distinction that what is good for capitalists is often not good for the

02:19:24.320 --> 02:19:30.440
[Amit Varma]: people that, you know, Milton Friedman drew a distinction between pro-business and pro-markets.

02:19:30.440 --> 02:19:35.880
[Amit Varma]: And I remember Ram Guha once making the argument in his book India after Gandhi, where he spoke

02:19:35.880 --> 02:19:42.240
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, the Bombay Plan, and how, sort of, you know, in the 40s, so many businessmen

02:19:42.240 --> 02:19:44.680
[Amit Varma]: were for Nehru's state led model.

02:19:44.680 --> 02:19:47.560
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, of course, they would be they wanted protectionism, they wanted to

02:19:47.560 --> 02:19:53.080
[Amit Varma]: protect their sort of area, which is why, you know, what is good for big businesses,

02:19:53.080 --> 02:19:55.160
[Amit Varma]: not necessarily good for markets.

02:19:55.160 --> 02:19:58.640
[Amit Varma]: But the other point there about money and power, that is something that I feel fairly

02:19:58.640 --> 02:20:02.240
[Amit Varma]: strongly about is that yes, of course, there is a vicious circle between money and power,

02:20:02.240 --> 02:20:05.560
[Amit Varma]: money will always chase power and use it to generate more money.

02:20:05.560 --> 02:20:06.560
[Amit Varma]: That's the nature of the game.

02:20:06.560 --> 02:20:10.840
[Amit Varma]: I think there is only one way to break that, which is not by demonizing big money, but

02:20:10.840 --> 02:20:15.460
[Amit Varma]: which is instead by reducing the power of the state, to the extent that it no longer

02:20:15.460 --> 02:20:18.840
[Amit Varma]: makes sense for big money to chase that power.

02:20:18.840 --> 02:20:23.160
[Amit Varma]: Instead, a big industrialist will say, how can I make money, I have to make it by creating

02:20:23.160 --> 02:20:27.680
[Amit Varma]: better products and by competing better, because I cannot use the coercive power of the state

02:20:27.680 --> 02:20:32.400
[Amit Varma]: to stop my competitors or do anti-competitive things.

02:20:32.400 --> 02:20:33.960
[Amit Varma]: That was observation number three.

02:20:33.960 --> 02:20:36.360
[Guest]: I'm sorry if this is a bit off.

02:20:36.360 --> 02:20:41.200
[Amit Varma]: And my fourth one is really a sort of a question that comes from this question of the design

02:20:41.200 --> 02:20:47.000
[Amit Varma]: of the state, which is that when the BJP took over in 2014, from the Congress, at one level,

02:20:47.000 --> 02:20:49.560
[Amit Varma]: it seems like a very fundamental shift.

02:20:49.560 --> 02:20:53.960
[Amit Varma]: I phrased it perhaps almost too grandiosely by saying that politics has finally caught

02:20:53.960 --> 02:20:55.740
[Amit Varma]: up with culture or whatever.

02:20:55.740 --> 02:21:00.520
[Amit Varma]: You have referred to it as something that could, you know, reverse India's progress

02:21:00.520 --> 02:21:04.280
[Amit Varma]: to a point where the damage may be irreversible.

02:21:04.280 --> 02:21:12.120
[Amit Varma]: But my larger sort of observation here is that just as independent India led to a takeover

02:21:12.120 --> 02:21:17.960
[Amit Varma]: of a colonial apparatus by rulers with a different, you know, color of skin, similarly, it might

02:21:17.960 --> 02:21:24.560
[Amit Varma]: be the case that in 2014, what simply happened was that the BJP took over an identical state

02:21:24.560 --> 02:21:25.560
[Amit Varma]: apparatus.

02:21:25.560 --> 02:21:29.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the laws under which all of these people, vada vada rao and all these guys have

02:21:29.120 --> 02:21:33.840
[Amit Varma]: been arrested are laws framed by the UPA, which many of them were arrested under in

02:21:33.840 --> 02:21:35.080
[Amit Varma]: the past.

02:21:35.080 --> 02:21:38.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it is really same old, same old, it's a different bunch of people with

02:21:38.320 --> 02:21:40.240
[Amit Varma]: slightly different imperatives.

02:21:40.240 --> 02:21:44.320
[Amit Varma]: But the fundamental flaw, which was a flaw in the conception and design of the state

02:21:44.320 --> 02:21:45.320
[Amit Varma]: still remains.

02:21:45.320 --> 02:21:51.040
[Guest]: So I think to observe, I mean, I broadly agree with you, but I think the readers will have

02:21:51.040 --> 02:21:56.480
[Guest]: more fun if we disagree a little bit, at least the nuances, I think two things, right?

02:21:56.480 --> 02:22:01.040
[Guest]: So one, I think on your last point, which I think is fair enough, I mean, I do think

02:22:01.040 --> 02:22:06.560
[Guest]: one of the things we need to reflect about the fact is that the BJP did not need to create

02:22:06.560 --> 02:22:13.760
[Guest]: any new law to, in a sense, impose its authority in our communal designs, right?

02:22:13.760 --> 02:22:18.880
[Guest]: But I think there is a second part of the culture story that we often don't reflect

02:22:18.880 --> 02:22:25.240
[Guest]: on enough, which is every constitution needs to be made to work.

02:22:25.240 --> 02:22:32.440
[Guest]: I mean, if only design produced, and in fact, the more I studied public history, I used

02:22:32.440 --> 02:22:38.560
[Guest]: to actually believe a lot in institutional design and still do, obviously, design matters,

02:22:38.560 --> 02:22:43.400
[Guest]: internal incentives matter, structures of accountability matter.

02:22:43.400 --> 02:22:51.880
[Guest]: But one of the sobering lessons of history is you can have all those design features.

02:22:51.880 --> 02:22:59.520
[Guest]: But if the aims of that new constitution are not internalized by its principal functionaries,

02:22:59.520 --> 02:23:00.520
[Guest]: it's not going to work.

02:23:00.520 --> 02:23:02.520
[Guest]: I think the Indian Supreme Court is a perfect example.

02:23:02.520 --> 02:23:07.960
[Guest]: I mean, it's one thing to say, look, there is a law, sedition law still on the books.

02:23:07.960 --> 02:23:10.520
[Guest]: It's another thing to say when the Supreme Court says, we are not going to give you a

02:23:10.520 --> 02:23:13.040
[Guest]: habeas corpus hearing for a year.

02:23:13.040 --> 02:23:16.280
[Guest]: I mean, there's no conceivable constraint there.

02:23:16.280 --> 02:23:21.120
[Guest]: I mean, now you can theorize post-retirement appointments, although I don't think, frankly,

02:23:21.120 --> 02:23:22.600
[Guest]: that's the issue here.

02:23:22.600 --> 02:23:28.240
[Guest]: So I actually do think that we are in this interesting moment, and one of the reasons

02:23:28.240 --> 02:23:33.560
[Guest]: I worry about a lot of the institutional design stuff is that sometimes it actually displaces

02:23:33.560 --> 02:23:35.560
[Guest]: individual responsibility as well.

02:23:35.560 --> 02:23:36.560
[Guest]: It becomes a convenient excuse.

02:23:36.560 --> 02:23:39.880
[Guest]: I mean, even the Supreme Court throws its hands up and says, this is how the constitution

02:23:39.880 --> 02:23:40.880
[Guest]: is.

02:23:40.880 --> 02:23:41.880
[Guest]: Of course, it's not like that.

02:23:41.880 --> 02:23:46.520
[Guest]: You can do a habeas corpus hearing tomorrow and, in a sense, render a judgment.

02:23:46.520 --> 02:23:52.840
[Guest]: And you know, constitutions are often, in a sense, destroyed by their elites, to be

02:23:52.840 --> 02:23:53.840
[Guest]: honest.

02:23:53.840 --> 02:23:54.840
[Guest]: I mean, the masses have certain grievances.

02:23:54.840 --> 02:24:02.960
[Guest]: And I think what we are witnessing, in a sense, is, for a variety of reasons, that elite destruction

02:24:02.960 --> 02:24:11.200
[Guest]: where even the most independent of institutions on paper are caving in ways that actually

02:24:11.200 --> 02:24:12.200
[Guest]: don't make sense.

02:24:12.200 --> 02:24:18.160
[Guest]: Even the United States, for example, is having the similar challenge where constitutional

02:24:18.160 --> 02:24:22.680
[Guest]: law scholars will say, you know, we can't go into class now and tell our kids what is

02:24:22.680 --> 02:24:26.120
[Guest]: the American constitution, right?

02:24:26.120 --> 02:24:31.200
[Guest]: So I do think we need to think about that aspect, right, going back to the human nature

02:24:31.200 --> 02:24:36.560
[Guest]: point of it, right, which is that think about the role of officials and all of this.

02:24:36.560 --> 02:24:40.200
[Guest]: The second thing I think I wanted to say, I agree with your point about kind of schooling

02:24:40.200 --> 02:24:41.200
[Guest]: and stuff.

02:24:41.200 --> 02:24:46.020
[Guest]: It's, you know, it can be done in a way in which it is neither, either or.

02:24:46.020 --> 02:24:50.400
[Guest]: But on this rent-seeking bit, and I think you're exactly right, which is that on first

02:24:50.400 --> 02:24:56.760
[Guest]: principles, if you keep the state out of business, business can be kept out of state.

02:24:56.760 --> 02:25:05.280
[Guest]: But here's the second sobering lesson, right, which is that if your image of where you can

02:25:05.280 --> 02:25:11.800
[Guest]: keep the state out is license per mitrage, kind of restrictions on production and, you

02:25:11.800 --> 02:25:15.800
[Guest]: know, restrictions on pricing, you're absolutely right.

02:25:15.800 --> 02:25:23.160
[Guest]: But any modern business is enmeshed in a different set of regulatory imperatives.

02:25:23.160 --> 02:25:27.200
[Guest]: So think of environmental regulation, for example, right now, you could, in principle,

02:25:27.200 --> 02:25:31.620
[Guest]: come up with a quotient solution, come up with a tort law penalty solution.

02:25:31.620 --> 02:25:37.840
[Guest]: But again, there is no regulatory place in the world, right, where the state will not

02:25:37.840 --> 02:25:44.920
[Guest]: have to take some decision, land as a scarce resource in some ways, right?

02:25:44.920 --> 02:25:45.920
[Guest]: Zoning is a state decision.

02:25:45.920 --> 02:25:52.040
[Guest]: I mean, we forget how much of the US political economy is simply a function of zoning, right?

02:25:52.040 --> 02:25:57.080
[Guest]: Okay, you have to do some coordination function in zoning, right?

02:25:57.080 --> 02:26:02.920
[Guest]: Now, what has unfortunately happened is that the weight of that corruption has shifted

02:26:02.920 --> 02:26:07.760
[Guest]: to all of these areas, or there's greater weight in these areas, these are always corrupt

02:26:07.760 --> 02:26:10.520
[Guest]: in some ways, right?

02:26:10.520 --> 02:26:13.320
[Guest]: Environmental regulation, factor markets, all of that.

02:26:13.320 --> 02:26:18.920
[Guest]: So even if all that you're saying is correct, I think in large areas of where you can think

02:26:18.920 --> 02:26:27.200
[Guest]: of deregulation, there is still enough important areas left, which are fundamental to businesses

02:26:27.200 --> 02:26:33.040
[Guest]: being able to operate, but also social good needed to be protected in some ways, that

02:26:33.040 --> 02:26:37.280
[Guest]: I don't think simply liberalization is going to be the whole answer.

02:26:37.280 --> 02:26:41.800
[Guest]: Because you, and that's exactly what we saw post 91, that, you know, I don't have to pay

02:26:41.800 --> 02:26:46.320
[Guest]: money now to get a phone, I don't have to pay money to get another industrial license.

02:26:46.320 --> 02:26:51.680
[Guest]: But I do have to pay money if I want to produce my water, or things of that kind, right?

02:26:51.680 --> 02:26:59.200
[Guest]: So we need to think smartly about where do we need to, right, produce regulation.

02:26:59.200 --> 02:27:06.600
[Guest]: And simply the narrative that if we simply got the state out of it, is actually not going

02:27:06.600 --> 02:27:08.480
[Guest]: to, you know, tell the whole story.

02:27:08.480 --> 02:27:12.640
[Amit Varma]: No, I actually agree with you. And this is probably where I come out of the closet as

02:27:12.640 --> 02:27:17.200
[Amit Varma]: a non libertarian, my purist friends would say, well, I'm not saying that, you know,

02:27:17.200 --> 02:27:20.800
[Amit Varma]: there should be no state regulation in areas like the environment, for example, because

02:27:20.800 --> 02:27:27.120
[Amit Varma]: it's very obvious that that's a place where you do need the state and even Gaussian solutions

02:27:27.120 --> 02:27:28.120
[Amit Varma]: won't always work.

02:27:28.120 --> 02:27:32.000
[Amit Varma]: But those are sort of kind of exceptional cases.

02:27:32.000 --> 02:27:33.320
[Amit Varma]: Let's take a quick commercial break.

02:27:33.320 --> 02:27:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And then when we come back, let's get down to talking about Indian politics itself and

02:27:37.840 --> 02:27:43.040
[Amit Varma]: how it has evolved in all this time.

02:27:43.040 --> 02:27:44.400
[Amit Varma]: Hi, I'm Vivek Kaur.

02:27:44.400 --> 02:27:45.400
[Amit Varma]: And I'm Amit Verma.

02:27:45.400 --> 02:27:49.800
[Amit Varma]: Here to tell you about a new weekly podcast that Vivek and I have launched called Econ

02:27:49.800 --> 02:27:50.800
[Unknown]: Central.

02:27:50.800 --> 02:27:56.960
[Unknown]: In Econ Central, we will help you make sense of the economic news of the last week.

02:27:56.960 --> 02:28:00.800
[Unknown]: And we'll also try to explain complex subjects in a simple language.

02:28:00.800 --> 02:28:05.720
[Amit Varma]: We will also take events outside the world of economics, like from politics, sports,

02:28:05.720 --> 02:28:10.200
[Amit Varma]: literature, and explain them through the lens of economic thinking.

02:28:10.200 --> 02:28:13.880
[Unknown]: Why is the stock market going up when the economy is going down?

02:28:13.880 --> 02:28:16.200
[Unknown]: What's the deal with high petrol prices?

02:28:16.200 --> 02:28:18.160
[Amit Varma]: Should we boycott Chinese goods?

02:28:18.160 --> 02:28:20.960
[Amit Varma]: What does free speech have to do with incentives?

02:28:20.960 --> 02:28:24.800
[Amit Varma]: Why are the roving bandits of Uttar Pradesh in competition with the biggest protection

02:28:24.800 --> 02:28:27.320
[Amit Varma]: racket out there, the Indian state?

02:28:27.320 --> 02:28:31.120
[Unknown]: All this and more in our new weekly podcast, Econ Central.

02:28:31.120 --> 02:28:35.760
[Amit Varma]: Econ Central launched a few weeks ago and is free on all podcast apps.

02:28:35.760 --> 02:28:40.720
[Amit Varma]: You can browse our archives at econcentral.in.

02:28:40.720 --> 02:28:44.480
[Unknown]: Econ Central, you have an incentive to listen.

02:28:44.480 --> 02:28:52.840
[Amit Varma]: Don't forget the URL, econcentral.in.

02:28:52.840 --> 02:28:54.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

02:28:54.200 --> 02:28:59.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm still talking with Pratap Bhanu Mehta about, you know, the state of our democracy

02:28:59.600 --> 02:29:02.560
[Amit Varma]: 73 years after we became independent.

02:29:02.560 --> 02:29:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I want to talk about politics right now.

02:29:05.880 --> 02:29:09.080
[Amit Varma]: And I want to, you know, I'll quote again from your book, The Burden of Democracy, where

02:29:09.080 --> 02:29:15.200
[Amit Varma]: at one point you said, quote, the imperatives of seeking sustainable majorities, most observers

02:29:15.200 --> 02:29:20.480
[Amit Varma]: argue, moderate even the most radical of movements, giving Indian politics a largely centrist

02:29:20.480 --> 02:29:22.880
[Amit Varma]: caste, stop quote.

02:29:22.880 --> 02:29:29.440
[Amit Varma]: And this is both, I would find profoundly true, and also is being profoundly challenged

02:29:29.440 --> 02:29:31.120
[Amit Varma]: in these modern times.

02:29:31.120 --> 02:29:34.080
[Amit Varma]: And I want your response to, you know, both of those.

02:29:34.080 --> 02:29:37.860
[Amit Varma]: One, I think it's, it's obviously profoundly true, because, you know, as we were discussing

02:29:37.860 --> 02:29:42.640
[Amit Varma]: before the show, the lens of left and right don't necessarily matter to, you know, in

02:29:42.640 --> 02:29:47.920
[Amit Varma]: India, because all parties when it comes to, you know, are sort of left of center when

02:29:47.920 --> 02:29:51.320
[Amit Varma]: it comes to economics, which is to say that their status and they believe in the heavy

02:29:51.320 --> 02:29:55.920
[Amit Varma]: hand of the state, and equally are right of center when it comes to society, as we can

02:29:55.920 --> 02:30:00.400
[Amit Varma]: see in these modern times, with even the Congress and the Aam Aadmi Party pandering to the same

02:30:00.400 --> 02:30:03.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of voter base, which the BJP seems to have lapped up.

02:30:03.560 --> 02:30:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, yeah, they are kind of similar, perhaps, because, you know, being skilled

02:30:09.000 --> 02:30:13.600
[Amit Varma]: politicians, they have an acute sense of what the culture is like, and maybe as that changes

02:30:13.600 --> 02:30:17.240
[Amit Varma]: over time, supply will adjust automatically to demand.

02:30:17.240 --> 02:30:22.840
[Amit Varma]: But the other aspect where it is being challenged is that what I find in modern politics, and

02:30:22.840 --> 02:30:29.880
[Amit Varma]: this is possibly something catalyzed by technology, is that there is a tendency to make people

02:30:29.880 --> 02:30:31.460
[Amit Varma]: more and more extreme.

02:30:31.460 --> 02:30:33.120
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of things here.

02:30:33.120 --> 02:30:38.920
[Amit Varma]: I think what technology has done is that it creates what Cass Sunstein calls group polarization,

02:30:38.920 --> 02:30:43.880
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, one, there might be preferences that you do not state in public because they're

02:30:43.880 --> 02:30:50.840
[Amit Varma]: not considered polite or acceptable, which could involve bigotry or sexism or whatever.

02:30:50.840 --> 02:30:55.140
[Amit Varma]: But when through social media, you see that enough people share that, you get emboldened

02:30:55.140 --> 02:30:59.420
[Amit Varma]: and you form what is called a preference cascade, which is why a lot of parties and politicians

02:30:59.420 --> 02:31:01.280
[Amit Varma]: don't need to dog whistle anymore.

02:31:01.280 --> 02:31:04.760
[Amit Varma]: They can just straight up say the most outrageous thing.

02:31:04.760 --> 02:31:09.560
[Amit Varma]: But the other thing what happens is that our tribalism expresses itself and are forming

02:31:09.560 --> 02:31:13.440
[Amit Varma]: these echo chambers and these sort of tribes online.

02:31:13.440 --> 02:31:19.240
[Amit Varma]: And that drifts towards the extremes automatically, because how do you lift your stature within

02:31:19.240 --> 02:31:20.400
[Amit Varma]: your in-group?

02:31:20.400 --> 02:31:25.640
[Amit Varma]: You do it by signaling how much of a true believer you are, which could be by, you know,

02:31:25.640 --> 02:31:30.640
[Amit Varma]: a lot of virtue signaling, abusing the other side, not arguing with usually abusing if

02:31:30.640 --> 02:31:36.160
[Amit Varma]: it's social media, or even attacking adherents of, you know, even attacking people in your

02:31:36.160 --> 02:31:40.720
[Amit Varma]: own tribe who to you are not pure enough, you know, and or fail some essential purity

02:31:40.720 --> 02:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: test and therefore you raise your own status within your in-group.

02:31:43.840 --> 02:31:50.760
[Amit Varma]: And what this seems to do is it seems to have an influence within not just on social media,

02:31:50.760 --> 02:31:54.520
[Amit Varma]: but an influence on politics where everyone is driven to the extremes.

02:31:54.520 --> 02:31:59.880
[Amit Varma]: So in America, you have a Trump on one extreme and you have the rise of woke politics at

02:31:59.880 --> 02:32:05.160
[Amit Varma]: the other extreme, which is also looking at, you know, neo Marxist narratives of oppression

02:32:05.160 --> 02:32:06.160
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

02:32:06.160 --> 02:32:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, looking at group identities rather than individuals, you have an extremism

02:32:10.360 --> 02:32:11.540
[Amit Varma]: happening there.

02:32:11.540 --> 02:32:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, what, you know, in India, they're all cut from the same mold.

02:32:15.760 --> 02:32:21.280
[Amit Varma]: But what we have seen within the BJP or the Jansangh as it was before is that an observation

02:32:21.280 --> 02:32:26.080
[Amit Varma]: commonly made is that each leader seems, you know, makes a previous guy look moderate.

02:32:26.080 --> 02:32:30.320
[Amit Varma]: So Vajpayee made Shyama Prasad look moderate, Advani, you know, made Vajpayee look moderate

02:32:30.320 --> 02:32:34.100
[Amit Varma]: and so on to Modi and Adityanath and God knows who next.

02:32:34.100 --> 02:32:38.560
[Amit Varma]: And it almost seems inevitable that then within a party, within a tribe of true believers,

02:32:38.560 --> 02:32:43.040
[Amit Varma]: the only way to raise your stature is not by seeming moderate, because then you can

02:32:43.040 --> 02:32:48.520
[Amit Varma]: be accused of being a sellout or whatever, but by being more extreme than the last guy.

02:32:48.520 --> 02:32:52.600
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, everybody is driven to these extreme fringes.

02:32:52.600 --> 02:32:57.200
[Amit Varma]: And this is quite the opposite of what you call, you know, the centrism, which you said

02:32:57.200 --> 02:33:03.920
[Amit Varma]: would come through pragmatism is now actually, you know, just going in the opposite direction.

02:33:03.920 --> 02:33:04.920
[Amit Varma]: What are your thoughts on this?

02:33:04.920 --> 02:33:10.080
[Guest]: Well, this is a big question, to be honest, I think one has to kind of acknowledge that,

02:33:10.080 --> 02:33:14.360
[Guest]: you know, we still don't fully know the dynamics of the moment we are in.

02:33:14.360 --> 02:33:19.640
[Guest]: I mean, I think a lot of clarity will come in hindsight, but I think two or three observations.

02:33:19.640 --> 02:33:28.280
[Guest]: One, I think it's probably always a good rule when thinking about politics to first begin

02:33:28.280 --> 02:33:31.160
[Guest]: about what objective facts might have changed.

02:33:31.160 --> 02:33:36.240
[Guest]: I mean, I think the point about social media and the generation of a certain kind of discourse

02:33:36.240 --> 02:33:39.080
[Guest]: is a very important one, and I think I'll build up to it.

02:33:39.080 --> 02:33:44.400
[Guest]: But you know, when we thought of the centrism of Indian politics, and I think there is a

02:33:44.400 --> 02:33:50.200
[Guest]: little bit of a difference between India and the US, the outcome might seem similar.

02:33:50.200 --> 02:33:59.360
[Guest]: In hindsight, I think the centrism was premised on two facts about social power.

02:33:59.360 --> 02:34:05.760
[Guest]: So the first fact was that Indians may not be individually liberal in the way that you

02:34:05.760 --> 02:34:15.480
[Guest]: had kind of described, but the sources of social power are fragmented enough that no

02:34:15.480 --> 02:34:20.280
[Guest]: force can kind of concentrate them, right?

02:34:20.280 --> 02:34:25.800
[Guest]: There are some traditional lines in which they are fragmented, region, caste, even religion

02:34:25.800 --> 02:34:28.080
[Guest]: under certain circumstances, right?

02:34:28.080 --> 02:34:32.120
[Guest]: The good thing, as the Rudolphs many years ago, the regional propounders of the centrist

02:34:32.120 --> 02:34:39.000
[Guest]: thesis said, these natural sources of social power, while they're illiberal internally,

02:34:39.000 --> 02:34:43.320
[Guest]: they also act as a certain kind of break on the centralization of power, right?

02:34:43.320 --> 02:34:49.520
[Guest]: So the first question for me to ask is, what has happened to these natural breaks, right?

02:34:49.520 --> 02:34:53.160
[Guest]: And we always used to say, look, even the old Congress, when it dominated, had to be

02:34:53.160 --> 02:34:55.320
[Guest]: a coalition of all of these, right?

02:34:55.320 --> 02:34:59.920
[Guest]: You had to build a kind of dominant caste, class, region, religion coalition.

02:34:59.920 --> 02:35:04.520
[Guest]: What is it about this moment that the BJP can, in a sense, override them in some ways,

02:35:04.520 --> 02:35:05.520
[Guest]: right?

02:35:05.520 --> 02:35:08.600
[Guest]: And create this mega majoritarian coalition.

02:35:08.600 --> 02:35:13.840
[Guest]: And that, I think, has to do with some profound changes in Indian society, and some are actually

02:35:13.840 --> 02:35:14.840
[Guest]: good changes.

02:35:14.840 --> 02:35:18.160
[Guest]: I mean, they're the unintended consequences of good changes.

02:35:18.160 --> 02:35:26.200
[Guest]: So one, I think what has happened is, the regional parties, in a sense, have also declined

02:35:26.200 --> 02:35:27.200
[Guest]: in a manner of speaking.

02:35:27.200 --> 02:35:32.720
[Guest]: I mean, there are regional parties, there's DMC, there's DMK, there's a whole bunch of...

02:35:32.720 --> 02:35:39.360
[Guest]: But they have declined in the sense that a lot of their edge came from the imminent prospect

02:35:39.360 --> 02:35:45.040
[Guest]: of a kind of North Indian, Hindi hegemony being imposed.

02:35:45.040 --> 02:35:52.600
[Guest]: And the BJP is sometimes internally divided on this, but for the most part, they have

02:35:52.600 --> 02:35:55.560
[Guest]: managed to neutralize that fear, right?

02:35:55.560 --> 02:35:59.880
[Guest]: I mean, occasionally people try, and frankly, I think it's much more fashionable in our

02:35:59.880 --> 02:36:03.120
[Guest]: circles to make this up.

02:36:03.120 --> 02:36:06.600
[Guest]: The result is every regional party thinks that whoever is at center, we can do business

02:36:06.600 --> 02:36:09.680
[Guest]: with them, right?

02:36:09.680 --> 02:36:12.360
[Guest]: So I think that's what happened to region.

02:36:12.360 --> 02:36:22.720
[Guest]: I think caste is in, I think, an interesting position where for many decades after independence,

02:36:22.720 --> 02:36:27.720
[Guest]: caste was a mobilizing force, and sometimes in a good way, I mean, in the sense that the

02:36:27.720 --> 02:36:30.600
[Guest]: demand was a demand for a certain kind of inclusion, right?

02:36:30.600 --> 02:36:35.400
[Guest]: It's not a sort of exclusive demand in some ways, it's just saying, give to us what everybody

02:36:35.400 --> 02:36:38.080
[Guest]: has, right?

02:36:38.080 --> 02:36:42.840
[Guest]: But the logic of caste inclusion was agglomerative, right?

02:36:42.840 --> 02:36:47.920
[Guest]: So when the Dravidian movements first started, you had to build bigger and bigger coalitions.

02:36:47.920 --> 02:36:53.560
[Guest]: When the BSP came up in the North, the object was to agglomerate Dalits so that they become

02:36:53.560 --> 02:36:56.400
[Guest]: a cohesive social movement.

02:36:56.400 --> 02:36:59.480
[Guest]: Mandal did that to the OBCs.

02:36:59.480 --> 02:37:03.760
[Guest]: And those agglomerative moments required two things.

02:37:03.760 --> 02:37:06.840
[Guest]: A, they required a lot of work of culture.

02:37:06.840 --> 02:37:11.280
[Guest]: Most of these came about after years of social movements, right?

02:37:11.280 --> 02:37:15.440
[Guest]: And second, they required a focal point around which to mobilize.

02:37:15.440 --> 02:37:20.640
[Guest]: So in the South, it was kind of anti-Brahmanism, simplifying it a little bit.

02:37:20.640 --> 02:37:25.480
[Guest]: In the North, it became reservations, Mandal became another focal point.

02:37:25.480 --> 02:37:31.600
[Guest]: Now, we are at an interesting inflection point where both of the energies of the social movement

02:37:31.600 --> 02:37:33.480
[Guest]: have disappeared, right?

02:37:33.480 --> 02:37:39.120
[Guest]: Again, BSP, once it came to power, the social movement kind of dissipated under it.

02:37:39.120 --> 02:37:45.240
[Guest]: But also the agglomerative potential of a focal point has dissipated, which is now the

02:37:45.240 --> 02:37:49.320
[Guest]: demand for reservation is demand for subdivision, right?

02:37:49.320 --> 02:37:57.280
[Guest]: EBCs, Jatavs versus Chamars, non-Yadavs versus Yadavs and OBCs, right?

02:37:57.280 --> 02:38:03.800
[Guest]: And there isn't a single straightforward focal point, which in a sense unites this agglomerative

02:38:03.800 --> 02:38:04.800
[Guest]: mobilization.

02:38:04.800 --> 02:38:08.560
[Guest]: And I think the BJP has been very clever in grasping that.

02:38:08.560 --> 02:38:13.440
[Guest]: So when in a state like UP, even the Yadav vote is split three ways.

02:38:13.440 --> 02:38:17.720
[Guest]: You actually know that the agglomerative power of that mobilization is gone, right?

02:38:17.720 --> 02:38:22.440
[Guest]: Now, the good news in this is that what it shows, and you can do a similar thing for

02:38:22.440 --> 02:38:25.160
[Guest]: in a sense, class-based things.

02:38:25.160 --> 02:38:29.040
[Guest]: So when the Rudolphs wrote their book, you know, the farmer's movement and the labor

02:38:29.040 --> 02:38:32.960
[Guest]: movement were the kind of two big poles of it, right?

02:38:32.960 --> 02:38:36.400
[Guest]: Now, India actually doesn't have a farmer's movement anymore.

02:38:36.400 --> 02:38:42.800
[Guest]: Let's be very clear, partly because the contradictions of different kinds of farmers, partly because

02:38:42.800 --> 02:38:48.440
[Guest]: agriculture has become un-renumerative and the fragmentation of thought sizes, the desire

02:38:48.440 --> 02:38:54.600
[Guest]: of people to move out, because of the party politicization of local panchayats, right?

02:38:54.600 --> 02:38:59.960
[Guest]: None of these basic social identities that were kind of agglomerative forces for mobilization

02:38:59.960 --> 02:39:00.960
[Guest]: exist anymore.

02:39:00.960 --> 02:39:03.760
[Guest]: At least not in the same, with the same form or same power.

02:39:03.760 --> 02:39:10.280
[Guest]: They may crop their head up if somebody poses a real existential threat, right?

02:39:10.280 --> 02:39:13.400
[Guest]: And that's what the BJP has been very clever at neutralizing.

02:39:13.400 --> 02:39:17.920
[Guest]: So what I think happened to centrist politics in India, let's call it there for want of

02:39:17.920 --> 02:39:22.360
[Guest]: that, and partly because I think they were reading too much social science, they all

02:39:22.360 --> 02:39:25.160
[Guest]: became socially deterministic.

02:39:25.160 --> 02:39:29.800
[Guest]: India's natural checks and balances, not caste, class, religion, region, class, you know,

02:39:29.800 --> 02:39:33.760
[Guest]: I mean, nobody can take over the system, right?

02:39:33.760 --> 02:39:37.760
[Guest]: And as I said, I think that there is something kind of interesting about this moment because

02:39:37.760 --> 02:39:42.080
[Guest]: it has embedded, I mean, you know, you can't even think of class terms, gradient producers

02:39:42.080 --> 02:39:47.400
[Guest]: are both consumers and producers, you know, they can work different ways in different

02:39:47.400 --> 02:39:48.400
[Guest]: contexts.

02:39:48.400 --> 02:39:57.360
[Guest]: Now, once this disembedding happens, then it opens up the space for the creation of

02:39:57.360 --> 02:40:02.160
[Guest]: a new kind of agglomerative force, right?

02:40:02.160 --> 02:40:10.200
[Guest]: And one thing I think Mr. Modi grasped and BJP grasped is that identities are not natural

02:40:10.200 --> 02:40:11.200
[Guest]: in that sense.

02:40:11.200 --> 02:40:16.520
[Guest]: They have to be created through the work of mobilization, tapping into fears, propaganda.

02:40:16.520 --> 02:40:20.800
[Guest]: The left, it's been its biggest failing always, is always socially deterministic, right?

02:40:20.800 --> 02:40:28.000
[Guest]: I mean, class will read this off, caste will read this off, and it got together all the

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:29.000
[Guest]: elements of it.

02:40:29.000 --> 02:40:32.680
[Guest]: I mean, it got, it has a social movement like the RSS, whatever else you might say about

02:40:32.680 --> 02:40:34.400
[Guest]: the RSS, it is actually a social movement.

02:40:34.400 --> 02:40:39.400
[Guest]: I mean, you know, even in this age of social media, one of the things we forget that how

02:40:39.400 --> 02:40:46.640
[Guest]: much the BJP relies on sheer human power, right, door-to-door campaigning.

02:40:46.640 --> 02:40:50.720
[Guest]: I mean, last election, you know, we were visited by the BJP guys six times, right?

02:40:50.720 --> 02:40:54.360
[Guest]: I don't think I saw a Congress worker, right?

02:40:54.360 --> 02:40:57.320
[Guest]: So it's kind of got that base.

02:40:57.320 --> 02:41:03.480
[Guest]: Modi's in a sense, recalibrated that identity into this collective narrative of sort of

02:41:03.480 --> 02:41:10.880
[Guest]: hurt, and then of course, he played the card of the decline of the old regime very well,

02:41:10.880 --> 02:41:18.400
[Guest]: that that became a symbol of plutocracy, corruption, dynasty, decrepitude, and frankly, that old

02:41:18.400 --> 02:41:20.440
[Guest]: order has no fight left in it.

02:41:20.440 --> 02:41:22.320
[Guest]: I mean, there's just, right?

02:41:22.320 --> 02:41:28.880
[Guest]: So I think, in that sense, I think India is a little bit different, which is that, you

02:41:28.880 --> 02:41:34.280
[Guest]: know, what the BJP has, in a sense, managed to do is its version of what the Congress

02:41:34.280 --> 02:41:40.520
[Guest]: did between 1920 and 1950, right, which is created a generative, newly generated social

02:41:40.520 --> 02:41:41.520
[Guest]: identity.

02:41:41.520 --> 02:41:46.320
[Guest]: Now, it needs the other little, you know, occasional, and as I said, it smartly fuses

02:41:46.320 --> 02:41:47.320
[Guest]: lots of elements, right?

02:41:47.320 --> 02:41:52.920
[Guest]: I mean, I joke with colleagues, one of the things about India is that, you know, it can

02:41:52.920 --> 02:41:58.080
[Guest]: be totalitarian, you know, 9am to 10am, it can be democratic in the afternoon, it can

02:41:58.080 --> 02:42:03.280
[Guest]: be anarchist in the evening, it can be oligarchic sometime in the day, right?

02:42:03.280 --> 02:42:09.360
[Guest]: So he can play the liberal card when he wants triple talaq, he can play a dog whistle card

02:42:09.360 --> 02:42:12.960
[Guest]: when he's campaigning in Bihar, right?

02:42:12.960 --> 02:42:19.280
[Guest]: So I would still argue, actually, that that driver is actually what's led breakdown, and

02:42:19.280 --> 02:42:25.480
[Guest]: the challenge for any opposition is that once politics operates in this way, the entry costs

02:42:25.480 --> 02:42:28.280
[Guest]: are now higher, right?

02:42:28.280 --> 02:42:32.520
[Guest]: Because now, you can't do what the Congress was trying to do the last election, you know,

02:42:32.520 --> 02:42:36.720
[Guest]: somehow the Dalits will get upset and somehow you just hope the Bengalis get upset enough

02:42:36.720 --> 02:42:40.760
[Guest]: and you know, the Tamils get upset enough, right?

02:42:40.760 --> 02:42:42.960
[Guest]: Because you have to do it as a national scale.

02:42:42.960 --> 02:42:47.880
[Guest]: Now, national scale requires resources of a different order of magnitude, it requires

02:42:47.880 --> 02:42:55.680
[Guest]: a control in some senses of a propaganda, information machinery, where BJP has a natural

02:42:55.680 --> 02:43:00.320
[Guest]: incumbent advantage, I mean, basically, it's cornered all of television media, it manages

02:43:00.320 --> 02:43:06.160
[Guest]: to control most of print media, in connivance with Indian capital, right?

02:43:06.160 --> 02:43:10.680
[Guest]: And it's interesting that the BJP, when it started out as an insurgent group, used social

02:43:10.680 --> 02:43:13.040
[Guest]: media, right?

02:43:13.040 --> 02:43:17.920
[Guest]: But contrary to what people thought, traditional media still remains important for it.

02:43:17.920 --> 02:43:22.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's important that Ram Madhav appear in the pages of Indian Express, right?

02:43:22.480 --> 02:43:30.240
[Guest]: It's important that, you know, scripts go out to television producers all the time,

02:43:30.240 --> 02:43:31.240
[Guest]: right?

02:43:31.240 --> 02:43:36.840
[Guest]: And because Mr. Modi is in a sense kind of both presidentialized the election in ways

02:43:36.840 --> 02:43:42.360
[Guest]: which we did not think possible, the entry barriers for somebody to dislodge are now

02:43:42.360 --> 02:43:45.600
[Guest]: going to be just that much higher, right?

02:43:45.600 --> 02:43:50.960
[Guest]: So I actually do think there's a, and as I said, part of it is as a result of those complex

02:43:50.960 --> 02:43:56.440
[Guest]: development processes that happened in the last 10-15 years, that we actually did see

02:43:56.440 --> 02:44:00.760
[Guest]: a little bit of that disembedding from that sociological fatalism.

02:44:00.760 --> 02:44:05.720
[Guest]: The polarization in the social media and forms of communication stuff, I think that you're

02:44:05.720 --> 02:44:12.400
[Guest]: talking about, I think is interesting, and I don't claim to understand the dynamics of

02:44:12.400 --> 02:44:13.400
[Guest]: it.

02:44:13.400 --> 02:44:16.840
[Guest]: I mean, is this just a passing phase or a kind of permanent feature?

02:44:16.840 --> 02:44:20.640
[Guest]: As I said, the one thing social media does manage to do is because of this asymmetry

02:44:20.640 --> 02:44:26.240
[Guest]: between truth and doubt, I think it's much easier to in a sense bring down reputations,

02:44:26.240 --> 02:44:33.760
[Guest]: because all you need to, and in a sense, create that platform for a kind of pervasive cynicism.

02:44:33.760 --> 02:44:37.240
[Guest]: Each of us has a skeleton in our closet.

02:44:37.240 --> 02:44:40.160
[Guest]: That seems to be the one common thread across social media, right?

02:44:40.160 --> 02:44:43.840
[Guest]: The way you argue is in a sense you impugn somebody's credibility, right?

02:44:43.840 --> 02:44:50.440
[Guest]: Now on the polarization and echo chamber story, the other important feature of social media,

02:44:50.440 --> 02:44:57.200
[Guest]: which I think is more important than I think the echo chamber dynamic, because echo chambers

02:44:57.200 --> 02:45:02.000
[Guest]: you could in principle correct, I mean, you do exist in other spaces as well other than

02:45:02.000 --> 02:45:05.360
[Guest]: social media and presumably interacting with different kinds of people.

02:45:05.360 --> 02:45:11.080
[Guest]: The important part of social media is that it completely erases the distinction between

02:45:11.080 --> 02:45:12.600
[Guest]: public and private.

02:45:12.600 --> 02:45:18.360
[Guest]: So the kind of conversation ethic that might have been okay in private, you sometimes even

02:45:18.360 --> 02:45:24.040
[Guest]: use inappropriate words, you sometimes say things for the heck of it.

02:45:24.040 --> 02:45:28.200
[Guest]: Once you have put it out in your social media, that actually defines your identity in some

02:45:28.200 --> 02:45:29.200
[Guest]: ways, right?

02:45:29.200 --> 02:45:33.600
[Guest]: The bad tweet that you made will, in a sense, right?

02:45:33.600 --> 02:45:41.320
[Guest]: Now, the minute you make your identities public in that way, it automatically congeals them

02:45:41.320 --> 02:45:46.600
[Guest]: and seals them because you have no other option but to defend yourself to death and the tweet

02:45:46.600 --> 02:45:48.120
[Guest]: becomes you, right?

02:45:48.120 --> 02:45:54.320
[Guest]: Rather than look, okay, I said this, on reflection, I've changed my mind, right?

02:45:54.320 --> 02:46:02.240
[Guest]: So in some ways, the performative aspect of this where it has actually made visible are

02:46:02.240 --> 02:46:04.240
[Guest]: impulsive thoughts, right?

02:46:04.240 --> 02:46:08.480
[Guest]: I mean, philosophers used to have a joke, you know, I think Wittgenstein's advice that

02:46:08.480 --> 02:46:12.880
[Guest]: when philosophers greet each other, they should raise their hands and say, slow down, you

02:46:12.880 --> 02:46:16.200
[Guest]: know, before you say something.

02:46:16.200 --> 02:46:20.040
[Guest]: In a sense, social media, your performance in a sense becomes your identity and defines

02:46:20.040 --> 02:46:21.040
[Guest]: you.

02:46:21.040 --> 02:46:25.480
[Guest]: And to my mind, I mean, this is just anecdotal thing, but when I see, you know, I find the

02:46:25.480 --> 02:46:29.520
[Guest]: echo chamber issue less significant, I mean, people still talk to enough different people

02:46:29.520 --> 02:46:32.600
[Guest]: and obviously, they're seeing the other echo chambers, I mean, they're responding to that

02:46:32.600 --> 02:46:33.600
[Guest]: in some ways, right?

02:46:33.600 --> 02:46:39.880
[Guest]: I think it's just the fact that once you've taken a position in public, you know, saying

02:46:39.880 --> 02:46:44.360
[Guest]: sorry, withdrawing is simply not an option, right?

02:46:44.360 --> 02:46:49.520
[Guest]: The second thing, which is, as Plato said, in democracy, the most corrupting thing is,

02:46:49.520 --> 02:46:54.600
[Guest]: of course, the desire for agglomeration and popularity, right?

02:46:54.600 --> 02:47:01.200
[Guest]: If what I'm after is more attention, right, then I have to probably differentiate and

02:47:01.200 --> 02:47:03.840
[Guest]: say the most outrageous things possible.

02:47:03.840 --> 02:47:11.680
[Guest]: The problem is I may be doing it for a pretty, it might almost be a game in some cases, right?

02:47:11.680 --> 02:47:16.640
[Guest]: But that in then some senses becomes you, right?

02:47:16.640 --> 02:47:20.520
[Guest]: It's an interesting question, you know, how even I'm sure you've experienced this, your

02:47:20.520 --> 02:47:24.520
[Guest]: perception of people's arguments and work changes because of what you've seen on them

02:47:24.520 --> 02:47:27.400
[Guest]: on social media, right?

02:47:27.400 --> 02:47:31.000
[Guest]: And I think there's a good reason liberalism insisted on the distinction between public

02:47:31.000 --> 02:47:36.240
[Guest]: and private, not just because the private is a space where you shield yourself from

02:47:36.240 --> 02:47:43.320
[Guest]: a kind of public gaze, but because private is also a space where you can churn and form

02:47:43.320 --> 02:47:47.440
[Guest]: before you actually appear in public, right?

02:47:47.440 --> 02:47:49.840
[Guest]: And that distinction is completely gone.

02:47:49.840 --> 02:47:55.000
[Guest]: I mean, we are quite happy making ourselves, you know, I don't want your nighttime thoughts

02:47:55.000 --> 02:47:58.000
[Guest]: to be transparent, frankly, right?

02:47:58.000 --> 02:48:02.240
[Guest]: But once they are, that's who you become in my eyes.

02:48:02.240 --> 02:48:03.320
[Amit Varma]: That's a fascinating insight.

02:48:03.320 --> 02:48:07.120
[Amit Varma]: I've just finished writing this essay called a meditation on form, not published it yet,

02:48:07.120 --> 02:48:12.200
[Amit Varma]: but it will come in my newsletter, where I am speculating on how the forms that you write

02:48:12.200 --> 02:48:17.400
[Amit Varma]: and read shape, not just the content, like it's, of course, a trivial matter that writing

02:48:17.400 --> 02:48:21.960
[Amit Varma]: for Twitter will make your content more concise or more simplistic or whatever, but also shape

02:48:21.960 --> 02:48:22.960
[Amit Varma]: the person.

02:48:22.960 --> 02:48:26.680
[Amit Varma]: And one way of doing that is that, you know, I thank God that Twitter was not around when

02:48:26.680 --> 02:48:27.680
[Amit Varma]: I was 20.

02:48:27.680 --> 02:48:31.160
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, what I would have done is I would have tweeted the kind of nonsense I used to

02:48:31.160 --> 02:48:35.680
[Amit Varma]: think that I would have doubled down on it, and I would have become that person.

02:48:35.680 --> 02:48:39.180
[Amit Varma]: So that's a great insight that you just shared.

02:48:39.180 --> 02:48:43.400
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the other thing that I think the other profound way in which social media

02:48:43.400 --> 02:48:48.320
[Amit Varma]: has changed us all is that, you know, 20 years ago, there was a broad consensus on the truth,

02:48:48.320 --> 02:48:51.880
[Amit Varma]: you got your mainstream newspapers and whatever, and there was a broad sense.

02:48:51.880 --> 02:48:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And now it's just everybody choosing her narrative.

02:48:55.160 --> 02:48:59.960
[Amit Varma]: And then you just listen to the sources that feed that narrative.

02:48:59.960 --> 02:49:04.760
[Amit Varma]: I have a couple of questions for you based on what you were talking about, you know,

02:49:04.760 --> 02:49:10.080
[Amit Varma]: based on the BJP and sort of on that one is about the BJP itself, which is that what they

02:49:10.080 --> 02:49:15.360
[Amit Varma]: have done is that and whether we attribute this political genius to Amit Shah or Modi

02:49:15.360 --> 02:49:18.000
[Amit Varma]: or it's a combination of whatever is a different matter.

02:49:18.000 --> 02:49:23.200
[Amit Varma]: But what they did was that they played identarian politics brilliantly in the sense that of

02:49:23.200 --> 02:49:27.360
[Amit Varma]: course, all our politics has been identarian, but they manipulated it brilliantly in the

02:49:27.360 --> 02:49:31.440
[Amit Varma]: sense that they could go inside UP and they could say, okay, you know, the Yadavs are

02:49:31.440 --> 02:49:37.240
[Amit Varma]: gone to us, we'll go for the non Yadav OBCs, we'll go for the non Jatav Dalits, in Maharashtra,

02:49:37.240 --> 02:49:39.400
[Amit Varma]: we'll go for the non Maratha OBCs.

02:49:39.400 --> 02:49:43.440
[Amit Varma]: So they really figured out which end of the market they want, and they went for that with

02:49:43.440 --> 02:49:45.480
[Amit Varma]: great pragmatism.

02:49:45.480 --> 02:49:50.800
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that they managed to do in that process, as Prashant Jha wrote

02:49:50.800 --> 02:49:55.920
[Amit Varma]: about in his book, how the BJP wins, I had an episode with him as well, is that they

02:49:55.920 --> 02:49:58.080
[Amit Varma]: became the de facto Dalit Party of India.

02:49:58.080 --> 02:50:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, whatever activists may say, the bottom line is that more Dalits have voted for the

02:50:02.560 --> 02:50:07.120
[Amit Varma]: BJP than their opponents, both in 2014 and 2019.

02:50:07.120 --> 02:50:11.800
[Amit Varma]: They've managed to agglomerate that identity within the larger umbrella of whatever they

02:50:11.800 --> 02:50:15.440
[Amit Varma]: stand for, which is, you know, very interesting to me.

02:50:15.440 --> 02:50:23.480
[Amit Varma]: So the two questions related to this, that I sort of have is that, one, within the BJP,

02:50:23.480 --> 02:50:27.400
[Amit Varma]: as we see them today, we see two conflicting impulses.

02:50:27.400 --> 02:50:33.880
[Amit Varma]: One impulse is the practical impulse of politics, where you do whatever it takes to power, which

02:50:33.880 --> 02:50:38.480
[Amit Varma]: includes mergers and acquisitions, where you'll buy MLAs from the Congress, and you might

02:50:38.480 --> 02:50:42.080
[Amit Varma]: have abused them during the election, but you buy them and you form the government and

02:50:42.080 --> 02:50:43.080
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

02:50:43.080 --> 02:50:45.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's a practical impulse of power politics.

02:50:45.680 --> 02:50:51.200
[Amit Varma]: But the other is also the ideological impulse of being true to their core social movement

02:50:51.200 --> 02:50:57.760
[Amit Varma]: and whatever that was, which also you see expressed in ways that I hardly need to elaborate

02:50:57.760 --> 02:50:58.760
[Amit Varma]: upon.

02:50:58.760 --> 02:51:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So, one question, what do you kind of make of this?

02:51:01.000 --> 02:51:05.040
[Amit Varma]: And if it is a movement from the latter towards the former, that is, if it is going to become

02:51:05.040 --> 02:51:10.760
[Amit Varma]: more and more pragmatic about retaining power, then does that dilute the ideological edge?

02:51:10.760 --> 02:51:14.560
[Amit Varma]: Or since the ideological edge is a dominant strain in the culture, anyway, it doesn't

02:51:14.560 --> 02:51:15.560
[Amit Varma]: really matter?

02:51:15.560 --> 02:51:16.560
[Amit Varma]: That's one question.

02:51:16.560 --> 02:51:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And the other question on caste is that the sort of direction we took at our founding

02:51:21.640 --> 02:51:27.400
[Amit Varma]: moment of saying that we will transform society from the top down, you know, caste is of course,

02:51:27.400 --> 02:51:33.520
[Amit Varma]: we would agree, one of our most grievous problems, if not the original sin of Indian civilization,

02:51:33.520 --> 02:51:39.240
[Amit Varma]: as you put it, but was the right way to solve it, the top down approach that we took, which

02:51:39.240 --> 02:51:45.000
[Amit Varma]: instead seems to have entrenched a certain kind of toxic identity politics, which just

02:51:45.000 --> 02:51:49.720
[Amit Varma]: makes divisions worse, and doesn't actually help with the problem.

02:51:49.720 --> 02:51:50.720
[Guest]: Okay.

02:51:50.720 --> 02:51:53.520
[Guest]: So let me begin with the caste question first, and then we'll come to the BJP.

02:51:53.520 --> 02:51:58.280
[Guest]: Because I think this, so, you know, Amit, I mean, and I think, I think this is something

02:51:58.280 --> 02:52:04.400
[Guest]: I think we have to acknowledge, right, that, I mean, we can debate the merits or demerits

02:52:04.400 --> 02:52:05.680
[Guest]: of reforming it through the state.

02:52:05.680 --> 02:52:11.480
[Guest]: But the fact of the matter is that reform of that social system did have an element

02:52:11.480 --> 02:52:13.120
[Guest]: that would have involved the state.

02:52:13.120 --> 02:52:17.560
[Guest]: So first of all, you need a legal structure that outlaws certain forms of discrimination

02:52:17.560 --> 02:52:18.560
[Guest]: and so forth.

02:52:18.560 --> 02:52:19.560
[Guest]: Right.

02:52:19.560 --> 02:52:24.600
[Guest]: And, in a sense, a lot of the focus of the debate over caste focused on one instrument,

02:52:24.600 --> 02:52:27.720
[Guest]: which was reservations.

02:52:27.720 --> 02:52:33.640
[Guest]: And I don't want to use this episode to kind of debate the pros and cons.

02:52:33.640 --> 02:52:38.680
[Guest]: I mean, I think the reservations for Dalits were not only justified, but I actually still

02:52:38.680 --> 02:52:42.920
[Guest]: think it continued to be justified, we can have an argument over that.

02:52:42.920 --> 02:52:48.600
[Guest]: I think what the expansion of reservations to OBCs in the form that they took in Mandal

02:52:48.600 --> 02:52:54.560
[Guest]: did was that it actually won, it took out the specificity of the Dalit experience.

02:52:54.560 --> 02:53:01.600
[Guest]: And in a sense, the entire discourse became about sharing a particular small pie.

02:53:01.600 --> 02:53:06.480
[Guest]: In fact, it left the upper cast of the hook in some ways, because the core of a society,

02:53:06.480 --> 02:53:11.000
[Guest]: right, which is you shall not discriminate against people for who they are.

02:53:11.000 --> 02:53:13.240
[Guest]: That question kind of dropped out of our consciousness.

02:53:13.240 --> 02:53:16.440
[Guest]: You know, we kept saying, look, but we've given reservation, we don't discriminate.

02:53:16.440 --> 02:53:19.640
[Guest]: Hello, you know, wake up, right?

02:53:19.640 --> 02:53:23.440
[Guest]: So I think that's one thing to, I think, bear in mind.

02:53:23.440 --> 02:53:29.000
[Guest]: But I think the larger context, why the reservation debate took the form it did, and frankly,

02:53:29.000 --> 02:53:38.600
[Guest]: there's a lot of bad faith on our part, is the state took on that instrument, in my view,

02:53:38.600 --> 02:53:44.160
[Guest]: not because it wanted a top-down transformation of society, but because it wanted a cheap

02:53:44.160 --> 02:53:46.920
[Guest]: and ineffective transformation of society.

02:53:46.920 --> 02:53:50.320
[Guest]: So reservation is cheap, it actually doesn't cost too many resources.

02:53:50.320 --> 02:53:54.880
[Guest]: You know, whatever institutions you have, you just kind of, you know, allocate.

02:53:54.880 --> 02:54:01.800
[Guest]: What we did not do, which would have taken collective action, was actually make education

02:54:01.800 --> 02:54:02.800
[Guest]: accessible.

02:54:02.800 --> 02:54:03.800
[Guest]: Right?

02:54:03.800 --> 02:54:10.000
[Guest]: I mean, frankly, if Dr. Ambedkar's plan in 10, 15 years, you know, I mean, it took India

02:54:10.000 --> 02:54:15.000
[Guest]: almost 65 years to reach even universal enrollment, right?

02:54:15.000 --> 02:54:18.120
[Guest]: So reservation was not about top-down transformation.

02:54:18.120 --> 02:54:28.200
[Guest]: Reservation was simply a very cheap way of India's elites satiating the demand for representativeness.

02:54:28.200 --> 02:54:32.640
[Guest]: Knowing fully well that one of the advantages of doing reservation is that you take your

02:54:32.640 --> 02:54:34.120
[Guest]: attention off these other things.

02:54:34.120 --> 02:54:38.720
[Guest]: I mean, you know, in my Knowledge Commission days, we used to often ask politicians, right?

02:54:38.720 --> 02:54:43.720
[Guest]: I've been always amazed by the fact that whenever there's reservation, of course, there's a

02:54:43.720 --> 02:54:48.520
[Guest]: focal point of mobilization, right, for and against.

02:54:48.520 --> 02:54:52.960
[Guest]: Which was the last political party, I mean, I can think of maybe Kamaraj as an exception

02:54:52.960 --> 02:54:59.200
[Guest]: in Tamil Nadu, maybe AAP briefly in Delhi now, that actually got really upset about

02:54:59.200 --> 02:55:08.760
[Guest]: the quality and accessibility of education to its constituents, which, you know, OBC

02:55:08.760 --> 02:55:15.240
[Guest]: or Dalit party, right, asked the question, what is the nature of quality education in

02:55:15.240 --> 02:55:16.240
[Guest]: our schools?

02:55:16.240 --> 02:55:22.400
[Guest]: So frankly, reservation was our cheap way of warding off the problem.

02:55:22.400 --> 02:55:26.600
[Guest]: And the biggest casualty of this, I mean, one is the one you alluded to, which is, does

02:55:26.600 --> 02:55:31.200
[Guest]: it entrench identities in a particular way, but I think the even bigger casualty was a

02:55:31.200 --> 02:55:33.960
[Guest]: permanent distrust.

02:55:33.960 --> 02:55:39.160
[Guest]: So and I have to say that I cannot in good conscience give an answer to this question.

02:55:39.160 --> 02:55:46.240
[Guest]: If you go and talk to Dalit students, and OBC students, many of whom are quite willing,

02:55:46.240 --> 02:55:51.440
[Guest]: not just willing, but quite happy to envisage a world where reservations were not necessary.

02:55:51.440 --> 02:55:56.320
[Guest]: They, of course, understand all the arguments that we make, look, isn't it better to give

02:55:56.320 --> 02:55:57.320
[Guest]: everybody education?

02:55:57.320 --> 02:56:00.400
[Guest]: Isn't it better to do A, B, C, and D?

02:56:00.400 --> 02:56:05.280
[Guest]: But we can't look them in the eye and say with a straight face that anybody actually

02:56:05.280 --> 02:56:08.840
[Guest]: intended to do that, right?

02:56:08.840 --> 02:56:12.400
[Guest]: So and to me, that's actually the vicious circle.

02:56:12.400 --> 02:56:18.280
[Guest]: That's the trust deficit that is now in a sense so deep, right, that it will take, you

02:56:18.280 --> 02:56:23.360
[Guest]: know, a 10 year performance by a state to show, look, we can deliver all of these things,

02:56:23.360 --> 02:56:29.680
[Guest]: right, that are yours by right such that these things become kind of, you know, unnecessary.

02:56:29.680 --> 02:56:33.840
[Guest]: So I think that's one thing I think I do think we have to, in some senses, acknowledge.

02:56:33.840 --> 02:56:38.040
[Guest]: And that's why I think many Dalits are able to also participate in this promise of delivery

02:56:38.040 --> 02:56:39.600
[Guest]: story, right?

02:56:39.600 --> 02:56:45.080
[Guest]: Because from their vantage point, what they have experienced is something that doesn't

02:56:45.080 --> 02:56:47.440
[Guest]: inspire trust in the state.

02:56:47.440 --> 02:56:50.160
[Guest]: It also, by the way, doesn't inspire trust in political parties.

02:56:50.160 --> 02:56:56.440
[Guest]: So for all of the Congress's reliance on apparently on Dalit words, the fact of the matter is

02:56:56.440 --> 02:57:00.720
[Guest]: its culture was deeply, deeply exclusionary in all kinds of quotidian ways.

02:57:00.720 --> 02:57:07.040
[Guest]: I mean, I have stories from Jagjivan Ram, even as late as the 70s, of kind of, you know,

02:57:07.040 --> 02:57:12.800
[Guest]: his cultural experiences in the political party called Congress.

02:57:12.800 --> 02:57:18.360
[Guest]: So I think we will have to, in a sense, now demonstrate by action, it's not just a question

02:57:18.360 --> 02:57:25.800
[Guest]: of abstractly saying, we'll get your education, we'll give you all these means to participate.

02:57:25.800 --> 02:57:26.800
[Guest]: Where do we go on reservations?

02:57:26.800 --> 02:57:32.400
[Guest]: As I said, I mean, I think there was, I have no doubt that we need forms of affirmative

02:57:32.400 --> 02:57:33.400
[Guest]: action.

02:57:33.400 --> 02:57:36.200
[Guest]: But there were different ways of designing it.

02:57:36.200 --> 02:57:43.600
[Guest]: I mean, one proposal, which I think I'm very attracted to is Rakesh Basant of IIM Ahmedabad.

02:57:43.600 --> 02:57:48.520
[Guest]: You know, he crunched some numbers and he basically said, look, parents' education is

02:57:48.520 --> 02:57:51.600
[Guest]: a good proxy predictor of whether the kids get educated or not.

02:57:51.600 --> 02:57:57.640
[Guest]: So if both your parents are graduate, chances are, you know, and he said, if you just made

02:57:57.640 --> 02:58:02.360
[Guest]: that a proxy criteria for reservation instead of caste, you would actually cover all the

02:58:02.360 --> 02:58:07.640
[Guest]: groups that you actually do need to cover, which is some, you know, Dalits and others,

02:58:07.640 --> 02:58:11.060
[Guest]: but it's self-liquidating in a nice kind of way, right?

02:58:11.060 --> 02:58:19.160
[Guest]: So I think other than for Dalits, I think it is worth opening up the debate, what kind

02:58:19.160 --> 02:58:20.160
[Guest]: of access matters.

02:58:20.160 --> 02:58:25.680
[Guest]: I think this 10% economic thing is, I think, beside the point, to be honest, I mean, you

02:58:25.680 --> 02:58:26.680
[Guest]: know.

02:58:26.680 --> 02:58:32.920
[Guest]: Now, the Dalit case, I think, I do think is an exceptional case in India, because it's

02:58:32.920 --> 02:58:38.280
[Guest]: the one community where all lines converge, right?

02:58:38.280 --> 02:58:43.800
[Guest]: So, you know, OBCs can have a history of, you might say, educational backwardness to

02:58:43.800 --> 02:58:48.720
[Guest]: use our official parlance, but not the history of humiliation and discrimination.

02:58:48.720 --> 02:58:54.040
[Guest]: In fact, in some cases, they're dominant, not all of them, some of them, right?

02:58:54.040 --> 02:59:01.240
[Guest]: Dalits are one group where every single historical line of marginalization, humiliation, a sort

02:59:01.240 --> 02:59:04.760
[Guest]: of deep cultural aversion.

02:59:04.760 --> 02:59:10.240
[Guest]: Not only was it so deep, but I hate to say this, even in my experience, I still think

02:59:10.240 --> 02:59:13.280
[Guest]: there are too many traces of it.

02:59:13.280 --> 02:59:16.120
[Guest]: So mere presence is actually important.

02:59:16.120 --> 02:59:21.320
[Guest]: I won't say this about any other group.

02:59:21.320 --> 02:59:25.480
[Guest]: But I think, yes, for the rest, I think we need to think of, you know, what are better

02:59:25.480 --> 02:59:28.760
[Guest]: ways of achieving these objectives.

02:59:28.760 --> 02:59:34.880
[Guest]: The BJP argument you made about sort of, you know, will the optionism tame the fanaticism,

02:59:34.880 --> 02:59:35.880
[Guest]: right?

02:59:35.880 --> 02:59:38.200
[Guest]: That was always our hope, right?

02:59:38.200 --> 02:59:42.480
[Guest]: And particularly when the polity was centrist, right?

02:59:42.480 --> 02:59:48.680
[Guest]: You know, I remember a political scientist used to joke, you know, even in the early

02:59:48.680 --> 02:59:53.720
[Guest]: 2000s, that in India, any party that becomes a ruling party will become like the Congress.

02:59:53.720 --> 02:59:57.760
[Guest]: I mean, and it was meant as a kind of constructive joke that you have to sort of move to the

02:59:57.760 --> 02:59:59.680
[Guest]: center and, you know, create a patchwork.

02:59:59.680 --> 03:00:04.080
[Guest]: And just for reasons I just mentioned, A, I don't think that's necessarily the case

03:00:04.080 --> 03:00:05.080
[Guest]: anymore.

03:00:05.080 --> 03:00:15.600
[Guest]: B, you know, in the BJP's case, I would put the relationship between opportunism and the

03:00:15.600 --> 03:00:18.040
[Guest]: ideological purity slightly differently.

03:00:18.040 --> 03:00:25.040
[Guest]: See, in every other political party, we see the opportunism as a betrayal of a principle,

03:00:25.040 --> 03:00:26.040
[Guest]: right?

03:00:26.040 --> 03:00:29.200
[Guest]: That's how we, you know, it's a practical compromise.

03:00:29.200 --> 03:00:36.240
[Guest]: I think one thing we have not noticed in BJP is that in BJP, the opportunism is a ruthless

03:00:36.240 --> 03:00:40.880
[Guest]: device for furthering the ideological agenda.

03:00:40.880 --> 03:00:45.880
[Guest]: You first consolidate power by all means, only when you have consolidated that power

03:00:45.880 --> 03:00:48.880
[Guest]: that you make the next move, right?

03:00:48.880 --> 03:00:55.360
[Guest]: Why have, in a sense, we've been surprised over Ram Mandir, Kashmir, Tipar Talag, UCC,

03:00:55.360 --> 03:00:59.680
[Guest]: whatever, you know, your pet issue, you know, CA, whatever, right?

03:00:59.680 --> 03:01:00.840
[Guest]: You can read it two ways.

03:01:00.840 --> 03:01:05.880
[Guest]: You can read it saying there's a opportunist BJP that, you know, brings down governments

03:01:05.880 --> 03:01:12.200
[Guest]: that, you know, does horse trading, that issues electoral bonds, that favors certain parts

03:01:12.200 --> 03:01:13.640
[Guest]: of Indian capital.

03:01:13.640 --> 03:01:16.480
[Guest]: And then there's this ideological purist.

03:01:16.480 --> 03:01:24.120
[Guest]: I think in their own imagination, the first is actually the means to the second, which

03:01:24.120 --> 03:01:31.520
[Guest]: is the lesson they have learned is consolidate power by all means, then strike.

03:01:31.520 --> 03:01:37.560
[Guest]: So the next item on that ideological agenda will come when they are in a position for

03:01:37.560 --> 03:01:40.080
[Guest]: it in some ways, right?

03:01:40.080 --> 03:01:44.440
[Guest]: And that's one of the, I think, the macabre attractions of the BJP.

03:01:44.440 --> 03:01:48.440
[Guest]: You know, you and I think Mr. Modi is compromising on principles.

03:01:48.440 --> 03:01:50.240
[Guest]: I think his constituents actually don't see that.

03:01:50.240 --> 03:01:55.720
[Guest]: I think they see it as he understands that Hindus need to acquire power by any means

03:01:55.720 --> 03:02:00.360
[Guest]: whatsoever in order for that ideological agenda to be fulfilled.

03:02:00.360 --> 03:02:04.800
[Guest]: So I think the relationship is a little bit different in some ways, I think, you know,

03:02:04.800 --> 03:02:05.800
[Guest]: in this party.

03:02:05.800 --> 03:02:07.600
[Guest]: And it's true of ideological parties, right?

03:02:07.600 --> 03:02:14.840
[Guest]: Even of the far left, historically, it's been true where because you're so sure of the purity

03:02:14.840 --> 03:02:20.840
[Guest]: of your ideological objectives, it becomes easier to justify the ruthlessness of your

03:02:20.840 --> 03:02:21.840
[Guest]: means.

03:02:21.840 --> 03:02:23.760
[Amit Varma]: No, no, that's a great point.

03:02:23.760 --> 03:02:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And as we see after the 2019 elections, you know, 370, the building of the temple, blah,

03:02:28.360 --> 03:02:33.680
[Amit Varma]: blah, they're getting there kind of one by one, we are already at, you know, the end

03:02:33.680 --> 03:02:35.320
[Amit Varma]: of our sort of time.

03:02:35.320 --> 03:02:40.360
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you for some final comments as we move on that, okay, we've, you know, completed

03:02:40.360 --> 03:02:42.880
[Amit Varma]: 73 years of our independence or whatever.

03:02:42.880 --> 03:02:47.280
[Amit Varma]: The fact is, it is with the hindsight bias that India seems inevitable.

03:02:47.280 --> 03:02:53.880
[Amit Varma]: And it wasn't so at all, in this shape, or perhaps in any shape, and yet, here we are.

03:02:53.880 --> 03:02:59.720
[Amit Varma]: So looking forward, maybe if I ask you to look forward just as little as 10 years, given

03:02:59.720 --> 03:03:05.160
[Amit Varma]: what is happening in our democracy, given what is happening in our politics, and so

03:03:05.160 --> 03:03:10.600
[Amit Varma]: on, and leaving aside, you know, unforeseen events like pandemics, and so on.

03:03:10.600 --> 03:03:12.880
[Amit Varma]: Looking forward 10 years, what gives you hope?

03:03:12.880 --> 03:03:13.880
[Amit Varma]: And what gives you despair?

03:03:13.880 --> 03:03:15.600
[Amit Varma]: Or what's your best case scenario for India?

03:03:15.600 --> 03:03:17.600
[Amit Varma]: And what's your worst case scenario?

03:03:17.600 --> 03:03:18.600
[Guest]: Okay.

03:03:18.600 --> 03:03:19.600
[Guest]: Wow.

03:03:19.600 --> 03:03:24.600
[Guest]: I mean, you know, looking into the future, you feel like lying, even if you turn out

03:03:24.600 --> 03:03:30.640
[Guest]: to be right, because you have no basis for saying what to say, um, I think, two things.

03:03:30.640 --> 03:03:36.280
[Guest]: So let me return to the broader frame of the conversation we started with.

03:03:36.280 --> 03:03:39.480
[Guest]: And so this is the wildly optimistic scenario.

03:03:39.480 --> 03:03:44.480
[Guest]: Okay, this is, this is like, I mean, and I'm saying optimistic, it's not just visual thinking,

03:03:44.480 --> 03:03:49.840
[Guest]: but it would go something like this, that look, there was a settlement that happened

03:03:49.840 --> 03:03:52.200
[Guest]: at partition.

03:03:52.200 --> 03:03:56.360
[Guest]: Pakistan obviously did not fare well as a result of that settlement.

03:03:56.360 --> 03:04:02.520
[Guest]: And partly because the premise of that settlement was bound to produce the kind of pathologies

03:04:02.520 --> 03:04:04.240
[Guest]: that you saw in Pakistan.

03:04:04.240 --> 03:04:08.640
[Guest]: Once you have a religious state, once you believe in blasphemy laws, once you say it's

03:04:08.640 --> 03:04:12.720
[Guest]: an Islamic state, even if Jinnah wanted it to be a relatively liberal Islamic state,

03:04:12.720 --> 03:04:17.560
[Guest]: you're still benchmarking insiders and outsiders, and you do to Ahmadiyyas what you do, and

03:04:17.560 --> 03:04:20.000
[Guest]: the whole thing falls apart, right?

03:04:20.000 --> 03:04:24.080
[Guest]: A little bit of that dialectic is beginning to be unleashed in India as well.

03:04:24.080 --> 03:04:28.320
[Guest]: In a sense that, and the BJP actually does, we are doing the unfinished work of partition.

03:04:28.320 --> 03:04:33.560
[Guest]: I mean, there's a kind of performative sort of admission in that we want to be kind of

03:04:33.560 --> 03:04:35.560
[Guest]: like Pakistan, right?

03:04:35.560 --> 03:04:36.560
[Guest]: Okay.

03:04:36.560 --> 03:04:43.320
[Guest]: Now, the wildly optimistic scenario is that, look, we do have three to five, six years

03:04:43.320 --> 03:04:49.680
[Guest]: of serious conflict around this, can't predict the scale of violence, but I think some violence

03:04:49.680 --> 03:04:54.080
[Guest]: is going to be, it's just in the nature of these things, right?

03:04:54.080 --> 03:05:04.560
[Guest]: But what that does is that actually concentrates our mind back on why we were doing certain

03:05:04.560 --> 03:05:06.600
[Guest]: things that we were in fact doing.

03:05:06.600 --> 03:05:10.280
[Guest]: And that one of the things that South Asia will need, I mean, I actually do strongly

03:05:10.280 --> 03:05:14.400
[Guest]: believe, frankly, that India and Pakistan's trajectories are very closely entwined.

03:05:14.400 --> 03:05:19.160
[Guest]: I think we underestimate the degree, I mean, yes, they're diverging, India has done partly

03:05:19.160 --> 03:05:23.720
[Guest]: better, but not as much as we like to think.

03:05:23.720 --> 03:05:30.080
[Guest]: That we still haven't come to terms with, in a sense, the legacy of 1947.

03:05:30.080 --> 03:05:34.120
[Guest]: And that's a legacy that distorts both our domestic politics.

03:05:34.120 --> 03:05:37.560
[Guest]: In Pakistan, that's the impetus of creating a particular relationship between the military

03:05:37.560 --> 03:05:38.920
[Guest]: and Islam.

03:05:38.920 --> 03:05:41.120
[Guest]: And here now we are kind of using it.

03:05:41.120 --> 03:05:50.080
[Guest]: So the optimistic scenario is that, look, you know, we go back and rethink, right, 1947

03:05:50.080 --> 03:05:54.120
[Guest]: and say, I mean, I don't mean we become one country, but that's not going to happen.

03:05:54.120 --> 03:06:00.280
[Guest]: But we say that, look, the fundamental premise by which we defined our identity post-1947,

03:06:00.280 --> 03:06:07.840
[Guest]: unexplicitly, India in a fuzzy, modus vivendi way, is no longer, in a sense, sustainable.

03:06:07.840 --> 03:06:11.840
[Guest]: And it's running up against a second fact, which is important, and I think going to be

03:06:11.840 --> 03:06:21.400
[Guest]: very significant on the optimistic side, is that while intra-religious conflict, or rather

03:06:21.400 --> 03:06:27.120
[Guest]: inter-religious conflict has occupied our attention, actually the fault lines on freedom

03:06:27.120 --> 03:06:31.960
[Guest]: and oppression are within each of our communities, right?

03:06:31.960 --> 03:06:36.520
[Guest]: The fact of the matter is young men and women in both communities are looking for different

03:06:36.520 --> 03:06:41.480
[Guest]: kinds of liberation, sometimes pathologically, right?

03:06:41.480 --> 03:06:47.120
[Guest]: That sociological dynamic is also going to research itself at some point, right?

03:06:47.120 --> 03:06:51.360
[Guest]: And the advantage of that dynamic is that it actually gives people in different communities

03:06:51.360 --> 03:06:57.400
[Guest]: a similar language to talk about, right, that we are actually all kind of oppressed by some

03:06:57.400 --> 03:07:00.280
[Guest]: of the traditional structures we inherited.

03:07:00.280 --> 03:07:04.560
[Guest]: So maybe what has happened is that that deep freeze in which we had put this conversation

03:07:04.560 --> 03:07:10.040
[Guest]: in 1947 is actually finally bubbling up in a pathological way.

03:07:10.040 --> 03:07:15.400
[Guest]: There will be some conflict, it will work itself out, and we will actually realize that

03:07:15.400 --> 03:07:21.160
[Guest]: the subcontinent needs to be the zone of shared freedom that you and I want it to be.

03:07:21.160 --> 03:07:24.960
[Guest]: That's the only rational way of resolving these conflicts.

